jumper wire from the digital input pin and that bikes corresponding jack. The jumper should be attached adjacent to each corresponding pin on the Arduino and the third pin from the left on EACH input jack. The other signals including power supply and ground are already routed via the board. \'\'If you can see a trace on the board that already makes this connection, this rework is unnecessary.\'\' \n\n[[Image:Rework.jpg|250px|thumb|left|jumper wire attached for bikes 1&2]]','utf-8'),(44,'*[[Electronics parts list]]\n\n*[[V2 Sensor board rework]]\n\n*[[Software/hardware solutions]]\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n<big>\'\'\'MediaWiki has been successfully installed.\'\'\'</big>\n\nConsult the [http://meta.wikimedia.org/wiki/Help:Contents User\'s Guide] for information on using the wiki software.\n\n== Getting started ==\n\n* [http://www.mediawiki.org/wiki/Manual:Configuration_settings Configuration settings list]\n* [http://www.mediawiki.org/wiki/Manual:FAQ MediaWiki FAQ]\n* [http://lists.wikimedia.org/mailman/listinfo/mediawiki-announce MediaWiki release mailing list]','utf-8'),(45,'Currently the software only runs on a Linux system. If you are unfamiliar with the system this can seem a bit daunting, however there are a few tips and ideas for getting the system up and running as quick as possible.\n\n\n If you don\'t have a machine that currently has this or any Linux operating system on it currently, I suggest running the setup from an attached USB thumbdrive with both the a Linux operating system as well as the other software requirements for Opensprints. One popular and straightforward operating system for Linux is [http://www.ubuntu.com UBUNTU]. The entire Ubuntu operating system as well as the other software packages can be stored on a single 2GB thumb drive and be moved to any machine with little changes. If your laptop currently has a windows operating system, it will remain intact and the whole setup becomes very portable.','utf-8'),(46,'Currently the software only runs on a Linux system. If you are unfamiliar with the system this can seem a bit daunting, however there are a few tips and ideas for getting the system up and running as quick as possible.\n\n----\n\n== Linux as an operating system ==\n\nIf you don\'t have a machine that currently has this or any Linux operating system on it currently, I suggest running the setup from an attached USB thumbdrive with both the a Linux operating system as well as the other software requirements for Opensprints. One popular and straightforward operating system for Linux is [http://www.ubuntu.com UBUNTU]. The entire Ubuntu operating system as well as the other software packages can be stored on a single 2GB thumb drive and be moved to any machine with little changes. If your laptop currently has a windows operating system, it will remain intact and the whole setup becomes very portable.\n\n*obtain a thumb drive (2GB min)\n*upload [http://Ubuntu.com Ubuntu]as an operating system\n*upload [http://shoooes.net/ Shoes]for Linux\n*upload the latest Opensprints software (unpack this to your desktop)\n*upload the [http://arduino.cc Arduino] operating panel\n*upload the programming language [http://http://www.ruby-lang.org/en/ Ruby]','utf-8'),(47,'Version2 (V2) of the opensprints PCB,(first run only) requires a small modification for operation with the piggyback board and ethernet jacks.The current hexcode uploaded to the Arduino calls for two separate inputs from the sensor and this board only supplies one. Each bike attached will require a jumper wire from the digital input pin and that bikes corresponding jack. The jumper should be attached adjacent to each corresponding pin on the Arduino and the third pin from the left on EACH input jack. The other signals including power supply and ground are already routed via the board. \'\'If you can see a trace on the board that already makes this connection, this rework is unnecessary.\'\' \n\n[[Image:Rework.jpg|250px|thumb|left|jumper wire attached for bikes 1&2]]','utf-8'),(48,'Currently the software only runs on a Linux system. If you are unfamiliar with the system this can seem a bit daunting, however there are a few tips and ideas for getting the system up and running as quick as possible.\n\n----\n\n== Linux as an operating system ==\n\nIf you don\'t have a machine that currently has this or any Linux operating system on it,running the setup from an attached USB thumbdrive with both the a Linux operating system as well as the other software requirements for Opensprints is another option. One popular and straightforward operating system for Linux is [http://www.ubuntu.com UBUNTU]. The entire Ubuntu operating system as well as the other software packages can be stored on a single 2GB thumb drive and be moved to any machine with little if any changes. If your laptop currently has a windows operating system, it will remain intact and the whole setup becomes very portable and non-intrusive.\n\n\n== Creating a bootdisk from an USB thumbdrive ==\n\n*obtain a thumb drive (2GB min)\n*upload [http://Ubuntu.com Ubuntu]as an operating system\n\nGetting a machine to boot from the USB location will differ on the machine and what version of operating system you are currently utilizing. On start there could be a screen that asks you to press an F key to change the boot order or bios. Press this key (many will be the F12 Key). Once the boot list has been located, change the order for the boot from the current hard drive C: to the USB thumb drive with the Ubuntu software installed on it. Once the bios has been changed the next start of the machine should use the USB drive as the first boot and bring up the Ubuntu operating system. Once you are operating in the Ubuntu system, download the following software packages to your new desktop:\n\n*download [http://shoooes.net/ Shoes]for Linux\n*download the latest Opensprints software (unpack this to your desktop once using Ubuntu)\n*download the [http://arduino.cc Arduino] operating pa