uld use the USB drive as the first boot and bring up the Ubuntu operating system. Select: Perpetually store changes to USB drive as the style of system you would like to run. Once you are operating in the Ubuntu system, download the following software packages to your new desktop:\n\n*download [http://shoooes.net/ Shoes]for Linux\n*download the latest Opensprints software (unpack this to your desktop once using Ubuntu)\n*download the [http://arduino.cc Arduino] operating panel\n*download the programming language [http://http://www.ruby-lang.org/en/ Ruby]\n\n*Shoes is a very straightforward install using its own installer and can be installed first.\n*The arduino panel also has its own unpacker and can be installed next. The panel will be used to upload the latest Opensprints hex codes to the Arduino microcontroller.\n*Those familiar with Linux will already know that many Linux software packages like Ruby can be uploaded through the install system included with Ubuntu. In this case the Ruby install will take care of most of the software needed, the required libraries will need to be uploaded in addition to the basic install.','utf-8'),(54,'Version2 (V2) of the opensprints PCB,(first run only) requires a small modification for operation with the piggyback board and ethernet jacks.The current code uploaded to the Arduino calls for two separate inputs from the sensor and this board only supplies one. Each bike attached will require a jumper wire from the digital input pin and that bikes corresponding jack. The jumper should be attached adjacent to each corresponding pin on the Arduino and the third pin from the left on EACH input jack. The other signals including power supply and ground are already routed via the board. \'\'If you can see a trace on the board that already makes this connection, this rework is unnecessary.\'\' \n\n[[Image:Rework.jpg|250px|thumb|left|jumper wire attached for bikes 1&2]]','utf-8'),(55,'*[[Electronics parts list]]\n\n*[[V2 Sensor board rework]]\n\n*[[Software/hardware solutions]]\n\n*[[Sensor board assembly]]\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n<big>\'\'\'MediaWiki has been successfully installed.\'\'\'</big>\n\nConsult the [http://meta.wikimedia.org/wiki/Help:Contents User\'s Guide] for information on using the wiki software.\n\n== Getting started ==\n\n* [http://www.mediawiki.org/wiki/Manual:Configuration_settings Configuration settings list]\n* [http://www.mediawiki.org/wiki/Manual:FAQ MediaWiki FAQ]\n* [http://lists.wikimedia.org/mailman/listinfo/mediawiki-announce MediaWiki release mailing list]','utf-8'),(56,'If you have a set of Opensprints v2 sensor boards, these are the instructions for assembling the components on that board. A list of all the required solid state components can be found in the Electronics requirements page.','utf-8'),(57,'If you have a set of Opensprints v2 sensor boards, these are the instructions for assembling the components on that board. A list of all the required solid state components can be found in the [[Electronics parts list]] page. \n\n\n== Tools required: ==\n*Soldering iron with small(micro) tip\n*electronic solder, the smaller the better\n*Small pair of dykes or cut off pliers\n*Soldering vise or clamp. This is to hold the work off the table\n\nTips/notes\n\n*Each bike will require a seperate board.\n*Take note of the polarity of each component installed as LED\'s will only operate with the polarity correct. \n*Use caution when handling the hall effect sensors as they are sensitive to static electricity. Note that each hall sensor has a beveled side (usually printed on as well) this is the \"UP\" side if you will and should be soldered in to face the magnet as it passes by. The beveled edge and printing should be facing UP when completed.\n*Consider using different colored LED\'s for the \"tick\" display for each board.','utf-8'),(58,'*[[Electronics parts list]]\n\n*[[V2 Sensor board rework]]\n\n*[[Software/hardware solutions]]\n\n*[[Sensor board assembly]]\n\n*[[Arduino piggyback board]]\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n<big>\'\'\'MediaWiki has been successfully installed.\'\'\'</big>\n\nConsult the [http://meta.wikimedia.org/wiki/Help:Contents User\'s Guide] for information on using the wiki software.\n\n== Getting started ==\n\n* [http://www.mediawiki.org/wiki/Manual:Configuration_settings Configuration settings list]\n* [http://www.mediawiki.org/wiki/Manual:FAQ MediaWiki FAQ]\n* [http://lists.wikimedia.org/mailman/listinfo/mediawiki-announce MediaWiki release mailing list]','utf-8'),(59,'The piggy back board created for the Opensprints setup will allow the use of Ethernet cables between the sensors and the microcontroller. Its assembly requires the components listed in the Electronics parts page. \n\n\n== Tools required: ==\n*Soldering iron with small(micro) tip\n*electronic solder, the smaller the better\n*Small pair of dykes or cut off pliers\n*Soldering vise or clamp. This is to hold the work off the table','utf-8'),(60,'The piggy back board created for the Opensprints setup will allow the use of Ethernet cables between the sensors and the microcontroller. Its assembly requires the components listed in the [[Electronics parts list]] page. \n\n\n== Tools required: ==\n*Soldering iron with small(micro) tip\n*electronic solder, the smaller the better\n*Small pair of dykes or cut off pliers\n*Soldering vise or clamp. This is to hold the work off the table. \n\nTips/tricks\n\n*The breakoff headers are very sensitive to heat. When soldering in the pins, work fast or the plastic casing will melt around the pin causing it to lean or tilt. \n*Use the Arduino board to align the breakoff header rows onto the board, then tack a single pin per strip quickly. This will hold the strips in place firm enough for you to remove the Arduino and finish the remaining pins.','utf-8'),(61,'If you have a set of Opensprints v2 sensor boards, these are the instructions for assembling the components on that board. A list of all the required solid state components can be found in the [[Electronics parts list]] page. \n\n\n== Tools required: ==\n*Soldering iron with small(micro) tip\n*electronic solder, the smaller the better\n*Small pair of dykes or cut off pliers\n*Soldering vise or clamp. This is to hold the work off the table\n\nTips/notes\n\n*Each bike will require a seperate board.\n*Take note of the polarity of each component installed as LED\'s will only operate with the polarity correct. \n*Use caution when handling the hall effect sensors as they are sensitive to static electricity. Note that each hall sensor has a beveled side (usually printed on as well) this is the \"UP\" side if you will and should be soldered in to face the magnet as it passes by. The beveled edge and printing should be facing UP when completed.\n*Consider using different colored LED\'s for the \"tick\" display for each board.\n\n\n----\n*First determine the \"up\" side of the sensor board. This is the side of the board with the traces on it. when looking at the upside of the board it should appear like this. All the components will be fitted onto the UP side of the board and all the soldering will be done to the UNDER side.\n*Place the sensor board with the upside facing you and the circle trace up. \n*','utf-8'),(62,'The piggy back board created for the Opensprints setup will allow the use of Ethernet cables between the sensors and the microcontroller. Its assembly requires the components listed in the [[Electronics parts list]] page. \n\n\n== Tools required: ==\n*Soldering iron with small(micro) tip\n*electronic solder, the smaller the better\n*Small pair of dykes or cut off pliers\n*Soldering vise or clamp. This is to hold the work off the table. \n\nTips/tricks\n\n*The breakoff headers are very sensitive to heat. When soldering in the pins, work fast or the plastic casing will melt around the pin causing it to lean or tilt. \n*Use the Arduino board to align the breakoff header rows onto the board, then tack a single pin per strip quickly. This will hold the strips in place firm enough for you to remove the Arduino and finish the remaining pins.\n\n----\nStasrt by aligning the header rows (long pins inward) to the recepticles on the Arduino. You will find the headers can be broken by hand if done with care. Fill all four rows with the headers.\nNow align the boards upside with the pins. Ensure that all pins align before attempting to press the two together. The alignment will look like this:\n\nSeat the board by pressing the two together. the pins should protrude slightly from the other side (down side). Hold the board in your vise with the downside facing you and as close to parralled with the ground as possible. This will allow the solder to run down the pin when we start adding it. Its never a good idea to solder with the board attached. I suggest tacking one pin per bank to start with and then removing to board to finish. Touch a hot soldering iron to the top of one of the middle pins in any of the rows. immediatley Touch the solder to the point where the iron and the pin meet, it will melt immediately and puddle at the base of the pin. Most of the other soldering done on this project can be done by waiting for the pin to be hot enough to melt the solder. If you wait for the pin to be hot enough to melt the solder instead of using the irons tip, the pin will also melt the plastic header holding it in place and wilt. The pins are small enough they will require very little solder. Tack the middle pin on each row and then flip the board over. Firmly grasp the sides of the Arduino and pull it from the main board. The two should seperate leaving just the headers attached. Finish soldering in the remaining pins in the same manner. Work quickly and just touch the tip for a second before adding the solder to the connection.','utf-8'),(63,'The piggy back board created for the Opensprints setup will allow the use of Ethernet cables between the sensors and the microcontroller. Its assembly requires the components listed in the [[Electronics parts list]] page. \n\n\n== Tools required: ==\n*Soldering iron with small(micro) tip\n*electronic solder, the smaller the better\n*Small pair of dykes or cut off pliers\n*Soldering vise or clamp. This is to hold the work off the table. \n\nTips/tricks\n\n*The breakoff headers are very sensitive to heat. When soldering in the pins, work fast or the plastic casing will melt around the pin causing it to lean or tilt. \n*Use the Arduino board to align the breakoff header rows onto the board, then tack a single pin per strip quickly. This will hold the strips in place firm enough for you to remove the Arduino and finish the remaining pins.\n\n----\nStart by aligning the header rows (long pins inward) to the recepticles on the Arduino. You will find the headers can be broken by hand if done with care. Fill all four rows with the headers.\nNow align the boards upside with the pins. Ensure that all pins align before attempting to press the two together. The alignment will look like this:\n\nSeat the board by pressing the two together. the pins should protrude slightly from the other side (down side). Hold the board in your vise with the downside facing you and as close to parralled with the ground as possible. This will allow the solder to run down the pin when we start adding it. Its never a good idea to solder with the board attached. I suggest tacking one pin per bank to start with and then removing to board to finish. Touch a hot soldering iron to the top of one of the middle pins in any of the rows. immediatley Touch the solder to the point where the iron and the pin meet, it will melt immediately and puddle at the base of the pin. Most of the other soldering done on this project can be done by waiting for the pin to be hot enough to melt the solder. If you wait for the pin to be hot enough to melt the solder instead of using the irons tip, the pin will also melt the plastic header holding it in place and wilt. The pins are small enough they will require very little solder. Tack the middle pin on each row and then flip the board over. Firmly grasp the sides of the Arduino and pull it from the main board. The two should seperate leaving just the headers attached. Finish soldering in the remaining pins in the same manner. Work quickly and just touch the tip for a second before adding the solder to the connection.','utf-8'),(64,'','utf-8'),(65,'If you have a set of Opensprints v2 sensor boards, these are the instructions for assembling the components on that board. A list of all the required solid state components can be found in the [[Electronics parts list]] page. \n\n\n== Tools required: ==\n*Soldering iron with small(micro) tip\n*electronic solder, the smaller the better\n*Small pair of dykes or cut off pliers\n*Soldering vise or clamp. This is to hold the work off the table\n\nTips/notes\n\n*Each bike will require a seperate board.\n*Take note of the polarity of each component installed as LED\'s will only operate with the polarity correct. \n*Use caution when handling the hall effect sensors as they are sensitive to static electricity. Note that each hall sensor has a beveled side (usually printed on as well) this is the \"UP\" side if you will and should be soldered in to face the magnet as it passes by. The beveled edge and printing should be facing UP when completed.\n*Consider using different colored LED\'s for the \"tick\" display for each board.\n\n\n----\n*First determine the \"up\" side of the sensor board. This is the side of the board with the traces on it. when looking at the upside of the board it should appear like this.\n{|\n|-\n| \n[[Image:Sensor_board.jpg|200px|left|thumb|Sensor board UP side]]\n|-\n|}\n*All the components will be fitted onto the UP side of the board and all the soldering will be done to the UNDER side.\n*Place the sensor board with the upside facing you and the circular trace up.','utf-8'),(66,'','utf-8'),(67,'If you have a set of Opensprints v2 sensor boards, these are th