GitHub repository.  See the [[Source Code]] page for more info.','utf-8'),(87,'The PCB CAD development files are found in the main OpenSprints GitHub repository.  See the [[Source Code]] page for more info.','utf-8'),(88,'The PCB CAD development files are found in the main OpenSprints GitHub repository.  See the [[Source Code]] page for more info.\n==Firmware Versions==\n===Basic Messaging===\nTBD.\n===Advanced Messaging===\n* The packets are in the structure !TIME@DATA#\n* TIME is an string representing 32-bit millis().\n* DATA is a block of characters encoding one HEX nibble per byte, to which we\'ve added 128 to remain string-friendly.\n* The first data byte corresponds to the tick status at TIME The second to TIME + RACE_FRAME_LENGTH (typically 2ms here).\n* Subsequent correspond to TIME + x, where x is the index of the byte in the data section.\n* Each HEX nibble represents the tick status of each sensor during the 1-2ms period to which it corresponds.','utf-8'),(89,'== Tools required ==\n*soldering iron with fine point\n*electronic solder, the finer gauge the better\n*pair of small angle cutters\n*Soldering vise or clamp. This is to hold the work off the table.\n== Soldering breakaway headers ==\n*The breakaway headers are very sensitive to heat. When soldering in the pins, work fast or the plastic casing will melt around the pin causing it to lean or tilt.\n* Hold the board in your vise with the downside facing you and as close to parallel with the ground as possible. This will allow the solder to run down the pin when we start adding it. \n* It is never a good idea to solder with the board attached. I suggest tacking one pin per bank to start with and then removing to board to finish. Touch a hot soldering iron to the top of one of the middle pins in any of the rows. Immediately touch the solder to the point where the iron and the pin meet, it will melt immediately and puddle at the base of the pin. Most of the other soldering done on this project can be done by waiting for the pin to be hot enough to melt the solder. If you wait for the pin to be hot enough to melt the solder instead of using the irons tip, the pin will also melt the plastic header holding it in place and wilt. The pins are small enough they will require very little solder. Tack the middle pin on each row and then flip the board over. Firmly grasp the sides of the Arduino and pull it from the main board. The two should seperate leaving just the headers attached. Finish soldering in the remaining pins in the same manner. Work quickly and just touch the tip for a second before adding the solder to the connection.','utf-8'),(90,'The OpenSprints system consists of the following subsystems:\n* A USB interface and sensors for monitoring roller rotations\n* A PC providing the race display (optional)\n==User Documentation==\n* [[Hardware Installation]]\n* [[Software Installation]]\n* [[Event Setup]]\n==Dev Resources==\n* [[Source Code]] - including PC application, sensor interface firmware, and electronics CAD files.\n* [[Hardware Development]]\n* [[Feature Requests]]\n* [[Video Interface Development]]\n* [[Bugs]]','utf-8'),(91,'\'\'\'In order of priority:\'\'\'\n# Windows support, we should be able to read off of a CDC device without blocking the whole thread\n# Killing off the buffer overrun. This could be solved a number of ways, please voice your opinions\n## moving game logic into the UBW, asking it occasionally for statistics in summary format.\n## a second buffer to read info off of the ubw quickly in a dedicated thread, possibly listening to interrupts  \n# Increase tick granularity, real races can have rpms higher than a centisecond.  \'\'What is the range of actual values observed for roller speed in rotations/second?\'\'\n# Rearchitect race data structure to keep a complete record of the race -- all times at which a bike sent a tick.  This will be used to support secondary calculations like power, and will provide easier access for graphing the data in more flexible ways.\n# Integrate new FW packet format into Ruby data collection setup -- start using a complete race representation rather than just \"distance accumulated\"','utf-8'),(92,'== Steps for assembling the electronic equipment ==\nFirst, acquire the items in the [[Electronics parts list]]. The [[Soldering tips]] page can be a good reference for beginners.\n=== Assembling the interface board ===\nThe USB interface board is basically an Arduino piggyback board that provides a safe and convenient interconnect for the sensors. Ethernet cables are used to connect the sensors to the Arduino.\n==== Notes ====\n*The breakaway headers are very sensitive to heat. When soldering in the pins, work fast or the plastic casing will melt around the pin causing it to lean or tilt.\n*The top of the interface/piggyback board is the side that has text.\n==== Assembly ====\n# Break the male breakaway headers into two 6-position strips and two 8-position strips.\n# Use the Arduino board to align the breakaway header on the piggyback board. Connect the male header pins\' longer sides to the female pins on the Arduino. With the top of the piggyback board facing the top of the Arduino, the Arduino into the piggyback board so that the shorter sides of the male pins enter the corresponding holes on the piggyback board. Ensure that all pins align before attempting to press the two together. The alignment will look like this: [Image coming soon] Then tack the end pins on each strip quickly. This will hold the strips in place firm enough for you to remove the Arduino and finish soldering the remaining pins.\n#Seat the Arduino on the interface board. the pins should protrude slightly from the other side (down side). \n===Assembling the sensors===\n\n*[[V2 Sensor board rework]]\n\n*[[Software/hardware solutions]]\n\n*[[Sensor board assembly]]','utf-8'),(93,'#REDIRECT [[Software Installation]]','utf-8'),(94,'== Essentials ==\n\n* Two to four Complete Bicycles, minus the front wheel\n* Two to four [[Rollers]]\n* Two to four [[Fork Mounts]], preferably mounted securely to a large base surface\n* Laptop/computer with a USB port, and setup as described in [[Software Installation]]\n* Digital Projector \'\'or\'\' lots of TVs\n* A big room, a table a chair and a projection surface\n\n== Nice to have parts ==\n\n* A stage or 1 ft high platform\n* Red and Blue electrical tape\n* Red and Blue handlebar tape\n* Red and Blue heat shrink tubing for cabling\n* Two to four 5x3 plywood boards and big 15mm bolts and angle brackets (for anchoring the fork mounts)\n* loooooong projector cable\n* differently sized seatposts, spare crankset, tubes\n* pump w/ gauge\n* gaffers tape for cords\n* [[Wheel Visualizations]]\n\n== Setting up ==\n\n* clearly indicate each bike red and blue\n* pump up the tires equally\n* put rollers on each side of the projection area, perpindicular to it\n* place fork mounts and bikes over rollers\n* set up laptop on table in view of the bikers\n\n== Race formats ==\n\n* [http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Template:16TeamBracket Complete Elimination]\n* Qualification Style: All riders race once, then race the top 8 in single elimination brackets.\n* Grudge Matches: charge per race, riders chose their opponents\n* Top Distance: racers ride for 20 seconds, highest distance wins.\n* Top Speed: ride for any ammount of time, highest speed wins.\n\n== Using a projector ==\n\nSince the racers are usually facing the crowd, they can\'t see the projected display behind them.  As you might expect, a common racer request is to have monitors in front of them.  With their forehead buried in their stem, LCD screens (heavily covered in a protective Plexiglas box) might work well in between the front and rear rollers.\n\nSending the same image to multiple screens is called \'\'\'mirroring\'\'\'  This can be done with a \'\'\'VGA splitter\'\'\'.  Here are some vendors: [http://www.kvms.com/ KVMs], [http://www.networktechinc.com/ NTI], [http://www.national-tech.com/ National Technology].  Simply do a search for \'vga splitter\' to find more vendors.\n\nTo share the screen with the digital projector in linux use this command:\n\n > xrandr --auto\n\n== References ==\n\n* [http://www.realtimesoft.com/multimon/faq.asp#Mirroring Multi-Monitor FAQ]','utf-8'),(95,'== Essentials ==\n\n* Two to four Complete Bicycles, minus the front wheel\n* Two to four [[Rollers]]\n* Two to four [[Fork Mounts]], preferably mounted securely to a large base surface\n* Laptop/computer with a USB port, and setup as described in [[Software Installation]]\n* Digital Projector \'\'or\'\' lots of TVs\n* A big room, a table a chair and a projection surface\n\n== Nice to have parts ==\n\n* A stage or 1 ft high platform\n* Red and Blue electrical tape\n* Red and Blue handlebar tape\n* Red and Blue heat shrink tubing for cabling\n* Two to four 5x3 plywood boards and big 15mm bolts and angle brackets (for anchoring the fork mounts)\n* loooooong projector cable\n* differently sized seatposts, spare crankset, tubes\n* pump w/ gauge\n* gaffers tape for cords\n* [[Wheel Visualizations]]\n\n== Setting up ==\n\n* clearly indicate each bike red and blue\n* pump up the tires equally\n* put rollers on each side of the projection area, perpindicular to it\n* place fork mounts and bikes over rollers\n* set up laptop on table in view of the bikers\n\n== Race formats ==\n\n* [http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Template:16TeamBracket Complete Elimination]\n* Qualification Style: All riders race once, then race the top 8 in single elimination brackets.\n* Grudge Matches: charge per race, riders chose their opponents\n* Top Distance: racers ride for 20 seconds, highest distance wins.\n* Top Speed: ride for any amount of time, highest speed wins.\n\n== Using a projector ==\n\nSince the racers are usually facing the crowd, they can\'t see the projected display behind them.  As you might expect, a common racer request is to have monitors in front of them.  With their forehead buried in their stem, LCD screens (heavily covered in a protective Plexiglas box) might work well in between the front and rear rollers.\n\nSending the same image to multiple screens is called \'\'\'mirroring\'\'\'  This can be done with a \'\'\'VGA splitter\'\'\'.  Here are some vendors: [http://www.kvms.com/ KVMs], [http://www.networktechinc.com/ NTI], [http://www.national-tech.com/ National Technology].  Simply do a search for \'vga splitter\' to find more vendors.\n\nTo share the screen with the digital projector in Linux use this command:\n\n > xrandr --auto\n\n== References ==\n\n* [http://www.realtimesoft.com/multimon/faq.asp#Mirroring Multi-Monitor FAQ]','utf-8'),(96,'== Essentials ==\n\n* Two to four Complete Bicycles, minus the front wheel\n* Two to four [[Bicycle Rollers]]\n* Two to four [[Fork Mounts]], preferably mounted securely to a large base surface\n* Laptop/computer with a USB port, and setup as described in [[Software Installation]]\n* Digital Projector \'\'or\'\' lots of TVs\n* A big room, a table a chair and a projection surface\n\n== Nice to have parts ==\n\n* A stage or 1 ft high platform\n* Red and Blue electrical tape\n* Red and Blue handlebar tape\n* Red and Blue heat shrink tubing for cabling\n* Two to four 5x3 plywood boards and big 15mm bolts and angle brackets (for anchoring the fork mounts)\n* loooooong projector cable\n* differently sized seatposts, spare crankset, tubes\n* pump w/ gauge\n* gaffers tape for cords\n* [[Wheel Visualizations]]\n\n== Setting up ==\n\n* clearly indicate each bike red and blue\n* pump up the tires equally\n* put rollers on each side of the projection area, perpindicular to it\n* place fork mounts and bikes over rollers\n* set up laptop on table in view of the bikers\n\n== Race formats ==\n\n* [http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Template:16TeamBracket Complete Elimination]\n* Qualification Style: All riders race once, then race the top 8 in single elimination brackets.\n* Grudge Matches: charge per race, riders chose their opponents\n* Top Distance: racers ride for 20 seconds, highest distance wins.\n* Top Speed: ride for any amount of time, highest speed wins.\n\n== Using a projector ==\n\nSince the racers are usually facing the crowd, they can\'t see the projected display behind them.  As you might expect, a common racer request is to have monitors in front of them.  With their forehead buried in their stem, LCD screens (heavily covered in a protective Plexiglas box) might work well in between the front and rear rollers.\n\nSending the same image to multiple screens is called \'\'\'mirroring\'\'\'  This can be done with a \'\'\'VGA splitter\'\'\'.  Here are some vendors: [http://www.kvms.com/ KVMs], [http://www.networktechinc.com/ NTI], [http://www.national-tech.com/ National Technology].  Simply do a search for \'vga splitter\' to find more vendors.\n\nTo share the screen with the digital projector in Linux use this command:\n\n > xrandr --auto\n\n== References ==\n\n* [http://www.realtimesoft.com/multimon/faq.asp#Mirroring Multi-Monitor FAQ]','utf-8'),(97,'\'\'\'Bicycle rollers\'\'\' are a type of bicycle trainer which makes it possible to ride a bicycle indoors without moving forward. However, unlike other types of bicycle trainers, rollers do not attach to the bicycle frame, and the rider must balance him or herself on the rollers while training. Bicycle rollers normally consist of three cylinders, drums, or \"rollers\" (two for the rear wheel and one for the front), on top of which the bicycle rides. A belt connects one of the rear rollers to the front roller, causing the front wheel of the bicycle to spin when the bicycle is pedaled. The spacing of bicycle rollers can usually be adjusted to match the bicycle\'s wheelbase. Generally, the front roller is adjusted to be slightly ahead of the hub of the front wheel.\n\nBecause most people don\'t know how to balance on rollers, especially when drunk, using [[fork stands]] is recommended for [[OpenSprints]].\n\n== Manufacturers ==\n\n* [http://www.nashbar.com Nashbar]\n* [http://www.kreitler.com/ Kreitler]\n* Elite Parabolic Rollers\n* [http://www.tacx.com/ Tacx]\n* [http://www.cycle-ops.com/ Saris]\n* [http://www.minoura.co.jp/trainer-e2.html Minoura]\n* [http://www.sportcrafters.com/ SportCrafters]\n* [http://www.trutrainer.com/ TruTrainer]\n* [http://www.zzzing.com/ ZZZing]\n* [http://mclaincycle.com/ McLain Cycle]\n\n===Measurements===\n{|  class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\"\n|-\n! Vendor\n! Frame height\n! Frame width\n! Distance distance from inside edge of frame to channel in roller*\n|-\n| [http://www.sportcrafters.com/ SportCrafters]\n| 1.0 in.\n| 1.0 in.\n| 0.50 in.\n|-\n| [http://www.trutrainer.com/ TruTrainer]\n| 2.0 in.\n| 1.0 in.\n| Pending answer to request for information from vendor\n|-\n| [http://www.kreitler.com/ Kreitler]\n| 0.75 in.\n| 0.75 in.\n| Pending measurement\n|-\n| [http://www.nashbar.com Nashbar]\n| Pending measurement\n| Pending measurement\n| Pending measurement\n|}\n\n<nowiki>*</nowiki> The channel is at the end of the roller, and the tension band runs through it. We mount the magnet for the revolution sensor in the channel.\n\n== References ==\n\n* [http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bicycle_rollers Wikipedia\'s Bicycle Rollers]','utf-8'),(98,'\'\'\'Fork Mounts\'\'\' are generally used to give stability to riders that haven\'t mastered riding on rollers with both wheels (or riders that have had a couple of drinks).  When a fork mount is used with rollers the majority of torque that the rider is displacing on the handlebars is translated into the fork mount.  The primary implication of this transmitting of power is that you will want the fork mount to be very sturdy and mounted firmly to ground (Note that some of the ones below mount to the rollers and not the ground).\n\nThere are many ways to stabilize the fork mounts.  Ideally you want something between very secure (bolting directly to the floor) and easy move (sand bags).  Using a large sheet of wood on which the rollers will sit and mounting the fork mount to it seems to work well.  Some have had success with angle brackets and bolts through the fork mounts.  Below you can see a picture of an alternative to bolts and drilling out the fork mounts.  The galvanized steel strap shown (in the link) is simply screwed to the piece of 1/2 inch thick MDF cut to 3\' by 6\'.\n\n[http://farm3.static.flickr.com/2400/2278736026_8599dec7cb_o.jpg example of galv straps] (WIKI ADMIN, feel free to upload this pic.)\n\n== Manufacturers ==\n[http://www.kreitler.com/product.php?section=product&item=accessories Kreitler]\n\n[http://www.minoura.jp/index-et.html Minoura]\n\n[http://www.cycle-ops.com/c-5-accessories.aspx Cycle-ops]','utf-8'),(99,'galv strap','utf-8'),(100,'','utf-8'),(101,'','utf-8'),(102,'Two or more rear are sitting in the same spot at a fast RPM, to not doing anything with that would be a wasted opportunity.\n\n== Light Patterns ==\n\nRegardless of which one you go with, you will need 3 per wheel to get the full effect.\n\n=== [http://www.hokeyspokes.com/ Hokey Spokes] ===\n\n[[Image:hokeyspokes.gif|thumb|Hokey Spokes]]\n\nHokey Spokes are a pre-assembled commercial product.  With the centripetal force you will need to use \'\'\'extra springs\'\'\' to keep the batteries in place.\n\n\'\'\'Pros:\'\'\'\n\n* Beer and Waterproof\n* No Magnets\n* Patterns automatically sync on the same wheel.\n* Turning one on/off automatically does the same with any other ones on a wheel.\n\n\'\'\'Cons:\'\'\'\n* Non-programmable.\n* Text un-readable at high RPM.\n\n=== [http://www.ladyada.net/make/spokepov/ SpokePOV] ===\n\n[[Image:spokepov.gif|thumb|SpokePOV]]\n\nSpokePOV is a do-it-yourself soldering kit.\n\n\'\'\'Pros:\'\'\'\n\n* Programmable\n\n\'\'\'Cons:\'\'\'\n\n* Not Waterproof\n* Requires setting magnets\n* You need to program all three individually.\n* You need to turn one on/off all three individually.','utf-8'),(103,'\'\'\'Fork Mounts\'\'\' are generally used to give stability to riders that haven\'t mastered riding on rollers with both wheels (or riders that have had a couple of drinks).  When a fork mount is used with rollers the majority of torque that the rider is displacing on the handlebars is translated into the fork mount.  The primary implication of this transmitting of power is that you will want the fork mount to be very sturdy and mounted firmly to ground (Note that some of the ones below mount to the rollers and not the ground).\n\nThere are many ways to stabilize the fork mounts.  Ideally you want something between very secure (bolting directly to the floor) and easy move (sand bags).  Using a large sheet of wood on which the rollers will sit and mounting the fork mount to it seems to work well.  Some have had success with angle brackets and bolts through the fork mounts.  Below you can see a picture of an alternative to bolts and drilling out the fork mounts.  The galvanized steel strap shown (in the link) is simply screwed to the piece of 1/2 inch thick MDF cut to 3\' by 6\'.\n[[Image:Galv_Strap.gif|thumb|example of galv straps]]\n\n== Manufacturers ==\n[http://www.kreitler.com/product.php?section=product&item=accessories Kreitler]\n\n[http://www.minoura.jp/index-et.html Minoura]\n\n[http://www.cycle-ops.com/c-5-accessories.aspx Cycle-ops]','utf-8'),(104,'\'\'\'Fork Mounts\'\'\' are generally used to give stability to riders that haven\'t mastered riding on rollers with both wheels (or riders that have had a couple of drinks).  When a fork mount is used with rollers the majority of torque that the rider is displacing on the handlebars is translated into the fork mount.  The primary implication of this transmitting of power is that you will want the fork mount to be very sturdy and mounted firmly to ground (Note that some of the ones below mount to the rollers and not the ground).\n\nThere are many ways to stabilize the fork mounts.  Ideally you want something between very secure (bolting directly to the floor) and easy move (sand bags).  Using a large sheet of wood on which the rollers will sit and mounting the fork mount to it seems to work well.  Some have had success with angle brackets and bolts through the fork mounts.  Below you can see a picture of an alternative to bolts and drilling out the fork mounts.  The galvanized steel strap shown (in the link) is simply screwed to the piece of 1/2 inch thick MDF cut to 3\' by 6\'.\n[[Image:Galv_Strap.jpg|thumb|example of galv straps]]\n\n== Manufacturers ==\n[http://www.kreitler.com/product.php?section=product&item=accessories Kreitler]\n\n[http://www.minoura.jp/index-et.html Minoura]\n\n[http://www.cycle-ops.com/c-5-accessories.aspx Cycle-ops]','utf-8'),(105,'the source repository is on github:\nhttp://github.com/evanfarrar/opensprints/tree/master\n\n# You can open a free github account.\n# In your github account, make a personal fork of the repository at http://github.com/evanfarrar/opensprints/tree/master\n# Make some improvements, and push your changes to your github repository. Then request that your changes be pulled by evanfarrar.\n# In order to develop under Windows, it is necessary to install git. The version available through cygwin works well. see http://git.or.cz/gitwiki/CygwinBinaryInstall\n== See Also ==\n\n* [[Git Gotchas]]\n* [[Development]]\n* http://git.or.cz/','utf-8'),(106,'==Trailing whitespace==\nLuckily, all the development for the OpenSprints system can be done under Linux. Prior to the switchover from UBW to Arduino, using MPLAB in Windows to develop for the UBW caused headaches with git. In our case, trailing whitespace is introduced in some of the output files that are generated by the MPLAB C18 build process. Git throws an error whenever a file being committed has trailing whitespace. Removing the trailing whitespace would be the optimal solution. However, saving time can be more important than file size in the repository, and a solution like this hack might be in order:\n\nin .git/hooks/pre-commit, comment the following lines:\n\n #	    if (/\\s$/) {\n #		bad_line(\"trailing whitespace\", $_);\n #	    }\n #	    if (/^\\s* \\t/) {\n #		bad_line(\"indent SP followed by a TAB\", $_);\n #	    }\n==Commands==\nWhen working on a development branch apart from the master branch, these commands seem to get the job done.\n*Clone:\n git clone git@github.com:lukeorland/opensprints.git /home/orluke/workspace/opensprints\n*Checkout the remote nopc branch into the new local branch called nopc:\n git checkout origin/nopc -b nopc\n*Push changes:\n git push\n*Do not use the following command. It does not update the remote repo\n git push origin origin/nopcNEW','utf-8'),(107,'==Trailing whitespace==\nLuckily, all the development for the OpenSprints system can be done under Linux. Prior to the switchover from UBW to Arduino, using MPLAB in Windows to develop for the UBW caused headaches with git. In our case, trailing whitespace is introduced in some of the output files that are generated by the MPLAB C18 build process. Git throws an error whenever a file being committed has trailing whitespace. Removing the trailing whitespace would be the optimal solution. However, saving time can be more important than file size in the repository, and a solution like this hack might be in order:\n\nin .git/hooks/pre-commit, comment the following lines:\n\n #	    if (/\\s$/) {\n #		bad_line(\"trailing whitespace\", $_);\n #	    }\n #	    if (/^\\s* \\t/) {\n #		bad_line(\"indent SP followed by a TAB\", $_);\n #	    }\n== Commands ==\nWhen working on a development branch apart from the master branch, these commands seem to get the job done.\n=== Clone: ===\n git clone git@github.com:lukeorland/opensprints.git /home/orluke/workspace/opensprints\n=== Checkout the remote nopc branch into the new local branch called nopc: ===\n git checkout origin/nopc -b nopc\n=== Push changes: ===\n==== commit local changes ====\n git commit\n==== pull from the origin to get up-to-date. ====\n git pull\n==== push local commit to the origin ====\n git push\n=== Do not use the following command. It does not update the remote repo.===\n git push origin origin/nopcNEW','utf-8'),(108,'== Steps for assembling the electronic equipment ==\nFirst, acquire the items in the [[Electronics parts list]]. The [[Soldering tips]] page can be a good reference for beginners.\n=== Assembling the USB interface board ===\n\nThe USB interface board is basically an Arduino piggyback board that provides a safe and convenient interconnect for the sensors. Ethernet cables are used to connect the sensors to the Arduino.\n\n==== Notes ====\n\n*The breakaway headers are very sensitive to heat. When soldering in the pins, work fast or the plastic casing will melt around the pin causing it to lean or tilt.\n*The top of the interface/piggyback board is the side that has text.\n\n==== Assembly ====\n\n# Break the male breakaway headers into two 6-position strips and two 8-position strips.\n# Use the Arduino board to align the breakaway header on the piggyback board. Connect the male header pins\' longer sides to the female pins on the Arduino. With the top of the piggyback board facing the top of the Arduino, the Arduino into the piggyback board so that the shorter sides of the male pins enter the corresponding holes on the piggyback board. Ensure that all pins align before attempting to press the two together. The alignment will look like this: [Image coming soon] Then tack the end pins on each strip quickly. This will hold the strips in place firm enough for you to remove the Arduino and finish soldering the remaining pins.\n#Seat the Arduino on the interface board.\n\n===Assembling the sensors===\n\n*[[V2 Sensor board rework]]\n\n*[[Software/hardware solutions]]\n\n*[[Sensor board assembly]]','utf-8'),(109,'== Steps for assembling the electronic equipment ==\nFirst, acquire the items in the [[Electronics parts list]]. The [[Soldering tips]] page can be a good reference for beginners.\n=== Assembling the USB interface board ===\n\nThe USB interface board is basically an Arduino piggyback board that provides a safe and convenient interconnect for the sensors. Ethernet cables are used to connect the sensors to the Arduino.\n\n==== Notes ====\n\n*The breakaway headers are very sensitive to heat. When soldering in the pins, work fast or the plastic casing will melt around the pin causing it to lean or tilt.\n*The top of the interface/piggyback board is the side that has text.\n\n==== Assembly ====\n\n# Break the male breakaway headers into two 6-position strips and two 8-position strips.\n# Use the Arduino board to align the breakaway header on the piggyback board. Connect the male header pins\' longer sides to the female pins on the Arduino. With the top of the piggyback board facing the top of the Arduino, press the Arduino into the piggyback board so that the shorter sides of the male pins enter the corresponding holes on the piggyback board. Ensure that all pins align before attempting to press the two together. The alignment will look like this: [Image coming soon] Then tack the end pins on each strip quickly. This will hold the strips in place firm enough for you to remove the Arduino and finish soldering the remaining pins.\n# Seat the Arduino on the interface board.\n# Solder RJ45 jacks to the piggyback board, one for each roller.\n# Affix the USB interface board to the bottom of the SERPAC C-6 project box with four machine screws.\n# (Optionally) cut the face plates of the project box to make openings for the USB jack and the RJ45 jack(s), and slide the face plates into place on the project box. Alternatively, omit this step.\n\n===Assembling the sensors===\n\n*[[V2 Sensor board rework]]\n\n*[[Software/hardware solutions]]\n\n*[[Sensor board assembly]]','utf-8'),(110,'TODO:\n* make the hardware parts list page prettier\n* sensor assembly\nDONE:\n* nothing','utf-8'),(111,'== Parts for Interface board version 2 ==\n\n{| {{table}} border=\"1\" \n| align=\"center\" style=\"backg