s routing the cathode, or shorter leg from the tick LED along the back to the VOUT pin labeled on the front. The route should look something like this:\n\n[[Image:Sensor2.JPG|200px|thumb|none|reroute on backside]]\n\n*The Hall sensor is installed across the top. Take care that the beveled edge (normally printed on) is facing the board and not away from it. \n*The capacitor is installed just in front of the sensor.\n\nHere is a picture of a finished board (save the RJ45 jack)\n\n[[Image:finishedfront.jpg|200px|thumb|none|finished front side]]\n\nand the backside with the wires trimmed. \'\'Note the rerouted wire\'\'.\n\n[[Image:finishedback.jpg|200px|thumb|none|Finished back]]\n\nNext, solder one or both of the RJ45 jacks to the board. If only one jack is being used, it can be soldered to either position, as the two jacks are wired in parallel.\n==== Mounting the sensor board in the enclosure ====\n* The sensor PCB is designed to fit well inside a SERPAC C-6 plastic enclosure, with slight modification to the enclosure. \n* The bottom half of the enclosure is the side that has the boss that the fastener screws into. On the bottom half of the enclosure, one of the shorter walls gets shaved off far enough that the locking legs of the RJ45 jacks are outside the enclosure. \n* The same wall is shaved off the top half of the enclosure so that the top of the RJ45 jack is exposed. NB: With the lower profile jacks from Digi-Key, it is likely that the RJ45 jack will fit under the top wall of the enclosure.\n* Surround the boss on the bottom half of the enclosure with hot melt glue\n* Seat the sensor board, component side up, down around the boss, with the glue locking the board in place.\n[[Image:Sensor_v2_open_1.jpg|400px|thumb|none]]\n[[Image:Sensor_v2_open_2.jpg|400px|thumb|none]]\n* Attach the top half of the sensor enclosure, and screw it down.','utf-8'),(127,'\'\'\'In order of priority:\'\'\'\n# Windows support, we should be able to read off of a CDC device without blocking the whole thread\n# Killing off the buffer overrun. This could be solved a number of ways, please voice your opinions\n## moving game logic into the UBW, asking it occasionally for statistics in summary format.\n## a second buffer to read info off of the ubw quickly in a dedicated thread, possibly listening to interrupts  \n# Increase tick granularity, real races can have rpms higher than a centisecond.  \'\'What is the range of actual values observed for roller speed in rotations/second?\'\'\n# Rearchitect race data structure to keep a complete record of the race -- all times at which a bike sent a tick.  This will be used to support secondary calculations like power, and will provide easier access for graphing the data in more flexible ways.\n# Integrate new FW packet format into Ruby data collection setup -- start using a complete race representation rather than just \"distance accumulated\"\n\nTest entry by DH suport','utf-8'),(128,'\'\'\'In order of priority:\'\'\'\n# Windows support, we should be able to read off of a CDC device without blocking the whole thread\n# Killing off the buffer overrun. This could be solved a number of ways, please voice your opinions\n## moving game logic into the UBW, asking it occasionally for statistics in summary format.\n## a second buffer to read info off of the ubw quickly in a dedicated thread, possibly listening to interrupts  \n# Increase tick granularity, real races can have rpms higher than a centisecond.  \'\'What is the range of actual values observed for roller speed in rotations/second?\'\'\n# Rearchitect race data structure to keep a complete record of the race -- all times at which a bike sent a tick.  This will be used to support secondary calculations like power, and will provide easier access for graphing the data in more flexible ways.\n# Integrate new FW packet format into Ruby data collection setup -- start using a complete race representation rather than just \"distance accumulated\"\n\nTest entry by DH support','utf-8'),(129,'\'\'Currently the software only runs on a Linux system. If you are unfamiliar with the system this can seem a bit daunting, however there are a few tips and ideas for getting the system up and running as quick as possible.\'\'\n\n\n== Linux as an operating system ==\n\nIf you don\'t have a machine that currently has a Linux operating system on it, running the setup from an attached USB thumbdrive with both the Linux operating system as well as the other software requirements for Opensprints is another option. One popular and straightforward operating system for Linux is [http://www.ubuntu.com UBUNTU]. The entire Ubuntu operating system as well as the other software packages can be stored on a single 2GB thumb drive and be moved to any machine with little if any changes. If your laptop currently has a windows operating system, it will remain intact and the whole setup becomes very portable and non-intrusive.\n\n== Creating a bootable persistant Ubuntu 8.10 thumbdrive ==\n\nCredit for this method goes to [http://www.pendrivelinux.com/ubuntu-810-persistent-flash-drive-install-from-live-cd/ Pen Drive Linux].\n\nWith this method, you must use a 2GB or larger thumb drive.\n\n   1. Download the Ubuntu 8.10 ISO and burn it to a CD\n   2. Restart your computer, booting from the Live CD\n   3. Insert a 2GB or larger USB flash drive\n   4. Open a terminal and type the following into the terminal window:\n\n          wget pendrivelinux.com/downloads/u810/u810.sh\n\n          chmod +x u810.sh && sh u810.sh\n\n   5. Follow the onscreen instructions\n   6. Once the script has finished, reboot your computer and set your BIOS or boot menu to boot from the USB device\n\n\nGetting a machine BIOS to boot from the USB drive will differ from computer to computer, typically with in the first 5 seconds, on-screen instructions on how to \"Enter Setup\" or \"Enter BIOS\" will explain which key(s) will allow you do do this. Typically, F2, F12, or Delete might work. Press this key immediately after starting you computer; If you see Windows loading, reboot as you have missed the opportunity.  Once the boot order list has been located in the BIOS setup, change the order for the boot from the current hard drive C: to the USB thumb drive (May be \"USB Mass Storage or External USB Device etc). Make sure to save before exiting the BIOS. Once the bios has been changed, the next reboot of the machine should boot from the USB drive and bring up the Ubuntu operating system. Select: Perpetually store changes to USB drive as the style of system you would like to run (basically press Enter twice). Once you are operating in the Ubuntu system, download the following software packages to your new desktop:\n\nYou will first need to configure your wireless settings or at least your ethernet connection in order to get the internet working. Ubuntu is designed to make this simple and this is beyond the scope of this document, so please consult the ubuntu forums if you are unable to get the internet to work. You will need to install a series of packages, the easiest way to do this is probably via the Add/Remove applications option.\n\n*avrtools\n*avrdude\n*gcc-avr\n*bin-utils\n*avr-libc\n*ruby\n*rubygems\n\nThese can also be installed manually by opening a command prompt (via Applications, Terminal) and typing \"sudo apt-get install PackageName\" (eg. sudo apt-get install avrtools )\n\nYou will also need to install Sun Java 6 (arduino needs this), which is easiest to install in the Add/Remove Applications GUI by selecting all repositories and searching for it. If you don\'t have ALL available repositories available (which is the default), only the gnu java package will install which will not work.\n \n*download [http://shoooes.net/ Shoes]for Linux\n*download the latest Opensprints software (unpack this to your desktop once using Ubuntu)\n*download the [http://arduino.cc Arduino] operating panel\n*download the programming language [http://http://www.ruby-lang.org/en/ Ruby]\n\n*Shoes is a very straightforward install using its own installer and can be installed first.\n*The arduino panel also has its own unpacker and can be installed next. The panel will be used to upload the latest Opensprints hex codes to the Arduino microcontroller.\n*Those familiar with Linux will already know that many Linux software packages like Ruby can be uploaded through the install system included with Ubuntu. In this case the Ruby install will take care of most of the software needed, the required libraries will need to be uploaded in addition to the basic install.\n\n== Creating a dual-boot windows/ubuntu system ==\nFor those with the hard-drive space, it is possible to install the most recent Ubuntu release (Intrepid Ibex) as a folder on your windows system. The choice of operating system will appear each time the computer is powered up, following the bios screen. This can be accomplished using a program called [http://wubi-installer.org Wubi]. \n\nA tutorial/memoir of the wubi/opensprints software installation process on an inexpensive acer laptop, as well as the problems encountered can be found [http://docs.google.com/Doc?id=dd4kx4mt_278gh78kgcq here].','utf-8'),(130,'\'\'Currently the software only runs on a Linux system. If you are unfamiliar with the system this can seem a bit daunting, however there are a few tips and ideas for getting the system up and running as quick as possible.\'\'\n\n\n== Linux as an operating system ==\n\nIf you don\'t have a machine that currently has a Linux operating system on it, running the setup from an attached USB thumbdrive with both the Linux operating system as well as the other software requirements for Opensprints is another option. One popular and straightforward operating system for Linux is [http://www.ubuntu.com UBUNTU]. The entire Ubuntu operating system as well as the other software packages can be stored on a single 2GB thumb drive and be moved to any machine with little if any changes. If your laptop currently has a windows operating system, it will remain intact and the whole setup becomes very portable and non-intrusive.\n\n== Creating a bootable persistant Ubuntu 8.10 thumbdrive ==\n\nCredit for this method goes to [http://www.pendrivelinux.com/ubuntu-810-persistent-flash-drive-install-from-live-cd/ Pen Drive Linux].\n\nWith this method, you must use a 2GB or larger thumb drive.\n\n   1. Download the Ubuntu 8.10 ISO and burn it to a CD\n   2. Restart your computer, booting from the Live CD\n   3. Insert a 2GB or larger USB flash drive\n   4. Open a terminal and type the following into the terminal window:\n\n          wget pendrivelinux.com/downloads/u810/u810.sh\n\n          chmod +x u810.sh && sh u810.sh\n\n   5. Follow the onscreen instructions\n   6. Once the script has finished, reboot your computer and set your BIOS or boot menu to boot from the USB device\n\n\nGetting a machine BIOS to boot from the USB drive will differ from computer to computer, typically with in the first 5 seconds, on-screen instructions on how to \"Enter Setup\" or \"Enter BIOS\" will explain which key(s) will allow you do do this. Typically, F2, F12, or Delete might work. Press this key immediately after starting you computer; If you see Windows loading, reboot as you have missed the opportunity.  Once the boot order list has been located in the BIOS setup, change the order for the boot from the current hard drive C: to the USB thumb drive (May be \"USB Mass Storage or \"External USB Device\"). Make sure to save before exiting the BIOS. After leaving the BIOS, the next reboot of the machine should boot from the USB drive and bring up the Ubuntu operating system. The Ubuntu boot screen will have options for \"Perpetually store changes\", select this option (Note: You should just need to press enter twice in practice once at this screen). Once you are operating in the Ubuntu system, you will need to start downloading files and packages for Opensprints. First focus