 an operating system ==\n\nIf you don\'t have a machine that currently has a Linux operating system on it, running the setup from an attached USB thumbdrive with both the Linux operating system as well as the other software requirements for Opensprints is another option. One popular and straightforward operating system for Linux is [http://www.ubuntu.com Ubuntu]. \n\n==Creating a bootable Ubuntu 8.10 persistent thumbdrive for Opensprints ==\n\nThe entire Ubuntu Linux operating system as well as the other software packages can be stored on a single 2GB thumb drive and be moved to any machine with little if any changes. The persistent thumbdrive installs a special copy of ubuntu that saves all changes and software packages to the thumbdrive, so no changes are lost. If your laptop currently has a windows operating system, it will remain intact and the whole setup becomes very portable and non-intrusive.\n\nCredit for the persistent install method and additional help on installing Ubuntu can be found at [http://www.pendrivelinux.com/ubuntu-810-persistent-flash-drive-install-from-live-cd/ Pen Drive Linux].\n\n# Download the Ubuntu 8.10 ISO and burn it to a CD [[http://www.ubuntu.com/getubuntu/download]].\n# Restart your computer, booting from the Live CD (You may need to follow the next step to boot off the CD)\n# Insert a 2GB or larger USB flash drive.\n# Open terminal (Applications -> Accessories -> Terminal) and type the following into the terminal window:\n## wget pendrivelinux.com/downloads/u810/u810.sh\n## chmod +x u810.sh && sh u810.sh\n# Follow the onscreen instructions.\n# Once the script has finished, reboot your computer and follow the instructions below to set your BIOS or boot menu to boot from the USB device.\n\n===Changing the Default Boot order of your computer ===\n\nGetting a machine BIOS to boot from the USB drive will differ from computer to computer, typically with in the first 5 seconds of booting your computer the on-screen instructions on how to \"Enter Setup\" or \"Enter BIOS\" will show which key(s) to press. They are commonly F2, F12, or Delete. You will have to press this key immediately after powering on your system, it\'s easy to miss and have it load windows instead, if this happens simply reboot and try again. Once in the BIOS, the drive boot order list has to be located and change in order to boot from the USB drive first. Search through your BIOS options until you see the option to change the boot order from the current hard drive (Eg. ATA/IDE HDD) to the USB thumb drive (Eg. \"USB Mass Storage or \"External USB Device\"). Make sure to save changes before exiting the BIOS (sometimes when you exit it will prompt you for this). After leaving the BIOS, the next reboot should boot from the USB drive and bring up the Ubuntu operating system. The Ubuntu boot screen will have options for booting \"Persistent\", select this option (In practice you will just press enter twice at the ubuntu boot screen). Once you are operating in the Ubuntu system, you will need to start downloading files and packages for Opensprints. Congratulations, you are now running Ubuntu Linux off of your USB Thumb drive in a persistent state (meaning everything you do going forward will be saved). \n\n===Get the internet working===\nFirst, focus on getting your network connection to work, via either wired ethernet or wireless. Ubuntu was designed make this as simple as possible but this is beyond the scope of this document. If you are unable to get the internet to work, please consult the [http://ubuntuforums.org/search.php ubuntu forums]. Be sure to gather as much information on your hardware and network card via the hardware manuals and manufacture website etc.\n\n===Installing necessary software packages and software===\nYou will need to install a series of software packages in order to run opensprints as well as compile the nessasary fireware hex code for the Arduino controller. The easiest way to install packaged software is via Applications then Add/Remove. This GUI will allow you to search for individual package names and easily install software. It is important to enable 3rd party applications by Selecting \"All available Applications\". You will need the following applications installed. Type the  package names in the search function to find and install them.\n\n*avrtools\n*avrdude\n*gcc-avr\n*bin-utils\n*avr-libc\n*ruby\n*rubygems\n\nThese can also be installed manually by opening a command prompt (via Applications, Terminal) and typing \"sudo apt-get install PackageName\" (eg. sudo apt-get install avrtools )\n\n*sun-java6-jre\nYou will also need to install Sun Java 6 (arduino operating panel needs this), which is easiest to install in the Add/Remove Applications GUI by selecting all repositories and searching for \"sun\". If you don\'t have ALL available repositories available (which is NOT the default), only the gnu java package will be available which will not work.\n \nThe following applications cannot be installed via apt or have not been tested yet and will need to be downloaded directly.\n*download [http://shoooes.net/ Shoes]for Linux\n**Shoes is a very straightforward install using its own installer and can be installed first.\n**\'\'Installing \"shoes\" via apt is available but untested.\'\'\n*download the latest [http://github.com/evanfarrar/opensprints/tree/master Opensprints software] (Click download, select .zip to download the most recent version from github)\n*download the [http://arduino.cc Arduino] operating panel.\n**\'\'The arduino panel also has its own unpacker and can be installed next. The panel will be used to upload the latest Opensprints hex codes to the Arduino microcontroller\'\'\n\n\n== Programing the Arduino==\n\nThe Arduino microcontroller will need to be programmed with firmware. There are two firmware sources to choose from:\n\n# basic_msg -- programmed by Evan Farrar\n# advanced_msg --  programmed by Morgan (SF)\n# arduino-0011 -- This is the Arduino panel software that is used to compile and burn hex firmware images to arduino MCs. It is included in the Opensprints distribution linked above.\n\n===basic_message===\nOpen a terminal window and change directory to the folder, eg:\n  cd /home/user/Desktop/evanfarrar-opensprints-6184492bc1410de49c0515441dd5cdff1b8da425/firmware/arduino/basic_msg\n\nopen the basic_msg.pde with your favorite text editor (vim, nano)\n\nedit the following line:\n  int raceLengthTicks = 1400;\nThis integer needs to match the \"race_distance:\" variable set in your \'\'\'conf.yml\'\'\' file, eg. in this case it would equal \"race_distance: 1400\"  If you are not familar with this file yet, it is the main configuration file used by opensprints and is located at the root of the OS folder. The default is 200 (200 meters), so if you are just testing hardware, setting it to something low like 20 and then making sure your conf.yml matches later might make testing easier.\nIf the integers dont equate out, you will have timing and finish errors. Getting the correct number of ticks into the hex requires a bit of figuring. \nFind your roller circumference. This is for the calculations for time and winner. \nDetermine the distance you would like to race at. This is for the animation\n Although the distance can be changed easily once shoes is running a race, the race will not end until the determined amount of ticks is reached. \nDetermine the amount of rotations will have to be completed to achieve the distance you want to race. \nex: if your roller circumference is 25CM, and you want to race 100 meters. The ticks to equal that distance would be 400 ticks. Your settings would look something like this:\nint raceLengthTicks = 400\ndistance in Meters = 100\nroller circumference = .25 (in meters remember) \nIf your roller isnt so easily calculated. Lets say its 23CM circumference. You want to err on the short side. The race animation will quit once the distance is reached and stop counting ticks. if the ticks have not been reached, the time will not be accurate or not operate at all.\n\n===advanced_message===\n\n*Supports 4 Riders\n\n== Creating a dual-boot windows/ubuntu system ==\nFor those with the hard-drive space, it is possible to install the most recent Ubuntu release (Intrepid Ibex) as a folder on your windows system. The choice of operating system will appear each time the computer is powered up, following the bios screen. This can be accomplished using a program called [http://wubi-installer.org Wubi]. \n\nA tutorial/memoir of the wubi/opensprints software installation process on an inexpensive acer laptop, as well as the problems encountered can be found [http://docs.google.com/Doc?id=dd4kx4mt_278gh78kgcq here].\n\n\n\n=Old Wiki=\n  This is a copy of the old wiki page, which will be merged with above. I wanted to make sure it was posted ASAP because I believe it is not accessible any longer through the main page.\n\n===  Base Dependencies ===\n\n* ruby: the programming language\n* ruby/gtk: to run the interface\n* gems: the ruby package management system \n\n sudo apt-get update\n sudo apt-get install ruby-gnome2 gems rubygems ruby1.8-dev libserialport-ruby shoes\n\n* the software: http://mindsplatter.net/opensprints/trunk/opensprints-linux.zip\n\n=== Ruby Library Dependencies ===\n\nThere are dependencies that can be installed through the gems system:\n\n* [http://rubyforge.org/projects/units units]\n* [http://rubyforge.org/projects/builder builder]\n* [http://rubyforge.org/projects/cairo/ cairo]\n\n sudo gem update --system\n sudo gem install units builder cairo\n\nIf you get this error like this one:\n \n ERROR: Error installing cairo:\n ERROR: Failed to build gem native extension.\n /usr/bin/ruby1.8 extconf.rb install units builder cairo\n extconf.rb:7:in `require\': no such file to load -- mkmf (LoadError)\n from extconf.rb:7\n\nMake sure you installed the package ruby1.8-dev and you do this:\n\n sudo rm /usr/bin/gem\n sudo ln -s /usr/bin/gem1.8 /usr/bin/gem\n\n== Using the Application ==\n\nMake sure that your conf.yml file is pointing to the right device, by default it should be /dev/ttyACM0.  If it isn\'t the OpenSprints application will count down from 5 and then disappear!\n\n=== Loading ===\n\nIssue the following commands in a terminal window, feel free to change \'\'RedName\'\' and \'\'BlueName\'\':\n\n > cd opensprints/\n opensprints> ruby main.rb RedName BlueName\n\n[[Image:opensprints_screen.png]]\n\n=== Starting a Race ===\n\n\'\'\'Hit the \'a\' key to start the countdown.\'\'\'\n\nIt will start at 5, go down to 1 and the say \'\'\'Go!\'\'\'  If it disappears after you say go, confirm that the USB port in your conf.yml file is correct.\n\n[[Image:opensprints_finish_screen.png]]\n\n=== Restarting a Race ===\n\nAt least for the current version, just close the window and restart it.\n\n== Troubleshooting ==\n\n=== Confirming USB port ===\n\nBy default, the configuration file ([[conf.yml]]) for [[OpenSprints]] uses /dev/ttyACM0\n\nHowever, you might want to confirm this by using the following command in a terminal:\n\n > ls /dev/ttyACM*\n\n[[Image:listing_usb_ports.png]]\n\nFor more diagnostic information on your USB Ports, use the following commands:\n\n > lsusb\n > dmesg | grep usb\n\n=== Testing the [[USB Bit Wacker]] ===\n\nWe need to make sure the [[UBW]] and [[firmware]] are working before we assume it is the software.\n\nFirst install GtkTerm if you haven\'t already.\n\n > sudo apt-get install gtkterm\n\n\'\'\'Step 1:\'\'\' Connect to the right port.  Open GtkTerm and goto Configuration-->Port or hit Ctrl-S.  Change the default port from /dev/ttyS0 to /dev/ttyACM0 (or whatever you determined the USB port to be).\n\n[[Image:gtkterm_connection.png]]\n\n\'\'\'Step 2:\'\'\' Hit the \'v\' key.  If you don\'t see anything hit the \'v\' key and ENTER] until you see a message from the Firmware.\n\n[[Image:gtkterm_ubw_v.png]]\n\n\'\'\'Step 3:\'\'\' Type \'go\' and [ENTER] and make sure the each sensor is working.  1;0:1233 means the first [[Sensor Board]] is working and 2;0:361 means the second is too.\n\n[[Image:gtkterm_ubw_go.png]]\n\n== See Also ==\n\n* [[Software Installation]]','utf-8'),(147,'\'\'Currently the software only runs on a Linux system. If you are unfamiliar with the system this can seem a bit daunting, however there are a few tips and ideas for getting the system up and running as quick as possible.\'\'\n\n== Linux as an operating system ==\n\nIf you don\'t have a machine that currently has a Linux operating system on it, running the setup from an attached USB thumbdrive with both the Linux operating system as well as the other software requirements for Opensprints is another option. One popular and straightforward operating system for Linux is [http://www.ubuntu.com Ubuntu]. \n\n==Creating a bootable Ubuntu 8.10 persistent thumbdrive for Opensprints ==\n\nThe entire Ubuntu Linux operating system as well as the other software packages can be stored on a single 2GB thumb drive and be moved to any machine with little if any changes. The persistent thumbdrive installs a special copy of ubuntu that saves all changes and software packages to the thumbdrive, so no changes are lost. If your laptop currently has a windows operating system, it will remain intact and the whole setup becomes very portable and non-intrusive.\n\nCredit for the persistent install method and additional help on installing Ubuntu can be found at [http://www.pendrivelinux.com/ubuntu-810-persistent-flash-drive-install-from-live-cd/ Pen Drive Linux].\n\n# Download the Ubuntu 8.10 ISO and burn it to a CD [[http://www.ubuntu.com/getubuntu/download]].\n# Restart your computer, booting from the Live CD (You may need to follow the next step to boot off the CD)\n# Insert a 2GB or larger USB flash drive.\n# Open terminal (Applications -> Accessories -> Terminal) and type the following into the terminal window:\n## wget pendrivelinux.com/downloads/u810/u810.sh\n## chmod +x u810.sh && sh u810.sh\n# Follow the onscreen instructions.\n# Once the script has finished, reboot your computer and follow the instructions below to set your BIOS or boot menu to boot from the USB device.\n\n===Changing the Default Boot order of your computer ===\n\nGetting a machine BIOS to boot from the USB drive will differ from computer to computer, typically with in the first 5 seconds of booting your computer the on-screen instructions on how to \"Enter Setup\" or \"Enter BIOS\" will show which key(s) to press. They are commonly F2, F12, or Delete. You will have to press this key immediately after powering on your system, it\'s easy to miss and have it load windows instead, if this happens simply reboot and try again. Once in the BIOS, the drive boot order list has to be located and change in order to boot from the USB drive first. Search through your BIOS options until you see the option to change the boot order from the current hard drive (Eg. ATA/IDE HDD) to the USB thumb drive (Eg. \"USB Mass Storage or \"External USB Device\"). Make sure to save changes before exiting the BIOS (sometimes when you exit it will prompt you for this). After leaving the BIOS, the next reboot should boot from the USB drive and bring up the Ubuntu operating system. The Ubuntu boot screen will have options for booting \"Persistent\", select this option (In practice you will just press enter twice at the ubuntu boot screen). Once you are operating in the Ubuntu system, you will need to start downloading files and packages for Opensprints. Congratulations, you are now running Ubuntu Linux off of your USB Thumb drive in a persistent state (meaning everything you do going forward will be saved). \n\n===Get the internet working===\nFirst, focus on getting your network connection to work, via either wired ethernet or wireless. Ubuntu was designed make this as simple as possible but this is beyond the scope of this document. If you are unable to get the internet to work, please consult the [http://ubuntuforums.org/search.php ubuntu forums]. Be sure to gather as much information on your hardware and network card via the hardware manuals and manufacture website etc.\n\n===Installing necessary software packages and software===\nYou will need to install a series of software packages in order to run opensprints as well as compile the nessasary fireware hex code for the Arduino controller. The easiest way to install packaged software is via Applications then Add/Remove. This GUI will allow you to search for individual package names and easily install software. It is important to enable 3rd party applications by Selecting \"All available Applications\". You will need the following applications installed. Type the  package names in the search function to find and install them.\n\n*avrtools\n*avrdude\n*gcc-avr\n*bin-utils\n*avr-libc\n*ruby\n*rubygems\n\nThese can also be installed manually by opening a command prompt (via Applications, Terminal) and typing \"sudo apt-get install PackageName\" (eg. sudo apt-get install avrtools )\n\n*sun-java6-jre\nYou will also need to install Sun Java 6 (arduino operating panel needs this), which is easiest to install in the Add/Remove Applications GUI by selecting all repositories and searching for \"sun\". If you don\'t have ALL available repositories available (which is NOT the default), only the gnu java package will be available which will not work.\n \nThe following applications cannot be installed via apt or have not been tested yet and will need to be downloaded directly.\n*download [http://shoooes.net/ Shoes]for Linux\n**Shoes is a very straightforward install using its own installer and can be installed first.\n**\'\'Installing \"shoes\" via apt is available but untested.\'\'\n*download the latest [http://github.com/evanfarrar/opensprints/tree/master Opensprints software] (Click download, select .zip to download the most recent version from github)\n*download the [http://arduino.cc Arduino] operating panel.\n**\'\'The arduino panel also has its own unpacker and can be installed next. The panel will be used to upload the latest Opensprints hex codes to the Arduino microcontroller\'\'\n\n\n== Programing the Arduino==\n\nThe Arduino microcontroller will need to be programmed with firmware. There are two firmware sources to choose from:\n\n# basic_msg -- programmed by Evan Farrar\n# advanced_msg --  programmed by Morgan (SF)\n# arduino-0011 -- This is the Arduino panel software that is used to compile and burn hex firmware images to arduino MCs. It is included in the Opensprints distribution linked above.\n\n===basic_message===\nOpen a terminal window and change directory to the folder, eg:\n  cd /home/user/Desktop/evanfarrar-opensprints-6184492bc1410de49c0515441dd5cdff1b8da425/firmware/arduino/basic_msg\n\nopen the basic_msg.pde with your favorite text editor (vim, nano)\n\nedit the following line:\n  int raceLengthTicks = 1400;\nThis integer needs to match the \"race_distance:\" variable set in your \'\'\'conf.yml\'\'\' file, eg. in this case it would equal \"race_distance: 1400\"  If you are not familar with this file yet, it is the main configuration file used by opensprints and is located at the root of the OS folder. The default is 200 (200 meters), so if you are just testing hardware, setting it to something low like 20 and then making sure your conf.yml matches later might make testing easier.\nIf the integers dont equate out, you will have timing and finish errors. Getting the correct number of ticks into the hex requires a bit of figuring. \nFind your roller circumference. This is for the calculations for time and winner. \nDetermine the distance you would like to race at. This is for the animation\nAlthough the distance can be changed easily once shoes is running a race, the race will not end until the determined amount of ticks is reached. \nDetermine the amount of rotations will have to be completed to achieve the distance you want to race. \nex: if your roller circumference is 25CM, and you want to race 100 meters. The ticks to equal that distance would be 400 ticks. Your settings would look something like this:\n int raceLengthTicks = 400\n distance in Meters = 100\n roller circumference = .25 (in meters remember) \nIf your roller isnt so easily calculated. Lets say its 23CM circumference. You want to err on the short side. The race animation will quit once the distance is reached and stop counting ticks. if the ticks have not been reached, the time will not be accurate or not operate at all.\n\n===advanced_message===\n\n*Supports 4 Riders\n\n== Creating a dual-boot windows/ubuntu system ==\nFor those with the hard-drive space, it is possible to install the most recent Ubuntu release (Intrepid Ibex) as a folder on your windows system. The choice of operating system will appear each time the computer is powered up, following the bios screen. This can be accomplished using a program called [http://wubi-installer.org Wubi]. \n\nA tutorial/memoir of the wubi/opensprints software installation process on an inexpensive acer laptop, as well as the problems encountered can be found [http://docs.google.com/Doc?id=dd4kx4mt_278gh78kgcq here].\n\n\n\n=Old Wiki=\n  This is a copy of the old wiki page, which will be merged with above. I wanted to make sure it was posted ASAP because I believe it is not accessible any longer through the main page.\n\n===  Base Dependencies ===\n\n* ruby: the programming language\n* ruby/gtk: to run the interface\n* gems: the ruby package management system \n\n sudo apt-get update\n sudo apt-get install ruby-gnome2 gems rubygems ruby1.8-dev libserialport-ruby shoes\n\n* the software: http://mindsplatter.net/opensprints/trunk/opensprints-linux.zip\n\n=== Ruby Library Dependencies ===\n\nThere are dependencies that can be installed through the gems system:\n\n* [http://rubyforge.org/projects/units units]\n* [http://rubyforge.org/projects/builder builder]\n* [http://rubyforge.org/projects/cairo/ cairo]\n\n sudo gem update --s