 The ticks to equal that distance would be 400 ticks. Your settings would look something like this:\n int raceLengthTicks = 400\n distance in Meters = 100\n roller circumference = .25 (in meters remember) \nIf your roller isnt so easily calculated. Lets say its 23CM circumference. You want to err on the short side. The race animation will quit once the distance is reached and stop counting ticks. if the ticks have not been reached, the time will not be accurate or not operate at all.\n\nNow to compile and upload your firmware to the arduino. From the firmware directory, type the \"make\" command. If that fails, you may have made a typo while editing the basic_message.pde file or some of your dependencies may be missing.\n\nIf that is successful, attach the arduino to your computer and run the command \"make upload\". If that is successful, you are ready to run opensprints.\n\n===advanced_message===\n\nDoes not require the above editing of source code. Just compile and upload your firmware to the arduino. From the firmware directory, type the \"make\" command. If that fails some of your dependencies may be missing.\n\nIf that is successful, attach the arduino to your computer and run the command \"make upload\". If that is successful, you are ready to run opensprints.\n\n== Creating a dual-boot windows/ubuntu system ==\nFor those with the hard-drive space, it is possible to install the most recent Ubuntu release (Intrepid Ibex) as a folder on your windows system. The choice of operating system will appear each time the computer is powered up, following the bios screen. This can be accomplished using a program called [http://wubi-installer.org Wubi]. \n\nA tutorial/memoir of the wubi/opensprints software installation process on an inexpensive acer laptop, as well as the problems encountered can be found [http://docs.google.com/Doc?id=dd4kx4mt_278gh78kgcq here].\n\n\n\n=Old Wiki=\n  This is a copy of the old wiki page, which will be merged with above. I wanted to make sure it was posted ASAP because I believe it is not accessible any longer through the main page.\n\n===  Base Dependencies ===\n\n* ruby: the programming language\n* ruby/gtk: to run the interface\n* gems: the ruby package management system \n\n sudo apt-get update\n sudo apt-get install ruby-gnome2 gems rubygems ruby1.8-dev libserialport-ruby shoes\n\n* the software: http://mindsplatter.net/opensprints/trunk/opensprints-linux.zip\n\n=== Ruby Library Dependencies ===\n\nThere are dependencies that can be installed through the gems system:\n\n* [http://rubyforge.org/projects/units units]\n* [http://rubyforge.org/projects/builder builder]\n* [http://rubyforge.org/projects/cairo/ cairo]\n\n sudo gem update --system\n sudo gem install units builder cairo\n\nIf you get this error like this one:\n \n ERROR: Error installing cairo:\n ERROR: Failed to build gem native extension.\n /usr/bin/ruby1.8 extconf.rb install units builder cairo\n extconf.rb:7:in `require\': no such file to load -- mkmf (LoadError)\n from extconf.rb:7\n\nMake sure you installed the package ruby1.8-dev and you do this:\n\n sudo rm /usr/bin/gem\n sudo ln -s /usr/bin/gem1.8 /usr/bin/gem\n\n== Using the Application ==\n\nMake sure that your conf.yml file is pointing to the right device, by default it should be /dev/ttyACM0.  If it isn\'t the OpenSprints application will count down from 5 and then disappear!\n\n=== Loading ===\n\nIssue the following commands in a terminal window, feel free to change \'\'RedName\'\' and \'\'BlueName\'\':\n\n > cd opensprints/\n opensprints> ruby main.rb RedName BlueName\n\n[[Image:opensprints_screen.png]]\n\n=== Starting a Race ===\n\n\'\'\'Hit the \'a\' key to start the countdown.\'\'\'\n\nIt will start at 5, go down to 1 and the say \'\'\'Go!\'\'\'  If it disappears after you say go, confirm that the USB port in your conf.yml file is correct.\n\n[[Image:opensprints_finish_screen.png]]\n\n=== Restarting a Race ===\n\nAt least for the current version, just close the window and restart it.\n\n== Troubleshooting ==\n\n=== Confirming USB port ===\n\nBy default, the configuration file ([[conf.yml]]) for [[OpenSprints]] uses /dev/ttyACM0\n\nHowever, you might want to confirm this by using the following command in a terminal:\n\n > ls /dev/ttyACM*\n\n[[Image:listing_usb_ports.png]]\n\nFor more diagnostic information on your USB Ports, use the following commands:\n\n > lsusb\n > dmesg | grep usb\n\n=== Testing the [[USB Bit Wacker]] ===\n\nWe need to make sure the [[UBW]] and [[firmware]] are working before we assume it is the software.\n\nFirst install GtkTerm if you haven\'t already.\n\n > sudo apt-get install gtkterm\n\n\'\'\'Step 1:\'\'\' Connect to the right port.  Open GtkTerm and goto Configuration-->Port or hit Ctrl-S.  Change the default port from /dev/ttyS0 to /dev/ttyACM0 (or whatever you determined the USB port to be).\n\n[[Image:gtkterm_connection.png]]\n\n\'\'\'Step 2:\'\'\' Hit the \'v\' key.  If you don\'t see anything hit the \'v\' key and ENTER] until you see a message from the Firmware.\n\n[[Image:gtkterm_ubw_v.png]]\n\n\'\'\'Step 3:\'\'\' Type \'go\' and [ENTER] and make sure the each sensor is working.  1;0:1233 means the first [[Sensor Board]] is working and 2;0:361 means the second is too.\n\n[[Image:gtkterm_ubw_go.png]]\n\n== See Also ==\n\n* [[Software Installation]]','utf-8'),(156,'The OpenSprints solution consists of the following subsystems:\n* A USB interface and sensors for monitoring roller rotations\n** An [http://arduino.cc/en/Main/ArduinoBoardDuemilanove Arduino] is used for interfacing the PC to the sensors. \n** Up to four rollers can be monitored simultaneously in the default configuration.\n*** Two status LEDs on each roller sensor display \"connected\" status and blinks once each \"revolution\".\n*** A magnet mounted on the roller drum triggers the sensor each revolution.\n* A PC providing the race display (optional)\n** Multi-platform support (Linux, Mac OS X, Windows)\n** Tournament interface with brackets, best times.\n==User Documentation==\n* [[Hardware Installation]]\n* [[Software Installation]]\n* [[Event Setup]]\n* [[FAQ]]\n\n==Dev Resources==\n* [[Source Code]] - including PC application, sensor interface firmware, and electronics CAD files.\n* [[Hardware Development]]\n* [[Feature Requests]]\n* [[Video Interface Development]]\n* [[Bugs]]\n==Community==\n* [[Community Images|Images]]\n* [[Community Videos|Videos]]','utf-8'),(157,'== Does the interface pack give me everything i would need to display progress? ==\n\nYes and no. We have in the past built an LED progress meter for each bike. Each meter was just a row of 4 LEDs, and we basically hacked some flashers, so it looked pretty raw. We ran races outside using those LED meters without any computer. That feature is not present in the current version of the firmware in the interface device. However, the next revision of hardware will have LED meters, so that feature will be available by default.\n\n== Would I require additional software? ==\n\nAdditional software is currently required in the following cases:\n* Displaying the race progress on a projector screen for an audience or on a computer monitor for the racers. This software is a free download available on our site.\n* Changing the race distance. This software is a free download available on the Arduino site.\n\n== How do they attach to rollers and comp? ==\n\nThe sensors can be taped to the roller frame or secured with hook and loop strips or zip ties.\n\nThe magnet can be taped to the roller. I\'ve seen an instance where some people fastened a cyclo-computer magnet to the flat edge of the roller drum. see this forum post for more info:\nhttp://www.opensprints.com/forum/comments.php?DiscussionID=2\n\nEach sensor connects to the interface device with a standard ethernet cable.\n\nThe interface device mainly consists of an Arduino, which link up to the computer via USB.\n\n== What frame size of bike do you feel is the most adaptable for riders? ==\n\nNot sure. when we had just two bikes in our setup, we had two sizes of frames a - smaller one that accommodated the smallest of racers, and a larger one that the big people could fit on. we always use track frames because that\'s what is currently in vogue :)\n\n== How much would it cost to buy the sensors, magnets and all other equipment to get the info from rollers to screen? ==\n\nRough estimate... assuming you already have the expensive stuff like bikes, rollers, computer, (projector), here\'s a rough estimate for the sensor system:\n\n* interface device:\n** $35 arduino\n** $10-15 electronics components\n** $12 enclosure\n** $5 cable\n\n* for each sensor:\n** $12 electronics components\n** $5 enclosure\n** $5 cable\n\nfor each LED progress meter\n$12 electronics components\n$5 enclosure\n$5 cable\n\nAgain, that\'s a rough estimate. Also, that\'s assuming you buy generic protoboard PCBs instead of fancy OpenSprints PCBs, of which we sold sets for $50 US incl. shipping. Basically our custom PCBs make assembly a breeze.\n\nOnce the next revision of the PCBs is finished, we are looking into selling kits, which will include all the parts for the system (except the Arduino and also the cables, which are easy to come by). Not sure how much we will be charging for that.','utf-8'),(158,'The OpenSprints solution consists of the following subsystems:\n* A USB interface and sensors for monitoring roller rotations\n** An [http://arduino.cc/en/Main/ArduinoBoardDuemilanove Arduino] is used for interfacing the PC to the sensors. The interface board is basically an Arduino-compatible shield.\n** Up to four rollers can be monitored simultaneously in the default configuration.\n*** Two status LEDs on each roller sensor display \"connected\" status and blinks once each \"revolution\".\n*** A magnet mounted on the roller drum triggers the sensor each revolution.\n* A PC providing the race display (optional)\n** Multi-platform support (Linux, Mac OS X, Windows)\n** Tournament interface with brackets, best times.\n==User Documentation==\n* [[Hardware Installation]]\n* [[Software Installation]]\n* [[Event Setup]]\n* [[FAQ]]\n\n==Dev Resources==\n* [[Source Code]] - including PC application, sensor interface firmware, and electronics CAD files.\n* [[Hardware Development]]\n* [[Feature Requests]]\n* [[Video Interface Development]]\n* [[Bugs]]\n==Community==\n* [[Community Images|Images]]\n* [[Community Videos|Videos]]','utf-8'),(159,'The OpenSprints solution consists of the following subsystems:\n* A USB interface and sensors for monitoring roller rotations\n** An [http://arduino.cc/en/Main/ArduinoBoardDuemilanove Arduino] is used for interfacing the PC to the sensors. The interface board is basically an Arduino-compatible shield.\n** Up to four rollers can be monitored simultaneously in the default configuration.\n*** Two status LEDs on each roller sensor display \"connected\" status and blinks once each \"revolution\".\n*** A magnet mounted on the roller drum triggers the sensor each revolution.\n* A PC providing the race display (optional)\n** Multi-platform support (Linux, Mac OS X, Windows)\n** Tournament interface with brackets, best times.\n* (Coming soon) Some flashy LED progress meters.\n==User Documentation==\n* [[Hardware Installation]]\n* [[Software Installation]]\n* [[Event Setup]]\n* [[FAQ]]\n\n==Dev Resources==\n* [[Source Code]] - including PC application, sensor interface firmware, and electronics CAD files.\n* [[Hardware Development]]\n* [[Feature Requests]]\n* [[Video Interface Development]]\n* [[Bugs]]\n==Community==\n* [[Community Images|Images]]\n* [[Community Videos|Videos]]','utf-8'),(160,'The OpenSprints solution consists of the following subsystems:\n* A USB interface and sensors for monitoring roller rotations\n** An [http://arduino.cc/en/Main/ArduinoBoardDuemilanove Arduino] is used for interfacing the PC to the sensors. The interface board is basically an Arduino-compatible shield.\n** Up to four rollers can be monitored simultaneously in the default configuration.\n*** Two status LEDs on each roller sensor display \"connected\" status and blinks once each \"revolution\".\n*** A magnet mounted on the roller drum triggers the sensor each revolution.\n* A PC providing the race display (optional)\n** Multi-platform support (Linux, Mac OS X, Windows)\n** Tournament interface with brackets, best times.\n* (Coming soon) Some flashy LED progress meters.\n==User Documentation==\n* [[Hardware Installation]]\n* [[Software Installation]]\n* [[Event Setup]]\n* [[FAQ]]\n* [http://www.opensprints.com/forum/ Forum]\n\n==Dev Resources==\n* [[Source Code]] - including PC application, sensor interface firmware, and electronics CAD files.\n* [[Hardware Development]]\n* [[Feature Requests]]\n* [[Video Interface Development]]\n* [[Bugs]]\n==Community==\n* [[Community Images|Images]]\n* [[Community Videos|Videos]]','utf-8'),(161,'Other questions? Need direct support? Check out the [http://www.opensprints.com/forum/ forum].\n\n== Does the interface pack give me everything i would need to display progress? ==\n\nYes and no. We have in the past built an LED progress meter for each bike. Each meter was just a row of 4 LEDs, and we basically hacked some flashers, so it looked pretty raw. We ran races outside using those LED meters without any computer. That feature is not present in the current version of the firmware in the interface device. However, the next revision of hardware will have LED meters, so that feature will be available by default.\n\n== Would I require additional software? ==\n\nAdditional software is currently required in the following cases:\n* Displaying the race progress on a projector screen for an audience or on a computer monitor for the racers. This software is a free download available on our site.\n* Changing the race distance. This software is a free download available on the Arduino site.\n\n== How do they attach to rollers and comp? ==\n\nThe sensors can be taped to the roller frame or secured with hook and loop strips or zip ties.\n\nThe magnet can be taped to the roller. I\'ve seen an instance where some people fastened a cyclo-computer magnet to the flat edge of the roller drum. see this forum post for more info:\nhttp://www.opensprints.com/forum/comments.php?DiscussionID=2\n\nEach sensor connects to the interface device with a standard ethernet cable.\n\nThe interface device mainly consists of an Arduino, which link up to the computer via USB.\n\n== What frame size of bike do you feel is the most adaptable for riders? ==\n\nNot sure. when we had just two bikes in our setup, we had two sizes of frames a - smaller one that accommodated the smallest of racers, and a larger one that the big people could fit on. we always use track frames because that\'s what is currently in vogue :)\n\n== How much would it cost to buy the sensors, magnets and all other equipment to get the info from rollers to screen? ==\n\nRough estimate... assuming you already have the expensive stuff like bikes, rollers, computer, (projector), here\'s a rough estimate for the sensor system:\n\n* interface device:\n** $35 arduino\n** $10-15 electronics components\n** $12 enclosure\n** $5 cable\n\n* for each sensor:\n** $12 electronics components\n** $5 enclosure\n** $5 cable\n\nfor each LED progress meter\n$12 electronics components\n$5 enclosure\n$5 cable\n\nAgain, that\'s a rough estimate. Also, that\'s assuming you buy generic protoboard PCBs instead of fancy OpenSprints PCBs, of which we sold sets for $50 US incl. shipping. Basically our custom PCBs make assembly a breeze.\n\nOnce the next revision of the PCBs is finished, we are looking into selling kits, which will include all the parts for the system (except the Arduino and also the cables, which are easy to come by). Not sure how much we will be charging for that.','utf-8'),(162,'Other questions? Need direct support? Check out the [http://www.opensprints.com/forum/ forum].\n== Steps for assembling the electronic equipment ==\nFirst, acquire the items in the [[Electronics parts list]]. The [[Soldering tips]] page can be a good reference for beginners.\n=== Assembling the USB interface board ===\n\nThe USB interface board is basically an Arduino piggyback board that provides a safe and convenient interconnect for the sensors. Ethernet cables are used to connect the sensors to the Arduino.\n\n==== Notes ====\n\n*The breakaway headers are very sensitive to heat. When soldering in the pins, work fast or the plastic casing will melt around the pin causing it to lean or tilt.\n*The top of the interface/piggyback board is the side that has text.\n\n==== Assembly ====\n\n# Break the male breakaway headers into two 6-position strips and two 8-position strips.\n# Use the Arduino board to align the breakaway header on the piggyback board. Connect the male header pins\' longer sides to the female pins on the Arduino. With the top of the piggyback board facing the top of the Arduino, press the Arduino into the piggyback board so that the shorter sides of the male pins enter the corresponding holes on the piggyback board. Ensure that all pins align before attempting to press the two together. The alignment will look like this: [Image coming soon] Then tack the end pins on each strip quickly. This will hold the strips in place firm enough for you to remove the Arduino and finish soldering the remaining pins.\n# Seat the Arduino on the interface board.\n# Solder RJ45 jacks to the piggyback board, one for each roller.\n# Affix the USB interface board to the bottom of the SERPAC C-6 project box with four machine screws.\n# (Optionally) cut the face plates of the project box to make openings for the USB jack and the RJ45 jack(s), and slide the face plates into place on the project box. Alternatively, omit this step.\n[[Image:Interface board mounted above 1.jpg|thumb|none|400px]]\n[[Image:Interface board mounted side 1.jpg|thumb|none|400px]]\n\n=== Assembling the sensors ===\nThe top of the board is the Side that has labels for the VCC, GND and VOUT traces. The date and version text is found on the bottom side of the board. A list of all the required components can be found in the [[Electronics parts list]] page. \n\n==== Tips/notes ====\n\n*Each bike requires a separate board.\n*Take note of the polarity of each component installed as LED\'s will only operate with the polarity correct. \n*Use caution when handling the hall effect sensors as they are sensitive to static electricity. Note that each hall sensor has a beveled side (usually printed on as well). This side should be soldered to face away from the magnet as it passes by. \n*Consider using different colored LED\'s for the \"tick\" display for each board.\n\n==== Sensor board assembly ====\n\nThere is a mistake in the design of the v2 sensor PCB that prevents the tick indicator LED from lighting only when a magnet is triggering the hall sensor. The tick indicator LED cathode is incorrectly tied to GND instead of VOUT from the HE sensor. A fairly simple rework is required, and is described below.\nInstall ALL components as directed before you begin soldering!\n* Find the top side of the PCB. All the components sit on the top side of the board, and their leads are soldered to the bottom side.\n* Install two resistors.\n* The power display LED is installed to the right. Take care when installing the LED, the longer leg, or anode, should be installed in the \"+\" socket. \n* The tick indicator requires a bit of a workaround. The anode, or longer leg should be installed in the \"+\" socket, however the cathode or \"-\" side, will be installed just to the left of it instead of the open socket to the right. The spacing will be a bit more than the spacing optimal for the LED but can certainly be installed with no problems if done with care. \nThe board should look something like this:\n\n[[Image:Sensor1.JPG|200px|thumb|none|Partially assembled board]]\n\nThe workaround involves routing the cathode, or shorter leg from the tick LED along the back to the VOUT pin labeled on the front. The route should look something like this:\n\n[[Image:Sensor2.JPG|200px|thumb|none|reroute on backside]]\n\n*The Hall sensor is installed across the top. Take care that the beveled edge (normally printed on) is facing the board and not away from it. \n*The capacitor is installed just in front of the sensor.\n\nHere is a picture of a finished board (save the RJ45 jack)\n\n[[Image:finishedfront.jpg|200px|thumb|none|finished front side]]\n\nand the backside with the wires trimmed. \'\'Note the rerouted wire\'\'.\n\n[[Image:finishedback.jpg|200px|thumb|none|Finished back]]\n\nNext, solder one or both of the RJ45 jacks to the board. If only one jack is being used, it can be soldered to either position, as the two jacks are wired in parallel.\n==== Mounting the sensor board in the enclosure ====\n* The sensor PCB is designed to fit well inside a SERPAC C-6 plastic enclosure, with slight modification to the enclosure. \n* The bottom half of the enclosure is the side that has the boss that the fastener screws into. On the bottom half of the enclosure, one of the shorter walls gets shaved off far enough that the locking legs of the RJ45 jacks are outside the enclosure. \n* The same wall is shaved off the top half of the enclosure so that the top of the RJ45 jack is exposed. NB: With the lower profile jacks from Digi-Key, it is likely that the RJ45 jack will fit under the top wall of the enclosure.\n* Surround the boss on the bottom half of the enclosure with hot melt glue\n* Seat the sensor board, component side up, down around the boss, with the glue locking the board in place.\n[[Image:Sensor_v2_open_1.jpg|400px|thumb|none]]\n[[Image:Sensor_v2_open_2.jpg|400px|thumb|none]]\n* Attach the top half of the sensor enclosure, and screw it down.','utf-8'),(163,'{| {{table}} border=\"1\" \n| align=\"center\" style=\"background:#f0f0f0;\"|\'\'\'Image\'\'\'\n| align=\"center\" style=\"background:#f0f0f0;\" width=\"400\"|\'\'\'Qty\'\'\'\n| align=\"center\" style=\"background:#f0f0f0;\"|\'\'\'Description\'\'\'\n|-\n| [[Image:OpensprintsPCB.jpg|200px|thumb|none|Opensprints PCB kit]]||1 Interface board; 1 sensor board for each roller in use||Roller sensor circuit board v2. Possibly available from opensprints.com, or make your own using OpenSprints design files.\n|}\n\n== Parts for Interface board version 2 ==\n\n{| {{table}} border=\"1\" \n| align=\"center\" style=\"background:#f0f0f0;\"|\'\'\'Image\'\'\'\n| align=\"center\" style=\"background:#f0f0f0;\" width=\"50\"|\'\'\'Qty\'\'\'\n| align=\"center\" style=\"background:#f0f0f0;\"|\'\'\'Description\'\'\'\n| align=\"center\" style=\"background:#f0f0f0;\"|\'\'\'Mfr\'\'\'\n| align=\"center\" style=\"background:#f0f0f0;\"|\'\'\'Mfr P/N\'\'\'\n| align=\"center\" style=\"background:#f0f0f0;\"|\'\'\'Supplier\'\'\'\n| align=\"center\" style=\"background:#f0f0f0;\"|\'\'\'Supplier P/N\'\'\'\n|-\n| [[Image:Arduino.jpg|200px|thumb|none|Arduino micro-controller]]||1||Arduino USB board||tinker.it||Arduino Diecimila, Duemilanove, or equivalent||[http://www.sparkfun.com/commerce/product_info.php?products_id=666 sparkfun.com]||DEV-00666\n|-\n| [[Image:serpac.jpg|200px|thumb|none|Project enclosure]]||1||plastic project enclosure. (5.1\" X 5.3\" X 1.75\")||SERPAC||A-31 GRAY||[http://search.digikey.com/scripts/DkSearch/dksus.dll?Detail&name=SRA31G-ND digikey.com]||SRA31G-ND\n|-\n| [[Image:Interface_board_v2_screws.jpg|200px|thumb|none|screws]]||4||For mounting interface board to project enclosure.||||18-8 SS Flat Head Phillips Machine Screw 4-40 Thread, 1/4\" Length||[http://www.mcmaster.com mcmaster.com]||91771A106\n|-\n| [[Image:RJ45.jpg|200px|thumb|none|Ethernet solderable jack]]||1 per bike setup (minimum 2 for a two bike arrangement) Note: Additional jacks are required for the each roller sensor (see below)||RJ45 modular jack. Low profile.||Tyco||5555164-1||[http://search.digikey.com/scripts/DkSearch/dksus.dll?Detail&name=A3144