ly by opening a command prompt (via Applications, Terminal) and typing \"sudo apt-get install gcc-avr avrdude avr-libc make\"\n\nThe following applications cannot be installed via apt:\n*download [http://shoooes.net/ Shoes]for Linux: [http://shoooes.net/dist/shoes2.run here]\n** Save it somwhere (e.g. ~/Desktop/shoes2.run)\n** Make it executable: <code>chmod 700 ~/Desktop/shoes2.run</code>\n*download the latest [http://github.com/evanfarrar/opensprints/zipball/master Opensprints software].\n** Unzip the software somewhere like ~/opensprints/\n\nNow simply run shoes by double-clicking it on your desktop, and click \"run a program\" then browse to ~/opensprints/main.rb\n\n== Programing the Arduino==\n\nThe Arduino microcontroller will need to be programmed with firmware. There are two firmware sources to choose from:\n\n# basic_msg -- programmed by Evan Farrar\n# advanced_msg --  programmed by Morgan (SF)\n# arduino-0011 -- This is the Arduino panel software that is used to compile and burn hex firmware images to arduino MCs. It is included in the Opensprints distribution linked above.\n\n===basic_message===\nOpen a terminal window and change directory to the folder, eg:\n  cd /home/user/Desktop/evanfarrar-opensprints-6184492bc1410de49c0515441dd5cdff1b8da425/firmware/arduino/basic_msg\n\nopen the basic_msg.pde with your favorite text editor (vim, nano)\n\nedit the following line:\n  int raceLengthTicks = 1400;\nThis integer needs to match the \"race_distance:\" variable set in your \'\'\'conf.yml\'\'\' file, eg. in this case it would equal \"race_distance: 1400\"  If you are not familiar with this file yet, it is the main configuration file used by opensprints and is located at the root of the OS folder. The default is 200 (200 meters), so if you are just testing hardware, setting it to something low like 20 and then making sure your conf.yml matches later might make testing easier.\nIf the integers dont equate out, you will have timing and finish errors. Getting the correct number of ticks into the hex requires a bit of figuring. \nFind your roller circumference. This is for the calculations for time and winner. \nDetermine the distance you would like to race at. This is for the animation\nAlthough the distance can be changed easily once shoes is running a race, the race will not end until the determined amount of ticks is reached. \nDetermine the amount of rotations will have to be completed to achieve the distance you want to race. \nex: if your roller circumference is 25CM, and you want to race 100 meters. The ticks to equal that distance would be 400 ticks. Your settings would look something like this:\n int raceLengthTicks = 400\n distance in Meters = 100\n roller circumference = .25 (in meters remember) \nIf your roller isnt so easily calculated. Lets say its 23CM circumference. You want to err on the short side. The race animation will quit once the distance is reached and stop counting ticks. if the ticks have not been reached, the time will not be accurate or not operate at all.\n\nNow to compile and upload your firmware to the arduino. From the firmware directory, type the \"make\" command. If that fails, you may have made a typo while editing the basic_message.pde file or some of your dependencies may be missing.\n\nIf that is successful, attach the arduino to your computer and run the command \"make upload\". If that is successful, you are ready to run opensprints.\n\n===advanced_message===\n\nDoes not require the above editing of source code. Just compile and upload your firmware to the arduino. From the firmware directory, type the \"make\" command. If that fails some of your dependencies may be missing.\n\nIf that is successful, attach the arduino to your computer and run the command \"make upload\". If that is successful, you are ready to run opensprints.\n\n== Creating a dual-boot windows/ubuntu system ==\nFor those with the hard-drive space, it is possible to install the most recent Ubuntu release (Intrepid Ibex) as a folder on your windows system. The choice of operating system will appear each time the computer is powered up, following the bios screen. This can be accomplished using a program called [http://wubi-installer.org Wubi]. \n\nA tutorial/memoir of the wubi/opensprints software installation process on an inexpensive acer laptop, as well as the problems encountered can be found [http://docs.google.com/Doc?id=dd4kx4mt_278gh78kgcq here].\n\n= Mac OS X =\n\n# Grab a copy of the latest code: http://github.com/evanfarrar/opensprints/zipball/master\n# Get the serproxy program from Arduino\'s website and extract it somewhere like the opensprints directory: http://download.berlios.de/arduino/serproxy-0.1.3-3.bin.macosx.zip\n# Install the Arduino Development suite and the USB Serial Drivers: http://arduino.cc/en/Guide/MacOSX\n# Edit the serproxy.cfg  included in opensprints\' main directory to use your arduino\'s address. There is a line that says \"serial_device1=/dev/ttyUSB0\". Change it to something like \"/dev/cu.usbserial-A9005fET\" (if you browse around in the finder you should be able to find the exact address).\n# run the serproxy program from a terminal: \"cd ~/Desktop/opensprints; ./serproxy serproxy.cfg\"\n# edit your conf.yml to use the sensor named \"network\"\n# Get the latest version of shoes and use it to open \"opensprints/main.rb\" : http://shoooes.net/dist/shoes2.dmg','utf-8'),(181,'Welcome to the OpenSprints wiki!\n\nThis wiki contains community built instructions for building and running OpenSprints.\n\nOther places:\n* [http://opensprints.org The OpenSprints Homepage]\n* [http://opensprints.org/news The OpenSprints Blog]\n* [http://opensprints.org/forum The OpenSprints Forum]\n\n\n\n=The System=\nThe OpenSprints solution consists of the following subsystems:\n* A USB interface and sensors for monitoring roller rotations\n** An [http://arduino.cc/en/Main/ArduinoBoardDuemilanove Arduino] is used for interfacing the PC to the sensors. The interface board is basically an Arduino-compatible shield.\n** Up to four rollers can be monitored simultaneously in the default configuration.\n*** Two status LEDs on each roller sensor display \"connected\" status and blinks once each \"revolution\".\n*** A magnet mounted on the roller drum triggers the sensor each revolution.\n* A PC providing the race display (optional)\n** Multi-platform support (Linux, Mac OS X, Windows)\n** Tournament interface with brackets, best times.\n* (Coming soon) Some flashy LED progress meters.\n==User Documentation==\n* [[Hardware Installation]]\n* [[Software Installation]]\n* [[Event Setup]]\n* [[FAQ]]\n\n=Dev Resources=\n* [[Source Code]] - including PC application, sensor interface firmware, and electronics CAD files.\n* [[Hardware Development]]\n* [[Feature Requests]]\n* [[Video Interface Development]]\n* [[Bugs]]\n=Community=\n* [[Community Images|Images]]\n* [[Community Videos|Videos]]','utf-8'),(182,'== Essentials ==\n\n* Two to four Complete Bicycles, minus the front wheel\n* Two to four [[Bicycle Rollers]]\n* Two to four [[Fork Mounts]], preferably mounted securely to a large base surface\n* Laptop/computer with a USB port, and setup as described in [[Software Installation]]\n* Digital Projector \'\'or\'\' lots of TVs\n* A big room, a table a chair and a projection surface\n\n== Nice to have parts ==\n\n* A stage or 1 ft high platform\n* Red and Blue electrical tape\n* Red and Blue handlebar tape\n* Red and Blue heat shrink tubing for cabling\n* Two to four 5x3 plywood boards and big 15mm bolts and angle brackets (for anchoring the fork mounts)\n* loooooong projector cable\n* differently sized seatposts, spare crankset, tubes\n* pump w/ gauge\n* gaffers tape for cords\n* [[Wheel Visualizations]]\n\n== Setting up ==\n\n* clearly indicate each bike red and blue\n* pump up the tires equally\n* put rollers on each side of the projection area, perpindicular to it\n* place fork mounts and bikes over rollers\n* set up laptop on table in view of the bikers\n* Be sure to pump up the tires to the same PSI (e.g. 100)\n\n== Race formats ==\n\n* [http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Template:16TeamBracket Complete Elimination]\n* Qualification Style: All riders race once, then race the top 8 in single elimination brackets.\n* Grudge Matches: charge per race, riders chose their opponents\n* Top Distance: racers ride for 20 seconds, highest distance wins.\n* Top Speed: ride for any amount of time, highest speed wins.\n\n== Using a projector ==\n\nSince the racers are usually facing the crowd, they can\'t see the projected display behind them.  As you might expect, a common racer request is to have monitors in front of them.  With their forehead buried in their stem, LCD screens (heavily covered in a protective Plexiglas box) might work well in between the front and rear rollers.\n\nSending the same image to multiple screens is called \'\'\'mirroring\'\'\'  This can be done with a \'\'\'VGA splitter\'\'\'.  Here are some vendors: [http://www.kvms.com/ KVMs], [http://www.networktechinc.com/ NTI], [http://www.national-tech.com/ National Technology].  Simply do a search for \'vga splitter\' to find more vendors.\n\nTo share the screen with the digital projector in Linux use this command:\n\n > xrandr --auto\n\n== References ==\n\n* [http://www.realtimesoft.com/multimon/faq.asp#Mirroring Multi-Monitor FAQ]','utf-8'),(183,'Welcome to the OpenSprints wiki!\n\nThis wiki contains community built instructions for building and running OpenSprints.\n\nOther places:\n* [http://opensprints.org The OpenSprints Homepage]\n* [http://opensprints.org/news The OpenSprints Blog]\n* [http://opensprints.org/forum The OpenSprints Forum]\n* [http://opensprints.org/forum The OpenSprints Developers Page]\n\n\n\n=The System=\nThe OpenSprints solution consists of the following subsystems:\n* A USB interface and sensors for monitoring roller rotations\n** An [http://arduino.cc/en/Main/ArduinoBoardDuemilanove Arduino] is used for interfacing the PC to the sensors. The interface board is basically an Arduino-compatible shield.\n** Up to four rollers can be monitored simultaneously in the default configuration.\n*** Two status LEDs on each roller sensor display \"connected\" status and blinks once each \"revolution\".\n*** A magnet mounted on the roller drum triggers the sensor each revolution.\n* A PC providing the race display (optional)\n** Multi-platform support (Linux, Mac OS X, Windows)\n** Tournament interface with brackets, best times.\n* (Coming soon) Some flashy LED progress meters.\n==User Documentation==\n* [[Hardware Installation]]\n* [[Software Installation]]\n* [[Event Setup]]\n* [[FAQ]]\n\n=Dev Resources=\n* [[Source Code]] - including PC application, sensor interface firmware, and electronics CAD files.\n* [[Hardware Development]]\n* [[Feature Requests]]\n* [[Video Interface Development]]\n* [[Bugs]]\n=Community=\n* [[Community Images|Images]]\n* [[Community Videos|Videos]]','utf-8'),(184,'Welcome to the OpenSprints wiki!\n\nThis wiki contains community built instructions for building and running OpenSprints.\n\nOther places:\n* [http://opensprints.org The OpenSprints Homepage]\n* [http://opensprints.org/news The OpenSprints Blog]\n* [http://opensprints.org/forum The OpenSprints Forum]\n* [http://github.com/evanfarrar/opensprints/tree/master The OpenSprints Developers Page]\n\n\n\n=The System=\nThe OpenSprints solution consists of the following subsystems:\n* A USB interface and sensors for monitoring roller rotations\n** An [http://arduino.cc/en/Main/ArduinoBoardDuemilanove Arduino] is used for interfacing the PC to the sensors. The interface board is basically an Arduino-compatible shield.\n** Up to four rollers can be monitored simultaneously in the default configuration.\n*** Two status LEDs on each roller sensor display \"connected\" status and blinks once each \"revolution\".\n*** A magnet mounted on the roller drum triggers the sensor each revolution.\n* A PC providing the race display (optional)\n** Multi-platform support (Linux, Mac OS X, Windows)\n** Tournament interface with brackets, best times.\n* (Coming soon) Some flashy LED progress meters.\n==User Documentation==\n* [[Hardware Installation]]\n* [[Software Installation]]\n* [[Event Setup]]\n* [[FAQ]]\n\n=Dev Resources=\n* [[Source Code]] - including PC application, sensor interface firmware, and electronics CAD files.\n* [[Hardware Development]]\n* [[Feature Requests]]\n* [[Video Interface Development]]\n* [[Bugs]]\n=Community=\n* [[Community Images|Images]]\n* [[Community Videos|Videos]]','utf-8'),(185,'{| {{table}} border=\"1\" \n| align=\"center\" style=\"background:#f0f0f0;\"|\'\'\'Image\'\'\'\n| align=\"center\" style=\"background:#f0f0f0;\" width=\"400\"|\'\'\'Qty\'\'\'\n| align=\"center\" style=\"background:#f0f0f0;\"|\'\'\'Description\'\'\'\n|-\n| [[Image:OpensprintsPCB.jpg|200px|thumb|none|Opensprints PCB kit]]||1 Interface board; 1 sensor board for each roller in use||Roller sensor circuit board v2. Possibly available from opensprints.com, or make your own using OpenSprints design files.\n|}\n\n== Parts for Interface board version 2 ==\n\n{| {{table}} border=\"1\" \n| align=\"center\" style=\"background:#f0f0f0;\"|\'\'\'Image\'\'\'\n| align=\"center\" style=\"background:#f0f0f0;\" width=\"50\"|\'\'\'Qty\'\'\'\n| align=\"center\" style=\"background:#f0f0f0;\"|\'\'\'Description\'\'\'\n| align=\"center\" style=\"background:#f0f0f0;\"|\'\'\'Mfr\'\'\'\n| align=\"center\" style=\"background:#f0f0f0;\"|\'\'\'Mfr P/N\'\'\'\n| align=\"center\" style=\"background:#f0f0f0;\"|\'\'\'Supplier\'\'\'\n| align=\"center\" style=\"background:#f0f0f0;\"|\'\'\'Supplier P/N\'\'\'\n|-\n| [[Image:Arduino.jpg|200px|thumb|none|Arduino USB microcontroller board]]||1||Arduino USB board||tinker.it||Arduino Diecimila, Duemilanove, or equivalent||[http://www.sparkfun.com/commerce/product_info.php?products_id=666 sparkfun.com]||DEV-00666\n|-\n| [[Image:serpac.jpg|200px|thumb|none|Project enclosure]]||1||plastic 