to the interface board\n** moved title text to a better location\n** added label for each RJ45 1,2,3,4\n** rotated and increased size of GND and 5V labels','utf-8'),(197,'Two or more rear are sitting in the same spot at a fast RPM, to not doing anything with that would be a wasted opportunity.\n\n== Light Patterns ==\n\nRegardless of which one you go with, you will need 3 per wheel to get the full effect.\n\n=== [http://www.hokeyspokes.com/ Hokey Spokes] ===\n\n[[Image:hokeyspokes.gif|thumb|Hokey Spokes]]\n\nHokey Spokes are a pre-assembled commercial product.  With the centripetal force you will need to use \'\'\'extra springs\'\'\' to keep the batteries in place.\n\n\'\'\'Pros:\'\'\'\n\n* Beer and Waterproof\n* No Magnets\n* Patterns automatically sync on the same wheel.\n* Turning one on/off automatically does the same with any other ones on a wheel.\n\n\'\'\'Cons:\'\'\'\n* Non-programmable.\n* Text un-readable at high RPM.\n\n=== [http://www.ladyada.net/make/spokepov/ SpokePOV] ===\n\n[[Image:spokepov.gif|thumb|SpokePOV]]\n\nSpokePOV is a do-it-yourself soldering kit.\n\n\'\'\'Pros:\'\'\'\n\n* Programmable\n\n\'\'\'Cons:\'\'\'\n\n* Not Waterproof\n* Requires setting magnets\n* You need to program all three individually.\n* You need to turn one on/off all three individually.\n\n\n=== [http://www.monkeylectric.com/ MonkeyLectric] ===\n\n[[Image:monkey.jpg|thumb|MonkeyLectric]]\n\nThe MonkeyLectric light features 32 of the brightest full color LEDs available, and cutting edge visual effects.\n\n\'\'\'Pros:\'\'\'\n\n* The digital effects are instantly customizable - with on-board buttons you can choose the colors, patterns and mood to fit any situation. \n* Able to display 16 colors!! at random or you can pick the colors you want it to display.\n* Beer and Waterproof\n* No Magnets\n* 30 hours of light with 3 AAA batteries\n\n\'\'\'Cons:\'\'\'\n\n* Non-programmable.','utf-8'),(198,'TODO:\n* instructions on the wiki for ordering boards from a fab house\n* sensor assembly: images of completed sensors\n* discuss mounting sensor to roller frame\n* redo interface board:\n** fix Arduino footprint to have 2 more mounting holes. odd spacing gap is 160 mil instead of 150 mil.\n** LED controllers\n* redo sensor board:\n** convertible to 4-LED status indicator\n** smaller resistors (1/8 W or 1/4 W, standing)\n** check board dimensions\n** move mount holes of RJ45s closer to edge so it can sit lower on board.\n* firmware changes:\n** spit out build version\n** dynamically load race distance, number of rollers, ...\n** control LED progress meters\n* remote control device with LCD screen and nav keys?\nDONE:\n* make the hardware parts list page prettier\n* sensor board v2.1 changes:\n** fixed routing error for tick LED\n** added \"top\" and \"bottom\" labels\n** changed version, date\n* interface board v2.1 changes:\n** arduino sticks out too far. distance from USB-jack-edge to center of furthest header pin is 2500 mil along the length of the board. Moved the Arduino down by 200 mil.\n** changed Makefile to produce interface_board.pcb.ps instead of interface_board.ps\n** added top and bottom text\n** added holes to mount the Arduino to the interface board\n** moved title text to a better location\n** added label for each RJ45 1,2,3,4\n** rotated and increased size of GND and 5V labels','utf-8'),(199,'Development files for the Arduino are found in the main OpenSprints GitHub repository.  See the [[Source Code]] page for information on getting and contributing to the source code. Also see the related page on [[Hardware development]].\n\n==Firmware Versions==\n===Basic Messaging===\nTBD.\n===Advanced Messaging===\n* The packets are in the structure !TIME@DATA#\n* TIME is an string representing 32-bit millis().\n* DATA is a block of characters encoding one HEX nibble per byte, to which we\'ve added 128 to remain string-friendly.\n* The first data byte corresponds to the tick status at TIME The second to TIME + RACE_FRAME_LENGTH (typically 2ms here).\n* Subsequent correspond to TIME + x, where x is the index of the byte in the data section.\n* Each HEX nibble represents the tick status of each sensor during the 1-2ms period to which it corresponds.\n\n== Feature requests ==\n* TBD.','utf-8'),(200,'__NOTOC__\n\nThe PCB CAD development files are found in the main OpenSprints GitHub repository.  See the [[Source Code]] page for information on getting and contributing to the source code. Also see the related page on [[Firmware development]].\n\n== Hardware development workflow ==\n\nLinux is the recommended OS for editing the existing CAD files. The hardware source files are found in the main source code repository under the directories:\n hardware/interface_board\n hardware/roller_sensor\n\nBelow each of those directories, the CAD source files are separated by CAD tool. You want to navigate into that subdirectory via the command line to do work on the hardware design. Previous versions of the hardware were designed using [http://www.geda.seul.org/ gEDA]/[http://pcb.sourceforge.net/ pcb], [roller_sensor_gerber_barebones.zip Kicad] and [http://www.cadsoft.de/index.htm Eagle]. The frustrating but libre-licensed gEDA/pcb platform will be used for future hardware development by the main OpenSprints hardware developer(s).\n<br />\n<br />\n\nAfter making new changes to the schematic or layout, use make to clean out temporary backup files and output files from previous versions of the CAD design.\n<br />\n<br />\n\nThe command to clean out the dross is\n make clean\n\nThen the following command will generate the gerber plots, which are used by fab houses to machine the PCBs. PDF or PostScript drawings will also be generated.\n make\n\n=== Ordering barebones circuit board fabrication === \n\nAnyone can take the photoplot (gerber) files generated from the OpenSprints CAD source files to basically any PCB production company (a.k.a. fab house) and order PCBs.\n<br />\n<br />\nThe command to generate the full set of gerber files and zip them is\n make output_zip\n\n==== Ordering from barebonespcb.com ====\nSo far, [http://www.4pcb.com/ Advanced Circuits] is the company that has produced all the OpenSprints circuit boards. Advanced Circuits offers a next-day barebones PCB service ([http://www.barebonespcb.com/ barebonespcb.com]). Boards ordered via this service do not have soldermask, silkscreen, nonrectangular shapes, or other fancy features common to most PCBs. All that fanciness is unnecessary for a DIY hacker-friendly project like OpenSprints, right?\n<br />\n<br />\nFirst, zip up the top copper, bottom copper and drill gerber files.\n make output_barebones\nThese archives for v2.1 circuit boards may be downloaded here: [http://github.com/evanfarrar/opensprints/blob/822cba15320fa35e1d88ffc908398d9af2202887/hardware/interface_board/geda/interface_board_barebones_output.zip interface_board_barebones_output.zip] and [http://github.com/evanfarrar/opensprints/tree/7d6bc74c9793fad5ee060803016ca931d48fdb19/hardware/roller_sensor/eagle/roller_sensor_gerber_barebones.zip roller_sensor_gerber_barebones.zip]. Then, visit [http://www.barebonespcb.com/ barebonespcb.com]. Fill out all the information and get out your credit card. A couple issues with the website caused problems in the past. After ordering one set of PCBs, It is recommended that you delete your browser\'s cache before going back to the barebonespcb.com website to order another set of boards. Also, gEDA/pcb at one time was generating separate gerber files for unplated and plated drill holes. The barebones service is not able to make unplated holes, so now the problem is being corrected in the Makefile by making any unplated holes plated before generating the barebones zip archive.\n\n== Hardware Versions ==\n\n=== Latest version: v2.1 ===\n==== Interface board ====\n===== Changes: =====\n* Arduino placement moved so it fits better inside the enclosure.\n* Mounting holes for mounting the Arduino.\n* \"top\" and \"bottom\" text.\n* Aesthetic changes to the title text.\n===== Bugs: =====\n* TBD\n\n==== Roller sensor board ====\n===== Changes: =====\n* Sensor indicator LED wiring issue was corrected..\n* \"top\" and \"bottom\" text.\n===== Bugs: =====\n* TBD\n\n=== Previous version: v2 ===\n==== Interface board ====\n===== Changes: =====\n* Phased out UBW support.\n* Designed to fit a specific plastic project box.\n* Moved the placement of the RJ45 jacks to provide better access to the tabs.\n===== Bugs: =====\n* TBD\n\n==== Roller sensor board ====\n===== Changes: =====\n* Designed to fit a specific plastic project enclosure.\n* Added power indicator LED.\n* Moved the placement of the RJ45 jacks to provide better access to the tabs.\n===== Bugs: =====\n* Ouch! The sensor trigger indicator LED was wired incorrectly.\n\n=== First version: v1 ===\n==== Interface board ====\nThis version supported both the [http://www.schmalzhaus.com/UBW/index.html UBW] and the [http://www.arduino.cc/ Arduino] microcontroller boards.\n==== Roller sensor board ====\nWorked fine, wired correctly.','utf-8'),(201,'__NOTOC__\n\nThe PCB CAD development files are found in the main OpenSprints GitHub repository.  See the [[Source Code]] page for information on getting and contributing to the source code. Also see the related page on [[Firmware development]].\n\n== Hardware development workflow ==\n\nLinux is the recommended OS for editing the existing CAD files. The hardware source files are found in the main source code repository under the directories:\n hardware/interface_board\n hardware/roller_sensor\n\nBelow each of those directories, the CAD source files are separated by CAD tool. You want to navigate into that subdirectory via the command line to do work on the hardware design. Previous versions of the hardware were designed using [http://www.geda.seul.org/ gEDA]/[http://pcb.sourceforge.net/ pcb], [http://www.lis.inpg.fr/realise_au_lis/kicad/ Kicad] and [http://www.cadsoft.de/index.htm Eagle]. The frustrating but libre-licensed \'\'gEDA/pcb\'\' platform will be used for future hardware development by the main OpenSprints hardware developer(s).\n<br />\n<br />\n\nAfter making new changes to the schematic or layout, use make to clean out temporary backup files and output files from previous versions of the CAD design.\n<br />\n<br />\n\nThe command to clean out the dross is\n make clean\n\nThen the following command will generate the gerber plots, which are used by fab houses to machine the PCBs. PDF or PostScript drawings will also be generated.\n make\n\n=== Ordering barebones circuit board fabrication === \n\nAnyone can take the photoplot (gerber) files generated from the OpenSprints CAD source files to basically any PCB production company (a.k.a. fab house) and order PCBs.\n<br />\n<br />\nThe command to generate the full set of gerber files and zip them is\n make output_zip\n\n==== Ordering from barebonespcb.com ====\nSo far, [http://www.4pcb.com/ Advanced Circuits] is the company that has produced all the OpenSprints circuit boards. Advanced Circuits offers a next-day barebones PCB service ([http://www.barebonespcb.com/ barebonespcb.com]). Boards ordered via this service do not have soldermask, silkscreen, nonrectangular shapes, or other fancy features common to most PCBs. All that fanciness is unnecessary for a DIY hacker-friendly project like OpenSprints, right?\n<br />\n<br />\nFirst, zip up the top copper, bottom copper and drill gerber files.\n make output_barebones\n\n<br />\n<br />\nAdvanced circuits offers a web utility at [http://www.freedfm.com/ freedfm.com] for checking your design for any possible errors, such as physical dimensions incompatible machines\' abilities or possible inadvertent circuit design errors.\n\nThe barebones archives for v2.1 circuit boards may be downloaded here: [http://github.com/evanfarrar/opensprints/blob/822cba15320fa35e1d88ffc908398d9af2202887/hardware/interface_board/geda/interface_board_barebones_output.zip interface_board_barebones_output.zip] and [http://github.com/evanfarrar/opensprints/tree/7d6bc74c9793fad5ee060803016ca931d48fdb19/hardware/roller_sensor/eagle/roller_sensor_gerber_barebones.zip roller_sensor_gerber_barebones.zip]. Then, visit [http://www.barebonespcb.com/ barebonespcb.com]. Fill out all the information and get out your credit card. A couple issues with the website caused problems in the past. After ordering one set of PCBs, It is recommended that you delete your browser\'s cache before going back to the barebonespcb.com website to order another set of boards. Also, gEDA/pcb at one time was generating separate gerber files for unplated and plated drill holes. The barebones service is not able to make unplated holes, so now the problem is being corrected in the Makefile by making any unplated holes plated before generating the barebones zip archive.\n\n== Hardware Versions ==\n\n=== Latest version: v2.1 ===\n==== Interface board ====\n===== Changes: =====\n* Arduino placement moved so it fits better inside the enclosure.\n* Mounting holes for mounting the Arduino.\n* \"top\" and \"bottom\" text.\n* Aesthetic changes to the title text.\n===== Bugs: =====\n* TBD\n\n==== Roller sensor board ====\n===== Changes: =====\n* Sensor indicator LED wiring issue was corrected..\n* \"top\" and \"bottom\" text.\n===== Bugs: =====\n* TBD\n\n=== Previous version: v2 ===\n==== Interface board ====\n===== Changes: =====\n* Phased out UBW support.\n* Designed to fit a specific plastic project box.\n* Moved the placement of the RJ45 jacks to provide better access to the tabs.\n===== Bugs: =====\n* TBD\n\n==== Roller sensor board ====\n===== Changes: =====\n* Designed to fit a specific plastic project enclosure.\n* Added power indicator LED.\n* Moved the placement of the RJ45 jacks to provide better access to the tabs.\n===== Bugs: =====\n* Ouch! The sensor trigger indicator LED was wired incorrectly.\n\n=== First version: v1 ===\n==== Interface board ====\nThis version supported both the [htt