unt holes of RJ45s closer to edge so it can sit lower on board. (or don\'t. I don\'t think the jack is designed to sit lower and there is naturally some open space under the business end of the jack.)\n\nnew hardware features:\n* remote control device with LCD screen and nav keys?\n\n* firmware changes:\n** spit out build version\n** dynamically load race distance, number of rollers, ...\n** control LED progress meters\n\nDONE:\n\n* instructions on the wiki for ordering boards from a fab house\n\n* make the hardware parts list page prettier\n\n* sensor board v2.1 changes:\n** fixed routing error for tick LED\n** added \"top\" and \"bottom\" labels\n** changed version, date\n\n* interface board v2.1 changes:\n** fix Arduino footprint to have 2 more mounting holes. odd spacing gap is 160 mil instead of 150 mil.\n** arduino sticks out too far. distance from USB-jack-edge to center of furthest header pin is 2500 mil along the length of the board. Moved the Arduino down by 200 mil.\n** changed Makefile to produce interface_board.pcb.ps instead of interface_board.ps\n** added top and bottom text\n** added holes to mount the Arduino to the interface board\n** moved title text to a better location\n** added label for each RJ45 1,2,3,4\n** rotated and increased size of GND and 5V labels','utf-8'),(206,'Other questions? Need direct support? Check out the [http://www.opensprints.com/forum/ forum].\n\n== I am not a electronics dork, but I can get some people to help with the soldering and have a guy who knows Linux (and all that computer jazz).  Would you rate this project something a relative handy person could do, or is it more of an expert thing? ==\n\nSoldering the parts onto the boards requires little to no experience. Assembling the hardware is definitely something anyone who is the least bit handy can handle.\n\nModerate computer experience required to get OpenSprints running. As the software is still in development, getting things running with the computer and projector can be a little challenging. The Linux version of the PC application is currently working the best, but of course Linux is an unfamiliar platform for most. Several groups are actively working out the kinks in the Mac OS X version (see [http://opensprints.org/forum/comments.php?DiscussionID=1&page=1#Item_20]. Windows is still waiting for someone to take on that challenge. The underlying software for the software app is cross-platform; the main obstacles seem to involve setting up the serial communication between the sensor hardware as well as other minor issues.\n\nMost of the groups who have successfully used this system have been handy people who have a Linux-familiar person to help if they get stuck. The project forum is getting more and more active; the support community is finally starting to form up.\n\n== Does the interface pack give me everything i would need to display progress? ==\n\nYes and no. We have in the past built an LED progress meter for each bike. Each meter was just a row of 4 LEDs, and we basically hacked some flashers, so it looked pretty raw. We ran races outside using those LED meters without any computer. That feature is not present in the current version of the firmware in the interface device. However, the next revision of hardware will have LED meters, so that feature will be available by default.\n\n== Would I require additional software? ==\n\nAdditional software is currently required in the following cases:\n* Displaying the race progress on a projector screen for an audience or on a computer monitor for the racers. This software is a free download available on our site.\n* Changing the race distance. This software is a free download available on the Arduino site.\n\n== How do they attach to rollers and comp? ==\n\nThe sensors can be taped to the roller frame or secured with hook and loop strips or zip ties.\n\nThe magnet can be taped to the roller. I\'ve seen an instance where some people fastened a cyclo-computer magnet to the flat edge of the roller drum. see this forum post for more info:\nhttp://www.opensprints.com/forum/comments.php?DiscussionID=2\n\nEach sensor connects to the interface device with a standard ethernet cable.\n\nThe interface device mainly consists of an Arduino, which link up to the computer via USB.\n\n== What frame size of bike do you feel is the most adaptable for riders? ==\n\nNot sure. when we had just two bikes in our setup, we had two sizes of frames a - smaller one that accommodated the smallest of racers, and a larger one that the big people could fit on. we always use track frames because that\'s what is currently in vogue :)\n\n== How much would it cost to buy the sensors, magnets and all other equipment to get the info from rollers to screen? ==\n\nRough estimate... assuming you already have the expensive stuff like bikes, rollers, computer, (projector), here\'s a rough estimate for the sensor system:\n\n* interface device:\n** $35 arduino\n** $10-15 electronics components\n** $12 enclosure\n** $5 cable\n\n* for each sensor:\n** $12 electronics components\n** $5 enclosure\n** $5 cable\n\nfor each LED progress meter\n$12 electronics components\n$5 enclosure\n$5 cable\n\nAgain, that\'s a rough estimate. Also, that\'s assuming you buy generic protoboard PCBs instead of fancy OpenSprints PCBs, of which we sold sets (at cost) for $50 US incl. shipping. Basically our custom PCBs make assembly a breeze.\n\nOnce the next revision of the PCBs is finished, we are looking into selling kits, which will include all the parts for the system (except the Arduino and the cables, which are easy to come by). Not sure yet about the pricing for that.','utf-8'),(207,'__NOTOC__\n\nThe PCB CAD development files are found in the main OpenSprints GitHub repository.  See the [[Source Code]] page for information on getting and contributing to the source code. Also see the related page on [[Firmware development]].\n\n== Hardware development workflow ==\n\nLinux is the recommended OS for editing the existing CAD files. The hardware source files are found in the main source code repository under the directories:\n hardware/interface_board\n hardware/roller_sensor\n\nBelow each of those directories, the CAD source files are separated by CAD tool. You want to navigate into that subdirectory via the command line to do work on the hardware design. Previous versions of the hardware were designed using [http://www.geda.seul.org/ gEDA]/[http://pcb.sourceforge.net/ pcb], [http://www.lis.inpg.fr/realise_au_lis/kicad/ Kicad] and [http://www.cadsoft.de/index.htm Eagle]. The frustrating yet libre-licensed \'\'\'gEDA/pcb\'\'\' platform will be used for future hardware development by the main OpenSprints hardware developer(s).\n<br />\n<br />\n\nAfter making new changes to the schematic or layout, use make to clean out temporary backup files and output files from previous versions of the CAD design.\n<br />\n<br />\nThe command to clean out the dross is\n make clean\n\nThen the following command will generate the gerber plots, which are used by fab houses to machine the PCBs. PDF or PostScript drawings will also be generated.\n make\n\n=== Ordering barebones circuit board fabrication === \n\nAnyone can take the photoplot (gerber) files generated from the OpenSprints CAD source files to basically any PCB production company (a.k.a. fab house) and order PCBs.\n<br />\n<br />\nThe command to generate the full set of gerber files and zip them is\n make output_zip\n\n==== Ordering from barebonespcb.com ====\nSo far, [http://www.4pcb.com/ Advanced Circuits] is the company that has produced all the OpenSprints circuit boards. Advanced Circuits offers a next-day barebones PCB service ([http://www.barebonespcb.com/ barebonespcb.com]). Boards ordered via this service do not have soldermask, silkscreen, nonrectangular shapes, or other fancy features common to most PCBs. All that fanciness is unnecessary for a DIY hacker-friendly project like OpenSprints, right?\n<br />\n<br />\nFirst, zip up the top copper, bottom copper and drill gerber files.\n make output_barebones\n\nAdvanced circuits offers a web utility at [http://www.freedfm.com/ freedfm.com] for checking your design for any possible errors, such as physical dimensions incompatible with machines\' abilities or possible inadvertent circuit design errors.\n<br />\n<br />\n\nThe barebones archives for v2.1 circuit boards may be downloaded here: [http://github.com/evanfarrar/opensprints/blob/822cba15320fa35e1d88ffc908398d9af2202887/hardware/interface_board/geda/interface_board_barebones_output.zip interface_board_barebones_output.zip] and [http://github.com/evanfarrar/opensprints/tree/7d6bc74c9793fad5ee060803016ca931d48fdb19/hardware/roller_sensor/eagle/roller_sensor_gerber_barebones.zip roller_sensor_gerber_barebones.zip].\n<br />\n<br />\n\nThen, visit [http://www.barebonespcb.com/ barebonespcb.com]. Fill out all the information and get out your credit card. \'\'\'NB:\'\'\' A couple issues with the website caused problems in the past. After ordering one set of PCBs, It is recommended that you delete your browser\'s cache before going back to the barebonespcb.com website to order another set of boards. Also, gEDA/pcb generates separate gerber files for unplated and plated drill holes. The barebones service is not able to make unplated holes and barebonespcb.com only allow submission of one drill file. That problem has been corrected in the Makefile by \"plating\" any unplated holes before generating the barebones zip archive.\n\n== Hardware Versions ==\n\n=== Latest version: v2.1 ===\n==== Interface board ====\n===== Changes: =====\n* Arduino placement moved so it fits better inside the enclosure.\n* Mounting holes for mounting the Arduino.\n* \"top\" and \"bottom\" text.\n* Aesthetic changes to the title text.\n===== Bugs: =====\n* TBD\n\n==== Roller sensor board ====\n===== Changes: =====\n* Sensor indicator LED wiring issue was corrected..\n* \"top\" and \"bottom\" text.\n===== Bugs: =====\n* TBD\n\n=== Previous version: v2 ===\n==== Interface board ====\n===== Changes: =====\n* Phased out UBW support.\n* Designed to fit a specific plastic project box.\n* Moved the placement of the RJ45 jacks to provide better access to the tabs.\n===== Bugs: =====\n* TBD\n\n==== Roller sensor board ====\n===== Changes: =====\n* Designed to fit a specific plastic project enclosure.\n* Added power indicator LED.\n* Moved the placement of the RJ45 jacks to provide better access to the tabs.\n===== Bugs: =====\n* Ouch! The sensor trigger indicator LED was wired incorrectly.\n\n=== First version: v1 ===\n==== Interface board ====\nThis version supported both the [http://www.schmalzhaus.com/UBW/index.html UBW] and the [http://www.arduino.cc/ Arduino] microcontroller boards.\n==== Roller sensor board ====\nWorked fine, wired correctly.','utf-8'),(208,'== Essentials ==\n\n* Two to four Complete Bicycles, minus the front wheel\n* Two to four [[Bicycle Rollers]]\n* Two to four [[Fork Mounts]], preferably mounted securely to a large base surface\n* Laptop/computer with a USB port, and setup as described in [[Software Installation]]\n* Digital Projector \'\'or\'\' lots of TVs\n* A big room, a table a chair and a projection surface\n\n== Nice to have parts ==\n\n* A stage or 1 ft high platform\n* Red and Blue electrical tape\n* Red and Blue handlebar tape\n* Red and Blue heat shrink tubing for cabling\n* Two to four 5x3 plywood boards and big 15mm bolts and angle brackets (for anchoring the fork mounts)\n* loooooong projector cable\n* differently sized seatposts, spare crankset, tubes\n* pump w/ gauge\n* gaffers tape for cords\n* [[Wheel Visualizations]]\n\n== Setting up ==\n\n* clearly indicate each bike red and blue\n* put rollers on each side of the projection area, perpindicular to it\n* place fork mounts and bikes over rollers\n* set up laptop on table in view of the bikers\n* Be sure to pump up the tires to the same PSI (e.g. 100)\n\n== Race formats ==\n\n* [http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Template:16TeamBracket Complete Elimination]\n* Qualification Style: All riders race once, then race the top 8 in single elimination brackets.\n* Grudge Matches: charge per race, riders chose their opponents\n* Top Distance: racers ride for 20 seconds, highest distance wins.\n* Top Speed: ride for any amount of time, highest speed wins.\n\n== Using a projector ==\n\nSince the racers are usually facing the crowd, they can\'t see the projected display behind them.  As you might expect, a common racer request is to have monitors in front of them.  With their forehead buried in their stem, LCD screens (heavily covered in a protective Plexiglas box) might work well in between the front and rear rollers.\n\nSending the same image to multiple screens is called \'\'\'mirroring\'\'\'  This can be done with a \'\'\'VGA splitter\'\'\'.  Here are some vendors: [http://www.kvms.com/ KVMs], [http://www.networktechinc.com/ NTI], [http://www.national-tech.com/ National Technology].  Simply do a search for \'vga splitter\' to find more vendors.\n\nTo share the screen with the digital projector in Linux use this command:\n\n > xrandr --auto\n\n== References ==\n\n* [http://www.realtimesoft.com/multimon/faq.asp#Mirroring Multi-Monitor FAQ]','utf-8'),(209,'\'\'Currently the software only runs on a Linux system. If you are unfamiliar with the system this can seem a bit daunting, however there are a few tips and ideas for getting the system up and running as quick as possible.\'\'\n\n= Linux =\n== Linux as an operating system ==\n\nIf you don\'t have a machine that currently has a Linux operating system on it, running the setup from an attached USB thumbdrive with both the Linux operating system as well as the other software requirements for Opensprints is another option. One popular and straightforward operating system for Linux is [http://www.ubuntu.com Ubuntu]. \n\n==Creating a bootable Ubuntu 8.10 persistent thumbdrive for Opensprints ==\n\nThe entire Ubuntu Linux operating system as well as the other software packages can be stored on a single 2GB thumb drive and be moved to any machine with little if any changes. The persistent thumbdrive installs a special copy of ubuntu that saves all changes and software packages to the thumbdrive, so no changes are lost. If your laptop currently has a windows operating system, it will remain intact and the whole setup becomes very portable and non-intrusive.\n\nCredit for the persistent install method and additional help on installing Ubuntu can be found at [http://www.pendrivelinux.com/ubuntu-810-persistent-flash-drive-install-from-live-cd/ Pen Drive Linux].\n\n# Download the Ubuntu 8.10 ISO and burn it to a CD [[http://www.ubuntu.com/getubuntu/download]].\n# Restart your computer, booting from the Live CD (You may need to follow the next step to boot off the CD)\n# Insert a 2GB or larger USB flash drive.\n# Open terminal (Applications -> Accessories -> Terminal) and type the following into the terminal window:\n## wget pendrivelinux.com/downloads/u810/u810.sh\n## chmod +x u810.sh && sh u810.sh\n# Follow the onscreen instructions.\n# Once the script has finished, reboot your computer and follow the instructions below to set your BIOS or boot menu to boot from the USB device.\n\n===Changing the Default Boot order of your computer ===\n\nGetting a machine BIOS to boot from the USB drive will differ from computer to computer, typically with in the first 5 seconds of booting your computer the on-screen instructions on how to \"Enter Setup\" or \"Enter BIOS\" will show which key(s) to press. They are commonly F2, F12, or Delete. You will have to press this key immediately after powering on your system, it\'s easy to miss and have it load windows instead, if this happens simply reboot and try again. Once in the BIOS, the drive boot order list has to be located and change in order to boot from the USB drive first. Search through your BIOS options until you see the option to change the boot order from the current hard drive (Eg. ATA/IDE HDD) to the USB thumb drive (Eg. \"USB Mass Storage or \"External USB Device\"). Make sure to save changes before exiting the BIOS (sometimes when you exit it will prompt you for this). After leaving the BIOS, the next reboot should boot from the USB drive and bring up the Ubuntu operating system. The Ubuntu boot screen will have options for booting \"Persistent\", select this option (In practice you will just press enter twice at the ubuntu boot screen). Once you are operating in the Ubuntu system, you will need to start downloading files and packages for Opensprints. Congratulations, you are now running Ubuntu Linux off of your USB Thumb drive in a persistent state (meaning everything you do going forward will be saved). \n\n===Get the internet working===\nFirst, focus on getting your network connection to work, via either wired ethernet or wireless. Ubuntu was designed make this as simple as possible but this is beyond the scope of this document. If you are unable to get the internet to work, please consult the [http://ubuntuforums.org/search.php ubuntu forums]. Be sure to gather as much information on your hardware and network card via the hardware manuals and manufacture website etc.\n\n===Installing necessary software packages and software===\nYou will need to install a series of software packages in order to run opensprints as well as compile the nessasary fireware hex code for the Arduino controller. The easiest way to install packaged software is via Applications then Add/Remove. This GUI will allow you to search for individual package names and easily install software. It is important to enable 3rd party applications by Selecting \"All available Applications\". You will need the following applications installed. Type the  package names in the search function to find and install them.\n\n*avrdude\n*gcc-avr\n*binutils\n*avr-libc\n*make\n\n\nThese can also be installed manually by opening a command prompt (via Applications, Terminal) and typing \"sudo apt-get install gcc-avr avrdude avr-libc make\"\n\nThe following applications cannot be installed via apt:\n*download [http://shoooes.net/ Shoes]for Linux: [http://shoooes.net/dist/shoes2.run here]\n** Save it somwhere (e.g. ~/Desktop/shoes2.run)\n** Make it executable: <code>chmod 700 ~/Desktop/shoes2.run</code>\n*download the latest [http://github.com/evanfarrar/opensprints/zipball/master Opensprints software].\n** Unzip the software somewhere like ~/opensprints/\n\nNow simply run shoes by double-clicking it on your desktop, and click \"run a program\" then browse to ~/opensprints/main.rb\n\n== Programing the Arduino==\n\nThe Arduino microcontroller will need to be programmed with firmware. There are two firmware sources to choose from:\n\n# basic_msg -- programmed by Evan Farrar\n# advanced_msg --  programmed by Morgan (SF)\n# arduino-0011 -- This is the Arduino panel software that is used to compile and burn hex firmware images to arduino MCs. It is included in the Opensprints distribution linked above.\n\n===basic_message===\nOpen a terminal window and change directory to the folder, eg:\n  cd /home/user/Desktop/evanfarrar-opensprints-6184492bc1410de49c0515441dd5cdff1b8da425/firmware/arduino/basic_msg\n\nopen the basic_msg.pde with your favorite text editor (vim, nano)\n\nedit the following line:\n  int raceLengthTicks = 1400;\nThis integer needs to match the \"race_distance:\" variable set in your \'\'\'conf.yml\'\'\' file, eg. in this case it would equal \"race_distance: 1400\"  If you are not familiar with this file yet, it is the main configuration file used by opensprints and is located at the root of the OS folder. The default is 200 (200 meters), so if you are just testing hardware, setting it to something low like 20 and then making sure your conf.yml matches later might make testing easier.\nIf the integers dont equate out, you will have timing and finish errors. Getting the correct number of ticks into the hex requires a bit of figuring. \nFind your roller circumference. This is for the calculations for time and winner. \nDetermine the distance you would like to race at. This is for the animation\nAlthough the distance can be changed easily once shoes is running a race, the race will not end until the determined amount of ticks is reached. \nDetermine the amount of rotations will have to be completed to achieve the distance you want to race. \nex: if your roller circumference is 25CM, and you want to race 100 meters. The ticks to equal that distance would be 400 ticks. Your settings would look something like this:\n int raceLengthTicks = 400\n distance in Meters = 100\n roller circumference = .25 (in meters remember) \nIf your roller isnt so easily calculated. Lets say its 23CM circumference. You want to err on the short side. The race animation will quit once the distance is reached and stop counting ticks. if the ticks have not been reached, the time will not be accurate or not operate at all.\n\nNow to compile and upload your firmware to the arduino. From the firmware directory, type the \"make\" command. If that fails, you may have made a typo while editing the basic_message.pde file or some of your dependencies may be missing.\n\nIf that is successful, attach the arduino to your computer and run the command \"make upload\". If that is successful, you are ready to run opensprints.\n\n===advanced_message===\n\nDoes not require the above editing of source code. Just compile and upload your firmware to the arduino. From the firmware directory, type the \"make\" command. If that fails some of your dependencies may be missing.\n\nIf that is successful, attach the arduino to your computer and run the command \"make upload\". If that is successful, you are ready to run opensprints.\n\n== Creating a dual-boot windows/ubuntu system ==\nFor those with the hard-drive space, it is possible to install the most recent Ubuntu release (Intrepid Ibex) as a folder on your windows system. The choice of operating system will appear each time the computer is powered up, following the bios screen. This can be accomplished using a program called [http://wubi-installer.org Wubi]. \n\nA tutorial/memoir of the wubi/opensprints software installation process on an inexpensive acer laptop, as well as the problems encountered can be found [http://docs.google.com/Doc?id=dd4kx4mt_278gh78kgcq here].\n\n= Mac OS X =\n\n# Grab a copy of the latest code: http://github.com/evanfarrar/opensprints/zipball/master\n# Get the serproxy program from Arduino\'s website and extract it somewhere like the opensprints directory: http://download.berlios.de/arduino/serproxy-0.1.3-3.bin.macosx.zip\n# Install the Arduino Development suite and the USB Serial Drivers: http://arduino.cc/en/Guide/MacOSX\n# Edit the serproxy.cfg  included in opensprints\' main directory to use your arduino\'s address. There is a line that says \"serial_device1=/dev/ttyUSB0\". Change it to something like \"/dev/cu.usbserial-A9005fET\" (if you browse around in the finder you should be able to find the exact address).\n# run the serproxy program from a terminal: \"cd ~/Desktop/opensprints; ./serproxy serproxy.cfg\"\n# edit your conf.yml to use the sensor named \"network\"\n# Get the latest version of shoes and use it to open \"opensprints/main.rb\" : http://shoooes.net/dist/shoes2.dmg\n\n== Common faults ==','utf-8'),(210,'\'\'Currently the software only runs on a Linux system. If you are unfamiliar with the system this can seem a bit daunting, however there are a few tips and ideas for getting the system up and running as quick as possible.\'\'\n\n= Linux =\n== Linux as an operating system ==\n\nIf you don\'t have a machine that currently has a Linux operating system on it, running the setup from an attached USB thumbdrive with both the Linux operating system as well as the other software requirements for Opensprints is another option. One popular and straightforward operating system for Linux is [http