vice.\n\n=== Changing the Default Boot Order in BIOS ===\n\n[[Image:cmos_bios_usb_boot.jpg|right|thumb|Example: CMOS BIOS]]\n[[Image:PhoenixBIOS_boot_order.jpg|right|thumb|Example: PhoenixBIOS]]\n\nEvery computer with a motherboard includes a special chip referred to as the BIOS (Basic Input/Output System). One of the primary jobs of BIOS is to search through a prioritized list of hardware devices to find a bootable operating system.  Most of the time you are booting off a hard drive, where an operating system is installed.  For the purposes of OpenSprints, you will need to boot off a USB device.\n\n# Getting a machine BIOS to boot from the USB drive will differ from computer to computer, typically with in the first 5 seconds of booting your computer the on-screen instructions on how to \"Enter Setup\" or \"Enter BIOS\" will show which key(s) to press. They are commonly F2, F12, or Delete. You will have to press this key immediately after powering on your system, it\'s easy to miss and have it load windows instead, if this happens simply reboot and try again.\n# Once in the BIOS, the drive boot order list has to be located and change in order to boot from the USB drive first. Search through your BIOS options until you see the option to change the boot order from the current hard drive (Eg. ATA/IDE HDD) to the USB thumb drive (AKA: Removeable Devices, USB Mass Storage, External USB Device).\n# Make sure to save changes before exiting the BIOS (sometimes when you exit it will prompt you for this).\n# After leaving the BIOS, the next reboot should boot from the USB drive and bring up the Ubuntu operating system.\n# The Ubuntu boot screen will have options for booting \"Persistent\", select this option (In practice you will just press enter twice at the ubuntu boot screen).\n\nCongratulations, you are now running Ubuntu Linux off of your USB Thumb drive in a persistent state (meaning everything you do going forward will be saved).\n\n===Get the internet working===\nFirs