 Arduino connect to the PC, go to Hardware Manager and determine which COM port the Arduino is connected to.\n* Configure the port:\n** Click on the \'\'Serial\'\' radio button.\n** \'\'COM?\'\', as determined in previous step.\n** As far as I remember, everything else should be default.\n\n=== Running a fake race ===\n\nOnce the chosen terminal is configured as per the previous step, you should see a cursor with nothing going on. Type the letter \'g\' on the keyboard. Nothing should happen for a few seconds (during the countdown - \"4, 3, 2, 1, 0, go!\"). Then you should see a stream of numbers and letters filling the screen.\n\nThis is an example of what you might see in the terminal at an instant:\n<pre>\n1: 0\n2: 0\n3: 0\n4: 0\nt: 15311\n</pre>\n\nTest the hardware by waving a magnet in front of the hall effect sensor. (Turn the magnet around until the \'\'tick\'\' LED flashes. That will be the correct orientation of the magnet.)\n\nEvery time you wave a magnet in front of the hall effect sensor you will see the number following the corresponding sensor increment. So if you caused a tick on sensor 2, the following report will look like this:\n<pre>\n1: 0\n2: 1\n3: 0\n4: 0\nt: 15562\n</pre>\n\nAt this point, if all the sensors are behaving as expected, it\'s time to install and start running the PC application. Check out the page on [[Software Installation|software installation]].\n\n== Finally! Execute the Opensprints GUI ==\n\n# Simply run shoes by double-clicking it on your desktop\n# Then click \"Open an app\"\n# Browse to ~/opensprints/main.rb\n\n== Common faults ==\n\n= Mac OS X =\n\n# Grab a copy of the latest code: http://github.com/evanfarrar/opensprints/zipball/master\n# Get the serproxy program from Arduino\'s website and extract it somewhere like the opensprints directory: http://download.berlios.de/arduino/serproxy-0.1.3-3.bin.macosx.zip\n# Install the Arduino Development suite and the USB Serial Drivers: http://arduino.cc/en/Guide/MacOSX\n# Edit the serproxy.cfg  included in opensprints\' main directory to use your arduino\'s address. There is a line that says \"serial_device1=/dev/ttyUSB0\". Change it to something like \"/dev/cu.usbserial-A9005fET\" (if you browse around in the finder you should be able to find the exact address).\n# run the serproxy program from a terminal: \"cd ~/Desktop/opensprints; ./serproxy serproxy.cfg\"\n# edit your conf.yml to use the sensor named \"network\"\n# Get the latest version of shoes and use it to open \"opensprints/main.rb\" : http://shoooes.net/dist/shoes2.dmg\n\n= Windows =\n\n# Grab a copy of the latest code: http://github.com/evanfarrar/opensprints/zipball/master\n# Get the serproxy program from the Arduino [http://www.arduino.cc/en/Main/Software website] and extract it somewhere like the opensprints directory.\n# Get the Arduino Development platform and USB serial drivers: http://arduino.cc/en/Guide/Windows\n# Get shoes: http://shoooes.net/','utf-8'),(391,'\'\'Currently the software only runs on a Linux system. If you are unfamiliar with the system this can seem a bit daunting, however there are a few tips and ideas for getting the system up and running as quick as possible.\'\'\n\n= Linux =\n\nWe recommend using the Ubuntu distribution of Linux, and here are 4 ways of installing Ubuntu:\n\n# Use [http://www.pendrivelinux.com/ubuntu-810-persistent-flash-drive-install-from-live-cd/ Pen Drive Linux], aka, make a bootable 2GB USB thumb drive that you can put in any Windows computer capable of booting off a USB device.\n# [https://help.ubuntu.com/community/Installation Install Ubuntu] as your only operating system.  Use this option if you already use Linux as a desktop operating system or have an extra computer that you don\'t mind dedicating to OpenSprints.\n# [https://help.ubuntu.com/community/WindowsDualBoot Dual Boot Ubuntu and Windows].  Use this option if you have extra hard drive space to spare.\n# Use [http://wubi-installer.org Wubi] to install Ubuntu on Windows as if it were just another program.  A tutorial/memoir of the wubi/opensprints software installation process on an inexpensive acer laptop, as well as the problems encountered can be found [http://docs.google.com/Doc?id=dd4kx4mt_278gh78kgcq here].\n\nChances are that you will be promoting an event, so you don\'t want the system to fail.  With that in mind, either bring a few computers to the event as backups and use the Pen Drive method, or dedicate a laptop or two to OpenSprints and spare them from daily wear and tear.\n\n== Installing Linux ==\n\n=== Creating a bootable Ubuntu 8.10 persistent thumbdrive ===\n\n[[Image:sandisk-4gb-cruzer-u3-micro-usb-flash-drive.jpg|thumb|right|Sandisk 4GB Cruzer U3 Micro USB Flash Drive]]\n\nThe entire Ubuntu Linux operating system as well as the other software packages can be stored on a single 2GB thumb drive and be moved to any machine with little if any changes. The persistent thumbdrive installs a special copy of ubuntu that saves all changes and software packages to the thumbdrive, so no changes are lost. If your laptop currently has a windows operating system, it will remain intact and the whole setup becomes very portable and non-intrusive.\n\n\'\'\'Pen Drive Install\'\'\'\n\n[[Image:unetbootin.jpg|UNetbootin configured to install Ubuntu 8.10 Live on the E:\\ drive which is a USB device]]\n\n# Download the latest version of [http://unetbootin.sourceforge.net/ UNetbootin] \n# Insert an empty 2GB or greater Thumb drive, [http://www.u3.com/uninstall/ delete the U3 partition] if need be.\n# Run UNetbootin\n# Select the \'\'Distribution\'\' radio button, \'\'Ubuntu\'\' dropdown option, \'\'8.**_Live\'\' dropdown option\n#* \'\'\'Optional:\'\'\' You may want to consider downloading the ISO separately, that way you don\'t have to re-download if you have to do it again.\n# Select the \'\'Show all Drives\'\' checkbox, Type \'\'USB Drive\'\', Drive ??? \'\'\'NOTE:\'\'\' You will erase whatever drive letter you pick, so pick wisely.\n# Click the \'\'OK\'\' button.\n# Goto [http://unetbootin.sourceforge.net/diskimg/ http://unetbootin.sourceforge.net/diskimg/] and download one of the files (128mb.zip, 256mb.zip, or 512mb.zip) corresponding to the amount of persistent space you want (make sure the size of the persistent disk image is smaller than the free space you have on your USB drive).\n# Now extract the file \"casper.rw\" from the zip file to your USB drive.\n# Now edit D:\\syslinux.cfg (assuming D:\\ is where your USB drive is) and add in \"persistent\" at the end of the line that begins with \"append\", and save the file, so your syslinux.cfg should look something like this:\n \'\'\'BEFORE:\'\'\' append initrd=/ubninit file=/cdrom/preseed/ubuntu.seed boot=casper quiet splash --\n \'\'\'AFTER:\'\'\' append initrd=/ubninit file=/cdrom/preseed/ubuntu.seed boot=casper quiet splash \'\'\'persistent\'\'\' --\n\nCredit for the persistent install method and additional help on installing Ubuntu can be found at [https://wiki.ubuntu.com/LiveUsbPendrivePersistent Live USB Pendrive Persistent].\n\n=== Changing the Default Boot Order in BIOS ===\n\n[[Image:cmos_bios_usb_boot.jpg|right|thumb|Example: CMOS BIOS]]\n[[Image:PhoenixBIOS_boot_order.jpg|right|thumb|Example: PhoenixBIOS]]\n\nEvery computer with a motherboard includes a special chip referred to as the BIOS (Basic Input/Output System). One of the primary jobs of BIOS is to search through a prioritized list of hardware devices to find a bootable operating system.  Most of the time you are booting off a hard drive, where an operating system is installed.  For the purposes of OpenSprints, you will need to boot off a USB device.\n\n# Getting a machine BIOS to boot from the USB drive will differ from computer to computer, typically with in the first 5 seconds of booting your computer the on-screen instructions on how to \"Enter Setup\" or \"Enter BIOS\" will show which key(s) to press. They are commonly F2, F12, or Delete. You will have to press this key immediately after powering on your system, it\'s easy to miss and have it load windows instead, if this happens simply reboot and try again.\n# Once in the BIOS, the drive boot order list has to be located and change in order to boot from the USB drive first. Search through your BIOS options until you see the option to change the boot order from the current hard drive (Eg. ATA/IDE HDD) to the USB thumb drive (AKA: Removeable Devices, USB Mass Storage, External USB Device).\n# Make sure to save changes before exiting the BIOS (sometimes when you exit it will prompt you for this).\n# After leaving the BIOS, the next reboot should boot from the USB drive and bring up the Ubuntu operating system.\n# The Ubuntu boot screen will have options for booting \"Persistent\", select this option (In practice you will just press enter twice at the ubuntu boot screen).\n\nCongratulations, you are now running Ubuntu Linux off of your USB Thumb drive in a persistent state (meaning everything you do going forward will be saved).\n\n\n\n=== Establish an Internet Connection ===\n\nFirst, focus on getting your network connection to work, via either wired ethernet or wireless. Ubuntu was designed make this as simple as possible but this is beyond the scope of this document. If you are unable to get the internet to work, please consult the [http://ubuntuforums.org/search.php ubuntu forums]. Be sure to gather as much information on your hardware and network card via the hardware manuals and manufacture website etc.\n\n=== Installing necessary software packages ===\n\nThere are some software dependencies, so you will need to install a series of software packages in order to run opensprints as well as compile the necessary firmware for the Arduino controller.\n\n\'\'\'NOTE:\'\'\' If you haven\'t done so already you will need to [https://help.ubuntu.com/community/Repositories/Ubuntu add the universe repository] by uncommenting lines in /etc/apt/sources.list\n\nTo install software packages using an easy to use GUI interface:\n\n# Start and login to Ubuntu using the user you created.\n# Goto Applications --> Add / Remove\n# Select \"All available Applications\"\n# Type the package names (listed below) in the search function to find and install them.\n#* avrdude\n#* gcc-avr\n#* binutils\n#* avr-libc\n#* make\n#* gtkterm\n\nTo manually install the software packages issue the following command in a the command prompt (Applications --> Terminal):\n sudo apt-get update\n sudo apt-get install gcc-avr avrdude avr-libc make gtkterm\n\n\'\'\'NOTE:\'\'\' Avoid the temptation to upgrade existing packages, <code>sudo apt-get upgrade</code> will only fill up the free space on your USB device.\n\n=== [http://help.shoooes.net/Installing.html Install the Graphics Library, Shoes] ===\n\n[[Image:downloading_shoes.jpg|thumb|right|Commands for downloading and executing shoes.]]\n[[Image:shoes.jpg]]\n\n# Download [http://shoooes.net/dist/shoes2.run Shoes] for Linux. <code>wget http://shoooes.net/dist/shoes2.run</code>\n# Save Shoes to the desktop (ex: ~/Desktop/shoes2.run)\n# Change file permissions: <code>chmod 700 ~/Desktop/shoes2.run</code>\n# To execute Shoes double click on the desktop icon or use the command: <code>./shoes2.run</code>\n\n== Installing Opensprints Software ==\n\n# Download the latest version of the Opensprints software in [http://github.com/evanfarrar/opensprints/tarball/master tar] or [http://github.com/evanfarrar/opensprints/zipball/master zip] format from [http://github.com/evanfarrar/opensprints/tree/master github.com].\n# Untar or unzip the Opensprints software to ~/Desktop/opensprints/\n\n== Programming the Arduino==\n\n[[Image:Arduino.jpg|thumb|right|Arduino USB Board]]\n\nThe Arduino microcontroller will need to be programmed with firmware. There are two firmware sources to choose from:\n\n# basic_msg -- programmed by Evan Farrar\n# advanced_msg --  programmed by Morgan (SF)\n# [http://www.arduino.cc/en/Main/Software arduino-00**] -- This is the Arduino panel software that is used to compile and burn hex firmware images to arduino MCs. It is included in the Opensprints software distribution linked above.\n\n===basic_message===\n\nBefore we can program the Arduino, we need to answer 3 math questions:\n\n# What is the \'\'race distance\'\' in meters?\n# What is the drum / \'\'roller circumference\'\' in meters?\n# How many times does the roller have to spin in order to finish the race?\n\n\'\'\'NOTE:\'\'\' If the following math is done incorrectly it will result in timing and finish errors.\n\n\'\'\'What is the race distance in meters?\'\'\'\n\nDetermine the distance you would like to race at. This is used for the animation.\n\nThis integer needs to match the \"race_distance:\" variable set in your \'\'\'[[conf.yml]]\'\'\' file, eg. in this case it would equal \"race_distance: 1400\"  If you are not familiar with this file yet, it is the main configuration file used by opensprints and is located at the root of the OS folder. The default is 200 (200 meters), so if you are just testing hardware, setting it to something low like 20 and then making sure your conf.yml matches later might make testing easier.\n\n\'\'\'What is the drum / roller circumference in meters?\'\'\'\n\nFind your roller circumference by multiplying the roller diameter by pi and converting to meters. This is for the calculations for time and winner.  Luckily Google Calculator does this for you.\n\n \'\'\'Examples:\'\'\'\n 2.25 inch (diameter) rollers: [http://www.google.com/search?q=(pi+*+2.25+in)+in+m (pi * 2.25 in) in m] = \'\'\'0.17954202 meters\'\'\'\n 3.0 inch (diameter) rollers: [http://www.google.com/search?q=(pi+*+3.0+in)+in+m (pi * 3.0 in) in m] = \'\'\'0.23938936 meters\'\'\'\n 4.5 inch (diameter) rollers: [http://www.google.com/search?q=(pi+*+4.5+in)+in+m (pi * 4.5 in) in m] = \'\'\'0.35908404 meters\'\'\'\n\nIf your roller isnt so easily calculated. Lets say its 23CM circumference. You want to err on the short side. The race animation will quit once the distance is reached and stop counting ticks. if the ticks have not been reached, the time will not be accurate or not operate at all.\n\n\n\'\'\'How many times does the roller have to spin in order to finish the race?\'\'\'\n\nWe will refer to each full rotation a \'\'tick\'\'.  Race distance (in meters) divided by the roller circumference (in meters) will give you the total number of ticks required to finish a race.  Here are some examples using Google Calculator and the earlier numbers:\n\n200 meter race distance divided by the circumference of 2.25 inch (diameter) rollers:\n [http://www.google.com/search?q=200+m+%2F+0.17954202+m 200 m / 0.17954202 m] = \'\'\'1,113.94536 ticks\'\'\'\n200 meter race distance divided by the circumference of 3.0 inch (diameter) rollers:\n [http://www.google.com/search?q=200+m+%2F+0.23938936+m 200 m / 0.23938936 m] = \'\'\'835.45902 ticks\'\'\'\n200 meter race distance divided by the circumference of 4.5 inch (diameter) rollers:\n [http://www.google.com/search?q=200+m+%2F+0.35908404+m 200 m / 0.35908404 m] = \'\'\'556.97268 ticks\'\'\'\n\n\'\'\'Programming the Arduino with basic_message\'\'\'\n\nFinally!  Now open a terminal window and change directory to the folder.\n  cd ~/Desktop/opensprints/firmware/arduino/basic_msg\n\nopen the basic_msg.pde with your favorite text editor (vim, nano)\n\nRound off the answer to our, \'\'how many times does the roller have to spin in order to finish the race\'\' question, edit the following line:\n  int raceLengthTicks = 1400;\n\n\'\'\'NOTE:\'\'\' This can\'t be a float / decimal value, it has to be a whole number!\n\nAlthough the distance can be changed easily once shoes is running a race, the race will not end until the determined amount of ticks is reached. \n\nNow to compile and upload your firmware to the arduino:\n# Go to the firmware directory (ex: ~/Desktop/opensprints/firmware/arduino/basic_msg/)\n# Type the \'\'\'make clean\'\'\' command.\n# Type the \'\'\'make\'\'\' command.\n# Attach the Arduino to your computer.\n# Run the command \'\'\'make upload\'\'\'.\n# You are now ready to run OpenSprints!\n\n\'\'\'NOTE:\'\'\' If \'\'make\'\' fails, you may have made a typo while editing the basic_message.pde file or some of your dependencies may be missing.\n\n===advanced_message BETA===\n\n\'\'\'NOTE:\'\'\' This version is still in testing, proceed at your own risk.\n\nDoes not require the above editing of source code. Just compile and upload your firmware to the arduino. From the firmware directory, type the \"make\" command. If that fails some of your dependencies may be missing.\n\nIf that is successful, attach the arduino to your computer and run the command \"make upload\". If that is successful, you are ready to run opensprints.\n\n===  Verifying the hardware ===\n\nConnect all the hardware together: the sensors connected to the interface board with ethernet cables, the programmed Arduino mounted on the interface board, and the Arduino connected to the computer with a USB cable.\n\n=== Setup for testing under Linux ===\n# Run \'\'gtkterm\'\'\n# Configure the port (Configuration -> Port) and select the following values:\n#* Port: \'\'/dev/ttyUSB0\'\'\n#* Speed: \'\'115200\'\'\n#* Parity: \'\'none\'\'\n#* Bits: \'\'8\'\'\n#* Stopbits: \'\'1\'\'\n#* Flow Control: \'\'none\'\'\n#* End of line delay: \'\'0\'\'\n\n=== Setup for testing under Mac OS X ===\n\n=== Setup for testing under Windows ===\n\n* Install and run [http://www.chiark.greenend.org.uk/~sgtatham/putty/download.html PuTTY].\n* With the Arduino connect to the PC, go to Hardware Manager and determine which COM port the Arduino is connected to.\n* Configure the port:\n** Click on the \'\'Serial\'\' radio button.\n** \'\'COM?\'\', as determined in previous step.\n** As far as I remember, everything else should be default.\n\n=== Running a fake race ===\n\nOnce the chosen terminal is configured as per the previous step, you should see a cursor with nothing going on. Type the letter \'g\' on the keyboard. Nothing should happen for a few seconds (during the countdown - \"4, 3, 2, 1, 0, go!\"). Then you should see a stream of numbers and letters filling the screen.\n\nThis is an example of what you might see in the terminal at an instant:\n<pre>\n1: 0\n2: 0\n3: 0\n4: 0\nt: 15311\n</pre>\n\nTest the hardware by waving a magnet in front of the hall effect sensor. (Turn the magnet around until the \'\'tick\'\' LED flashes. That will be the correct orientation of the magnet.)\n\nEvery time you wave a magnet in front of the hall effect sensor you will see the number following the corresponding sensor increment. So if you caused a tick on sensor 2, the following report will look like this:\n<pre>\n1: 0\n2: 1\n3: 0\n4: 0\nt: 15562\n</pre>\n\nAt this point, if all the sensors are behaving as expected, it\'s time to install and start running the PC application. Check out the page on [[Software Installation|software installation]].\n\n== Finally! Execute the Opensprints GUI ==\n\n# Simply run shoes by double-clicking it on your desktop\n# Then click \"Open an app\"\n# Browse to ~/opensprints/main.rb\n\n== Common faults ==\n\n= Mac OS X =\n\n# Grab a copy of the latest code: http://github.com/evanfarrar/opensprints/zipball/master\n# Get the serproxy program from Arduino\'s website and extract it somewhere like the opensprints directory: http://download.berlios.de/arduino/serproxy-0.1.3-3.bin.macosx.zip\n# Install the Arduino Development suite and the USB Serial Drivers: http://arduino.cc/en/Guide/MacOSX\n# Edit the serproxy.cfg  included in opensprints\' main directory to use your arduino\'s address. There is a line that says \"serial_device1=/dev/ttyUSB0\". Change it to something like \"/dev/cu.usbserial-A9005fET\" (if you browse around in the finder you should be able to find the exact address).\n# run the serproxy program from a terminal: \"cd ~/Desktop/opensprints; ./serproxy serproxy.cfg\"\n# edit your conf.yml to use the sensor named \"network\"\n# Get the latest version of shoes and use it to open \"opensprints/main.rb\" : http://shoooes.net/dist/shoes2.dmg\n\n= Windows =\n\n# Grab a copy of the latest code: http://github.com/evanfarrar/opensprints/zipball/master\n# Get the serproxy program from the Arduino [http://www.arduino.cc/en/Main/Software website] and extract it somewhere like the opensprints directory.\n# Get the Arduino Development platform and USB serial drivers: http://arduino.cc/en/Guide/Windows\n# Get shoes: http://shoooes.net/','utf-8'),(392,'Welcome to the OpenSprints wiki!\n\nThis wiki contains community-contributed instructions for building and running OpenSprints.\n\nOther places:\n* [http://opensprints.org The OpenSprints Homepage]\n* [http://opensprints.org/news The OpenSprints Blog]\n* [http://opensprints.org/forum The OpenSprints Forum]\n* [http://github.com/evanfarrar/opensprints/tree/master The OpenSprints Developers Page]\n\n=The System=\n\nOpenSprints is a collaboratively and openly developed goldsprints solution primarily comprised of free software and source files. Most development work can be performed using free tools. The system consists of the following subsystems:\n* A USB interface and sensors for monitoring roller rotations\n** An [http://arduino.cc/en/Main/ArduinoBoardDuemilanove Arduino] is used for interfacing the PC to the sensors. The interface board is basically an Arduino-compatible shield.\n** Up to four rollers can be monitored simultaneously in the default configuration.\n*** Two status LEDs on each roller sensor display \"connected\" status and blinks once each \"revolution\".\n*** A magnet mounted on the roller drum triggers the sensor each revolution.\n* A PC providing the race display (optional)\n** Multi-platform support (Linux, Mac OS X, Windows)\n** Tournament interface with brackets, best times.\n* (Coming soon) Some flashy LED progress meters.\n==User Documentation==\n* [[Hardware Installation]]\n* [[Software Installation]]\n* [[Event Setup]]\n* [[FAQ]]\n\n=Dev Resources=\n* [[Source Code]] - including PC application, sensor interface firmware, and electronics CAD files.\n* [[Hardware Development]]\n* [[Feature Requests]]\n* [[Video Interface Development]]\n* [[Bugs]]\n=Community=\n* [[Community Images|Images]]\n* [[Community Videos|Videos]]','utf-8'),(393,'Other places:\n* [http://opensprints.org The OpenSprints Homepage]\n* [http://opensprints.org/news The OpenSprints Blog]\n* [http://opensprints.org/forum The OpenSprints Forum]\n* [http://github.com/evanfarrar/opensprints/tree/master The OpenSprints Developers Page]\n\n== Gettings Started ==\n\n\'\'\'Welcome to the OpenSprints wiki!\'\'\'\n\nThis wiki contains community-contributed instructions for building and running OpenSprints.\n\n# What do I need to buy?\n# What do I need to build?\n# What do I need to install?\n# What do I need to put on an event?\n\n==User Documentation==\n* [[Hardware Installation]]\n* [[Software Installation]]\n* [[Event Setup]]\n* [[FAQ]]\n\n=Dev Resources=\n* [[Source Code]] - including PC application, sensor interface firmware, and electronics CAD files.\n* [[Hardware Development]]\n* [[Feature Requests]]\n* [[Video Interface Development]]\n* [[Bugs]]\n=Community=\n* [[Community Images|Images]]\n* [[Community Videos|Videos]]','utf-8'),(394,'OpenSprints is a collaboratively and openly developed goldsprints solution primarily comprised of free software and source files. Most development work can be performed using free tools. The system consists of the following subsystems:\n* A USB interface and sensors for monitoring roller rotations\n** An [http://arduino.cc/en/Main/ArduinoBoardDuemilanove Arduino] is used for interfacing the PC to the sensors. The interface board is basically an Arduino-compatible shield.\n** Up to four rollers can be monitored simultaneously in the default configuration.\n*** Two status LEDs on each roller sensor display \"connected\" status and blinks once each \"revolution\".\n*** A magnet mounted on the roller drum triggers the sensor each revolution.\n* A PC providing the race display (optional)\n** Multi-platform support (Linux, Mac OS X, Windows)\n** Tournament interface with brackets, best times.\n* (Coming soon) Some flashy LED progress meters.','utf-8'),(395,'Bringing Goldsprints to the masses!  The revolutions will be digitized!\n\n== Gettings Started ==\n\n\'\'\'Welcome to the OpenSprints wiki!\'\'\'\n\nThis wiki contains community-contributed instructions for building and running OpenSprints.\n\n# What do I need to buy?\n#* [[Electronic Parts List]]\n# What do I need to build?\n#* [[Hardware Installation]]\n# What do I need to install?\n#* [[Software Installation]]\n# What do I need to put on an event?\n#* [[Event Setup]]\n# Where can I get help?\n#* [[FAQ]]\n#* [http://opensprints.org The OpenSprints Homepage]\n#* [http://opensprints.org/news The OpenSprints Blog]\n#* [http://opensprints.org/forum The OpenSprints Forum]\n#* [http://github.com/evanfarrar/opensprints/tree/master The OpenSprints Developers Page]\n\n== Dev Resources ==\n* [[System Overview]]\n* [[Source Code]] - including PC application, sensor interface firmware, and electronics CAD files.\n* [[Hardware Development]]\n* [[Feature Requests]]\n* [[Video Interface Development]]\n* [[Bugs]]\n\n== Community== \n* [[Community Images|Images]]\n* [[Community Videos|Videos]]','utf-8'),(396,'Bringing Goldsprints to the masses!  The revolutions will be digitized!\n\n== Gettings Started ==\n\n\'\'\'Welcome to the OpenSprints wiki!\'\'\'\n\nThis wiki contains community-contributed instructions for building and running OpenSprints.\n\n# What do I need to buy?\n#* [[Electronic Parts List]]\n# What do I need to build?\n#* [[Hardware Installation]]\n# What do I need to install?\n#* [[Software Installation]]\n# What do I need to put on an event?\n#* [[Event Setup]]\n#* [[Community Images]]\n#* [[Community Videos]]\n# Where can I get help?\n#* [[FAQ]]\n#* [http://opensprints.org The OpenSprints Homepage]\n#*