REDIRECT [[Fork Stands]]','utf-8'),(426,'\'\'\'Fork Stands\'\'\' are generally used to give stability to riders that haven\'t mastered riding on rollers with both wheels (or riders that have had a couple of drinks).  When a fork mount is used with rollers the majority of torque that the rider is displacing on the handlebars is translated into the fork mount.  The primary implication of this transmitting of power is that you will want the fork mount to be very sturdy and mounted firmly to ground (Note that some of the ones below mount to the rollers and not the ground).\n\n== Securing ==\n\nThere are many ways to stabilize the fork mounts.  Ideally you want something between very secure (bolting directly to the floor) and easy move (sand bags).  Using a large sheet of wood on which the rollers will sit and mounting the fork mount to it seems to work well.  Some have had success with angle brackets and bolts through the fork mounts.  Below you can see a picture of an alternative to bolts and drilling out the fork mounts.  The galvanized steel strap shown (in the link) is simply screwed to the piece of 1/2 inch thick MDF cut to 3\' by 6\'.\n[[Image:Galv_Strap.jpg|thumb|example of galv straps]]\n\n== Manufacturers ==\n\n=== Kreitler ===\n[[Image:kreitler_fork_stand.jpg|Kreitler Fork Stand]]\n\n[http://www.kreitler.com/product.php?section=product&item=accessories Kreitler]\n\n=== Minoura ===\n\n[[Image:minoura_fork_stand.jpg|Minoura Fork Stand]]\n\n[http://www.minoura.jp/index-et.html Minoura]\n\n=== Cycle-Ops ===\n\n[[Image:cycle_ops_fork_stand.jpg|Cycle-ops Fork Stand]]\n\n[http://www.cycle-ops.com/c-5-accessories.aspx Cycle-ops]','utf-8'),(427,'','utf-8'),(428,'\'\'\'Fork Stands\'\'\' are generally used to give stability to riders that haven\'t mastered riding on rollers with both wheels (or riders that have had a couple of drinks).  When a fork mount is used with rollers the majority of torque that the rider is displacing on the handlebars is translated into the fork