n handling the hall effect sensors as they are sensitive to static electricity. Note that each hall sensor has a beveled side (usually printed on as well). This side should be soldered to face away from the magnet as it passes by. \n* Consider using different colored LED\'s for the \"tick\" indicator for each board.\n* Good through-hole soldering tutorial provided by [http://www.sparkfun.com/commerce/tutorial_info.php?tutorials_id=106 SparkFun].\n\n== Assembly ==\n\n=== USB Interface (Main) Board ===\n\nSee [[Main Board]]\n\n=== Sensor Boards ===\n\n Each bike requires a separate board.\n\nSee [[Sensor Boards]]\n\n== What\'s Next? ==\n\nNow that your hardware is fully assembled you need to install two things:\n# [[Software_Installation#Programing_the_Arduino|Firmware]] on the Arduino USB Board.\n# [[Software_Installation#basic_message|Software]] on a computer or USB Thumb drive.','utf-8'),(504,'#REDIRECT [[Soldering Tips]]','utf-8'),(505,'#REDIRECT [[Soldering Tips]]','utf-8'),(506,'\'\'\'In order of priority:\'\'\'\n# Windows support, we should be able to read off of a CDC device without blocking the whole thread\n# Killing off the buffer overrun. This could be solved a number of ways, please voice your opinions\n## moving game logic into the UBW, asking it occasionally for statistics in summary format.\n## a second buffer to read info off of the ubw quickly in a dedicated thread, possibly listening to interrupts  \n# Increase tick granularity, real races can have rpms higher than a centisecond.  \'\'What is the range of actual values observed for roller speed in rotations/second?\'\'\n# Rearchitect race data structure to keep a complete record of the race -- all times at which a bike sent a tick.  This will be used to support secondary calculations like power, and will provide easier access for graphing the data in more flexible ways.\n# Integrate new FW packet format into Ruby data collection setup -- start using a complete race representation rather than just \"distance accumulated\"\n\nTest entry by DH support\n\n== See Also ==\n\n* [[Feature Requests]]','utf-8'),(507,'== Software ==\n\n# Sounds: race start, racer finish, overall race finish\n# MPH added to game interface: current MPH per racer, max MPH per racer, average MPH per racer.\n# Custom backgrounds\n# Configuration file would ask for Roller Diameter (inches or centimeters) instead of Circumference and then the program would calculate circumference on its own using Diameter * PI with the appropriate unit conversion.\n# If the race distance was changed on saving the configuration file a new version of firmware would be automatically created and uploaded (for basic_msg).\n# Configuration file would default to basic_msg until advanced_msg was stable.\n# Put checkboxes next to each of the rollers that make the roller inputboxes active or inactive (instead of the No bike button).\n# Dump to an Error Log instead of relying on Alt-/ for troubleshooting.\n\n== Hardware ==\n\n# Printable schematic outlines for cutting away at the [[Main Board]] and [[Sensor Board]] enclosures / boxes.\n# Extra sensor board to come with kit to be built and used as a backup on race nights.  As an alternative to having to fix a board during a race, it would be nice to just swap out the unit.\n# Big [[OpenSprints]] logo sticker (including website URL) to fit on the top of the [[Main Board]] enclosure.\n# Just for effect, Light up [[Main Board]] enclosure like a computer case.\n# Complete kits similar to [http://www.adafruit.com/index.php?main_page=index&cPath=6 Spoke POV] whereas directions are online.\n\n== Web Services ==\n\n# Race result uploads for each city.\n# Race event listings.\n# Press Kit section on website for reporters and columnists.\n\n== Other ==\n\n# Logo\n# Stickers\n\n== See Also ==\n\n* [[Bugs]]','utf-8'),(508,'\'\'\'Fork Stands\'\'\' are generally used to give stability to riders that haven\'t mastered riding on rollers with both wheels (or riders that have had a couple of drinks).  When a fork mount is used with rollers the majority of torque that the rider is displacing on the handlebars is translated into the fork mount.  The primary implication of this transmitting of power is that you will want the fork mount to be very sturdy and mounted firmly to ground (Note that some of the ones below mount to the rollers and not the ground).\n\n== Securing ==\n\n=== Galvanized Steel Straps ===\n\n[[Image:Galv_Strap.jpg|thumb|right|example of galv straps]]\n\nThere are many ways to stabilize the fork mounts.  Ideally you want something between very secure (bolting directly to the floor) and easy move (sand bags).  Using a large sheet of wood on which the rollers will sit and mounting the fork mount to it seems to work well.  Some have had success with angle brackets and bolts through the fork mounts.  Below you can see a picture of an alternative to bolts and drilling out the fork mounts.  The galvanized steel strap shown (in the link) is simply screwed to the piece of 1/2 inch thick MDF cut to 3\' by 6\'.\n\n=== Square U-Bolts ===\n\n[[Image:square_u_bolts.jpg|thumb|right|Square U-Bolts]]\n\n== Manufacturers ==\n\n=== Kreitler ===\n[[Image:kreitler_fork_stand.jpg|Kreitler Fork Stand]]\n\n[http://www.kreitler.com/product.php?section=product&item=accessories Kreitler]\n\n=== Minoura ===\n\n[[Image:minoura_fork_stand.jpg|Minoura Fork Stand]]\n\n[http://www.minoura.jp/index-et.html Minoura]\n\n=== Cycle-Ops ===\n\n[[Image:cycle_ops_fork_stand.jpg|Cycle-ops Fork Stand]]\n\n[http://www.cycle-ops.com/c-5-accessories.aspx Cycle-ops]\n\n== See Also ==\n\n* [[Bicycle Rollers]]','utf-8'),(509,'== Tools required ==\n*soldering iron with fine point\n*electronic solder, the finer gauge the better\n*pair of small angle cutters\n*Soldering vise or clamp. This is to hold the work off the table.\n== Soldering breakaway headers ==\n*The breakaway headers are very sensitive to heat. When soldering in the pins, work fast or the plastic casing will melt around the pin causing it to lean or tilt.\n* Hold the board in your vise with the downside facing you and as close to parallel with the ground as possible. This will allow the solder to run down the pin when we start adding it. \n* It is never a good idea to solder with the board attached. I suggest tacking one pin per bank to start with and then removing to board to finish. Touch a hot soldering iron to the top of one of the middle pins in any of the rows. Immediately touch the solder to the point where the iron and the pin meet, it will melt immediately and puddle at the base of the pin. Most of the other soldering done on this project can be done by waiting for the pin to be hot enough to melt the solder. If you wait for the pin to be hot enough to melt the solder instead of using the irons tip, the pin will also melt the plastic header holding it in place and wilt. The pins are small enough they will require very little solder. Tack the middle pin on each row and then flip the board over. Firmly grasp the sides of the Arduino and pull it from the main board. The two should seperate leaving just the headers attached. Finish soldering in the remaining pins in the same manner. Work quickly and just touch the tip for a second before adding the solder to the connection.\n\n== See Also ==\n\n* [[Hardware Assembly]]','utf-8'),(510,'Other questions? Need direct support? Check out the [http://www.opensprints.com/forum/ forum].\n\n== I am not a electronics dork, but I can get some people to help with the soldering and have a guy who knows Linux (and all that computer jazz).  Would you rate this project something a relative handy person could do, or is it more of an expert thing? ==\n\nSoldering the parts onto the boards requires little to no experience. Assembling the hardware is definitely something anyone who is the least bit handy can handle.\n\nModerate computer experience required to get OpenSprints running. As the software is still in development, getting things running with the computer and projector can be a little challenging. The Linux version of the PC application is currently working the best, but of course Linux is an unfamiliar platform for most. Several groups are actively working out the kinks in the Mac OS X version (see [http://opensprints.org/forum/comments.php?DiscussionID=1&page=1#Item_20]. Windows is still waiting for someone to take on that challenge. The underlying software for the software app is cross-platform; the main obstacles seem to involve setting up the serial communication between the sensor hardware as well as other minor issues.\n\nMost of the groups who have successfully used this system have been handy people who have a Linux-familiar person to help if they get stuck. The project forum is getting more and more active; the support community is finally starting to form up.\n\n== Does the interface pack give me everything i would need to display progress? ==\n\nYes and no. We have in the past built an LED progress meter for each bike. Each meter was just a row of 4 LEDs, and we basically hacked some flashers, so it looked pretty raw. We ran races outside using those LED meters without any computer. That feature is not present in the current version of the firmware in the interface device. However, the next revision of hardware will have LED meters, so that feature will be available by default.\n\n== Would I require additional software? ==\n\nAdditional software is currently required in the following cases:\n* Displaying the race progress on a projector screen for an audience or on a computer monitor for the racers. This software is a free download available on our site.\n* Changing the race distance. This software is a free download available on the Arduino site.\n\n== How do they attach to rollers and comp? ==\n\nThe sensors can be taped to the roller frame or secured with hook and loop strips or zip ties.\n\nThe magnet can be taped to the roller. I\'ve seen an instance where some people fastened a cyclo-computer magnet to the flat edge of the roller drum. see this forum post for more info:\nhttp://www.opensprints.com/forum/comments.php?DiscussionID=2\n\nEach sensor connects to the interface device with a standard ethernet cable.\n\nThe interface device mainly consists of an Arduino, which link up to the computer via USB.\n\n== What frame size of bike do you feel is the most adaptable for riders? ==\n\nNot sure. when we had just two bikes in our setup, we had two sizes of frames a - smaller one that accommodated the smallest of racers, and a larger one that the big people could fit on. we always use track frames because that\'s what is currently in vogue :)\n\n== How much would it cost to buy the sensors, magnets and all other equipment to get the info from rollers to screen? ==\n\nRough estimate... assuming you already have the expensive stuff like bikes, rollers, computer, (projector), here\'s a rough estimate for the sensor system:\n\n* interface device:\n** $35 arduino\n** $10-15 electronics components\n** $12 enclosure\n** $5 cable\n\n* for each sensor:\n** $12 electronics components\n** $5 enclosure\n** $5 cable\n\nfor each LED progress meter\n$12 electronics components\n$5 enclosure\n$5 cable\n\nAgain, that\'s a rough estimate. Also, that\'s assuming you buy generic protoboard PCBs instead of fancy OpenSprints PCBs, of which we sold sets (at cost) for $50 US incl. shipping. Basically our custom PCBs make assembly a breeze.\n\nOnce the next revision of the PCBs is finished, we are looking into selling kits, which will include all the parts for the system (except the Arduino and the cables, which are easy to come by). Not sure yet about the pricing for that.\n\n== See Also ==\n\n* [[Bugs]]\n* [[Feature Requests]]\n* [http://opensprints.org The OpenSprints Homepage]\n* [http://opensprints.org/news The OpenSprints Blog]\n* [http://opensprints.org/forum The OpenSprints Forum]','utf-8'),(511,'\n== AZ Fixed ==\n\n* http://www.flickr.com/photos/suicideking15/3167678197/\n* http://www.flickr.com/photos/suicideking15/3167678347/in/photostream/\n* http://www.flickr.com/photos/suicideking15/3167678527/in/photostream/\n* http://www.flickr.com/photos/suicideking15/3168510430/in/photostream/\n* http://www.flickr.com/photos/suicideking15/3168510572/in/photostream/\n* http://www.flickr.com/photos/suicideking15/3167679009/in/photostream/\n* http://www.flickr.com/photos/suicideking15/3201966623/in/photostream/\n* http://www.flickr.com/photos/suicideking15/3202813730/in/photostream/\n* http://www.flickr.com/photos/suicideking15/3201966845/in/photostream/\n* http://www.flickr.com/photos/suicideking15/3205064490/in/photostream/\n\n== See Also ==\n\n* [[Community Videos]]','utf-8'),(512,'* http://vimeo.com/2236719\n* http://www.flickr.com/photos/johnprolly/2868583231/\n* http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HQLUd3tsY0Y\n\n== See Also ==\n\n* [[Community Photos]]','utf-8'),(513,'* http://vimeo.com/2236719\n* http://www.flickr.com/photos/johnprolly/2868583231/\n* http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HQLUd3tsY0Y\n\n== See Also ==\n\n* [[Community Images]]','utf-8'),(514,'Two or more rear wheels are sitting in the same spot at a very high RPM, to not doing anything with that would be a wasted opportunity.\n\n== Light Patterns ==\n\nRegardless of which one you go with, you will need 3 per wheel to get the full effect.\n\n=== [http://www.hokeyspokes.com/ Hokey Spokes] ===\n\n[[Image:hokeyspokes.gif|thumb|Hokey Spokes]]\n\nHokey Spokes are a pre-assembled commercial product.  With the centripetal force you will need to use \'\'\'extra springs\'\'\' to keep the batteries in place.\n\n\'\'\'Pros:\'\'\'\n\n* Beer and Waterproof\n* No Magnets\n* Patterns automatically sync on the same wheel.\n* Turning one on/off automatically does the same with any other ones on a wheel.\n\n\'\'\'Cons:\'\'\'\n* Non-programmable.\n* Text un-readable at high RPM.\n\n=== [http://www.ladyada.net/make/spokepov/ SpokePOV] ===\n\n[[Image:spokepov.gif|thumb|SpokePOV]]\n\nMuch like [[OpenSprints]] SpokePOV is a do-it-yourself soldering kit.\n\n\'\'\'Pros:\'\'\'\n\n* Programmable\n\n\'\'\'Cons:\'\'\'\n\n* Not Waterproof\n* Requires setting magnets\n* You need to program all three individually.\n* You need to turn one on/off all three individually.\n\n== See Also ==\n\n* [[Event Setup]]\n\n=== [http://www.monkeylectric.com/ MonkeyLectric] ===\n\n[[Image:monkey.jpg|thumb|MonkeyLectric]]\n\nThe MonkeyLectric light features 32 of the brightest full color LEDs available, and cutting edge visual effects.\n\n\'\'\'Pros:\'\'\'\n\n* The digital effects are instantly customizable - with on-board buttons you can choose the colors, patterns and mood to fit any situation. \n* Able to display 16 colors!! at random or you can pick the colors you want it to display.\n* Beer and Waterproof\n* No Magnets\n* 30 hours of light with 3 AAA batteries\n\n\'\'\'Cons:\'\'\'\n\n* Non-programmable.','utf-8'),(515,'Two or more rear wheels are sitting in the same spot at a very high RPM, to not doing anything with that would be a wasted opportunity.\n\n== Light Patterns ==\n\nRegardless of which one you go with, you will need 3 per wheel to get the full effect.\n\n=== [http://www.hokeyspokes.com/ Hokey Spokes] ===\n\n[[Image:hokeyspokes.gif|thumb|Hokey Spokes]]\n\nHokey Spokes are a pre-assembled commercial product.  With the centripetal force you will need to use \'\'\'extra springs\'\'\' to keep the batteries in place.\n\n\'\'\'Pros:\'\'\'\n\n* Beer and Waterproof\n* No Magnets\n* Patterns automatically sync on the same wheel.\n* Turning one on/off automatically does the same with any other ones on a wheel.\n\n\'\'\'Cons:\'\'\'\n* Non-programmable.\n* Text un-readable at high RPM.\n\n=== [http://www.ladyada.net/make/spokepov/ SpokePOV] ===\n\n[[Image:spokepov.gif|thumb|SpokePOV]]\n\nMuch like [[OpenSprints]] SpokePOV is a do-it-yourself soldering kit.\n\n\'\'\'Pros:\'\'\'\n\n* Programmable\n\n\'\'\'Cons:\'\'\'\n\n* Not Waterproof\n* Requires setting magnets\n* You need to program all three individually.\n* You need to turn one on/off all three individually.\n\n=== [http://www.monkeylectric.com/ MonkeyLectric] ===\n\n[[Image:monkey.jpg|thumb|MonkeyLectric]]\n\nThe MonkeyLectric light features 32 of the brightest full color LEDs available, and cutting edge visual effects.\n\n\'\'\'Pros:\'\'\'\n\n* The digital effects are instantly customizable - with on-board buttons you can choose the colors, patterns and mood to fit any situation. \n* Able to display 16 colors!! at random or you can pick the colors you want it to display.\n* Beer and Waterproof\n* No Magnets\n* 30 hours of light with 3 AAA batteries\n\n\'\'\'Cons:\'\'\'\n\n* Non-programmable.\n\n== See Also ==\n\n* [[Event Setup]]','utf-8'),(516,'The PCB CAD development files are found in the main OpenSprints GitHub repository.  See the [[Source Code]] page for information on getting and contributing to the source code. Also see the related page on [[Firmware development]].\n\n== Hardware development workflow ==\n\nLinux is the recommended OS for editing the existing CAD files. The hardware source files are found in the main source code repository under the directories:\n hardware/interface_board\n hardware/roller_sensor\n\nBelow each of those directories, the CAD source files are separated by CAD tool. You want to navigate into that subdirectory via the command line to do work on the hardware design. Previous versions of the hardware were designed using [http://www.geda.seul.org/ gEDA]/[http://pcb.sourceforge.net/ pcb], [http://www.lis.inpg.fr/realise_au_lis/kicad/ Kicad] and [http://www.cadsoft.de/index.htm Eagle]. The frustrating yet libre-licensed \'\'\'gEDA/pcb\'\'\' platform will be used for future hardware development by the main OpenSprints hardware developer(s).\n<br />\n<br />\n\nAfter making new changes to the schematic or layout, use make to clean out temporary backup files and output files from previous versions of the CAD design.\n<br />\n<br />\nThe command to clean out the dross is\n make clean\n\nThen the following command will generate the gerber plots, which are used by fab houses to machine the PCBs. PDF or PostScript drawings will also be generated.\n make\n\n=== Ordering barebones circuit board fabrication === \n\nAnyone can take the photoplot (gerber) files generated from the OpenSprints CAD source files to basically any PCB production company (a.k.a. fab house) and order PCBs.\n<br />\n<br />\nThe command to generate the full set of gerber files and zip them is\n make output_zip\n\n==== Ordering from barebonespcb.com ====\nSo far, [http://www.4pcb.com/ Advanced Circuits] is the company that has produced all the OpenSprints circuit boards. Advanced Circuits offers a next-day barebones PCB service ([http://www.barebonespcb.com/ barebonespcb.com]). Boards ordered via this service do not have soldermask, silkscreen, nonrectangular shapes, or other fancy features common to most PCBs. All that fanciness is unnecessary for a DIY hacker-friendly project like OpenSprints, right?\n<br />\n<br />\nFirst, zip up the top copper, bottom copper and drill gerber files.\n make output_barebones\n\nAdvanced circuits offers a web utility at [http://www.freedfm.com/ freedfm.com] for checking your design for any possible errors, such as physical dimensions incompatible with machines\' abilities or possible inadvertent circuit design errors.\n<br />\n<br />\n\nThe barebones archives for v2.1 circuit boards may be downloaded here: [http://github.com/evanfarrar/opensprints/blob/822cba15320fa35e1d88ffc908398d9af2202887/hardware/interface_board/geda/interface_board_barebones_output.zip interface_board_barebones_output.zip] and [http://github.com/evanfarrar/opensprints/tree/7d6bc74c9793fad5ee060803016ca931d48fdb19/hardware/roller_sensor/eagle/roller_sensor_gerber_barebones.zip roller_sensor_gerber_barebones.zip].\n<br />\n<br />\n\nThen, visit [http://www.barebonespcb.com/ barebonespcb.com]. Fill out all the information and get out your credit card. \'\'\'NB:\'\'\' A couple issues with the website caused problems in the past. After ordering one set of PCBs, It is recommended that you delete your browser\'s cache before going back to the barebonespcb.com website to order another set of boards. Also, gEDA/pcb generates separate gerber files for unplated and plated drill holes. The barebones service is not able to make unplated holes and barebonespcb.com only allow submission of one drill file. That problem has been corrected in the Makefile by \"plating\" any unplated holes before generating the barebones zip archive.\n\n== Hardware Versions ==\n\n=== Latest version: v2.1 ===\n==== Interface board ====\n===== Changes: =====\n* Arduino placement moved so it fits better inside the enclosure.\n* Mounting holes for affixing the Arduino to the board with small nuts and bolts.\n* \"top\" and \"bottom\" labels.\n* Aesthetic changes to the title text.\n\n===== Bugs: =====\n* TBD\n\n==== Roller sensor board ====\n===== Changes: =====\n* Sensor indicator LED wiring issue was corrected.\n* \"top\" and \"bottom\" labels.\n\n===== Bugs: =====\n* TBD\n\n=== Previous version: v2 ===\n==== Interface board ====\n===== Changes: =====\n* Phased out UBW support.\n* Designed to fit a specific plastic project box.\n* Moved the placement of the RJ45 jacks to provide better access to the tabs.\n===== Bugs: =====\n* TBD\n\n==== Roller sensor board ====\n===== Changes: =====\n* Designed to fit a specific plastic project enclosure.\n* Added power indicator LED.\n* Moved the placement of the RJ45 jacks to provide better access to the tabs.\n===== Bugs: =====\n* Ouch! The sensor trigger indicator LED was wired incorrectly.\n\n=== First version: v1 ===\n==== Interface board ====\nThis version supported both the [http://www.schmalzhaus.com/UBW/index.html UBW] and the [http://www.arduino.cc/ Arduino] microcontroller boards.\n\n\'\'\'NOTE:\'\'\' [[V1 interface board rework]]\n\n==== Roller sensor board ====\nWorked fine, wired correctly.','utf-8'),(517,'[[Image:Rework.jpg|250px|thumb|right|jumper wire attached for bikes 1&2]]\n\nVersion2 (V2) of the opensprints PCB,(first run only) requires a small modification for operation with the piggyback board and ethernet jacks.The current code uploaded to the Arduino calls for two separate inputs from the sensor and this board only supplies one. Each bike attached will require a jumper wire from the digital input pin and that bikes corresponding jack. The jumper should be attached adjacent to each corresponding pin on the Arduino and the third pin from the left on EACH input jack. The other signals including power supply and ground are already routed via the board. \'\'If you can see a trace on the board that already makes this connection, this rework is unnecessary.\'\' \n\n== See Also ==\n\n* [[Hardware Development]]','utf-8'),(518,'<code>\n<br># == Choose a Sensor\n<br># Which sensor type you will be using?\n<br># basic_message_arduino - the main sensor type for racing\n<br># advanced_message_arduino - for debugging without hall effect boards\n<br># mock - for debugging without a sensor\n<br>sensor:\n<br>  type: advanced_message_arduino\n<br># Device is where the UBW is located in your system, usually:\n<br>#   Mac OS X: /dev/tty.usbmodem0000103D1\n<br>#   Linux: /dev/ttyUSB0\n<br>#   Windows: com6\n<br>  device: /dev/ttyUSB0\n<br>\n<br># == Choose a Track\n<br># What display would you like?\n<br>#   progress_bars - the classic race window\n<br>#   circle_track - the *actual* classic race window (experimental)\n<br>track: progress_bars\n<br>\n<br># how long the race should be, in meters\n<br>race_distance: 200\n<br>\n<br># the size of each roller, in meters\n<br>roller_circumference: 1.0\n<br>\n<br>#the title displayed\n<br>title: OpenSprints\n<br>\n<br>#the measurement system displayed: standard or metric\n<br>units: standard\n<br>#units: metric\n<br>\n<br>\n<br># The list of racers\' colors. Supports from 1-4 racers.\n<br># Provide as many colors as you want racers.\n<br># Can be in any format shoes understands:\n<br># e.g.: \"red\" or \"#FF0000\" or \"rgb(255,0,0)\"\n<br>bikes:\n<br>- red\n<br>- blue\n</code>\n\n== See Also ==\n\n* [[Software Installation]]','utf-8'),(519,'==Trailing whitespace==\nLuckily, all the development for the OpenSprints system can be done under Linux. Prior to the switchover from UBW to Arduino, using MPLAB in Windows to develop for the UBW caused headaches with git. In our case, trailing whitespace is introduced in some of the output files that are generated by the MPLAB C18 build process. Git throws an error whenever a file being committed has trailing whitespace. Removing the trailing whitespace would be the optimal solution. However, saving time can be more important than file size in the repository, and a solution like this hack might be in order:\n\nin .git/hooks/pre-commit, comment the following lines:\n\n #	    if (/\\s$/) {\n #		bad_line(\"trailing whitespace\", $_);\n #	    }\n #	    if (/^\\s* \\t/) {\n #		bad_line(\"indent SP followed by a TAB\", $_);\n #	    }\n== Commands ==\nWhen working on a development branch apart from the master branch, these commands seem to get the job done.\n=== Clone: ===\n git clone git@github.com:lukeorland/opensprints.git /home/orluke/workspace/opensprints\n=== Checkout the remote nopc branch into the new local branch called nopc: ===\n git checkout origin/nopc -b nopc\n=== Push changes: ===\n==== commit local changes ====\n git commit\n==== pull from the origin to get up-to-date. ====\n git pull\n==== push local commit to the origin ====\n git push\n=== Do not use the following command. It does not update the remote repo.===\n git push origin origin/nopcNEW\n\n== See Also ==\n\n* [[Source Code]]','utf-8'),(520,'OpenSprints is a collaboratively and openly developed goldsprints solution primarily comprised of free software and source files. Most development work can be performed using free tools. The system consists of the following subsystems:\n* A [[USB interface board]] and [[roller board sensors]] for monitoring roller rotations\n** An [http://arduino.cc/en/Main/ArduinoBoardDuemilanove Arduino] is used for interfacing the PC to the sensors. The interface board is basically an Arduino-compatible shield.\n** Up to four rollers can be monitored simultaneously in the default configuration.\n*** Two status LEDs on each roller sensor display \"connected\" status and blinks once each \"revolution\".\n*** A magnet mounted on the roller drum triggers the sensor each revolution.\n* A PC providing the race display (optional)\n** Multi-platform support (Linux, Mac OS X, Windows)\n** Tournament interface with brackets, best times.\n* (Coming soon) Some flashy LED progress meters.','utf-8'),(521,'=== USB Interface (Main) Board ===\n\nThe USB interface board is basically an Arduino piggyback board that provides a safe and convenient interconnect for the sensors. Ethernet cables are used to connect the sensors to the Arduino.\n\n==== Notes ====\n\n* The breakaway headers are very sensitive to heat. When soldering in the pins, work fast or the plastic casing will melt around the pin causing it to lean or tilt.\n* The top of the interface/piggyback board is the side that has text.\n\n==== Assembly ====\n[[Image:broken_male_header_pins.jpg|thumb|none|400px]]\n[[Image:male_header_pins_closeup.jpg|thumb|none|400px]]\n\n# Break the male breakaway headers into two 6-position strips and two 8-position strips.\n# Use the Arduino board to align the breakaway header on the piggyback board. Connect the male header pins\' longer sides to the female pins on the Arduino. With the top of the piggyback board facing the top of the Arduino, press the Arduino into the piggyback board so that the shorter sides of the male pins enter the corresponding holes on the piggyback board. Ensure that all pins align before pressing the Arduino onto the piggyback board. Then tack the end pins on each strip quickly. This will hold the strips in place firm enough for you to remove the Arduino and finish soldering the remaining pins.\n# Seat the Arduino on the interface board. NB: The OpenSprints system is compatible with multiple versions of the Arduino USB device. See the [[electronics parts list]] for more info.\n# Solder RJ45 jacks to the piggyback board, one for each roller.\n# Affix the USB interface board to the bottom of the SERPAC C-6 project box with four machine screws.\n# (Optionally) cut the face plates of the project box to make openings for the USB jack and the RJ45 jack(s), and slide the face plates into place on the project box. Alternatively, omit this step.  Here are the drawings for the parts if you wanted to get them cut:\n#* Enclosure: [http://www.serpac.com/Products/Aseries/a-31.aspx Click on the User Prints tab]\n#* Ethernet Jack: [http://catalog.tycoelectronics.com/TE/bin/TE.Connect?C=1&M=BYPN&TCPN=5555164-1&RQPN=5555164-1 Click on the Product Drawings]\n#* Arduino Board:[http://arduino.cc/en/Main/ArduinoBoardDuemilanove Schematic & Reference Design]\n\n[[Image:Interface board headers.JPG|thumb|none|400px]]\n[[Image:Interface board unmounted.JPG|thumb|none|400px]]\n[[Image:Interface board mounted above 1.jpg|thumb|none|400px]]\n[[Image:Interface board mounted side 1.jpg|thumb|none|400px]]','utf-8'),(522,'The \'\'\'Main Board\'\'\', aka the \'\'USB interface board\'\', is basically an Arduino piggyback board that provides a safe and convenient interconnect for the sensors. Ethernet cables are used to connect the sensors to the Arduino.\n\n== Notes ==\n\n* The breakaway headers are very sensitive to heat. When soldering in the pins, work fast or the plastic casing will melt around the pin causing it to lean or tilt.\n* The top of the interface/piggyback board is the side that has text.\n\n== Assembly ==\n\n[[Image:broken_male_header_pins.jpg|thumb|none|400px]]\n[[Image:male_header_pins_closeup.jpg|thumb|none|400px]]\n\n# Break the male breakaway headers into two 6-position strips and two 8-position strips.\n# Use the Arduino board to align the breakaway header on the piggyback board. Connect the male header pins\' longer sides to the female pins on the Arduino. With the top of the piggyback board facing the top of the Arduino, press the Arduino into the piggyback board so that the shorter sides of the male pins enter the corresponding holes on the piggyback board. Ensure that all pins align before pressing the Arduino onto the piggyback board. Then tack the end pins on each strip quickly. This will hold the strips in place firm enough for you to remove the Arduino and finish soldering the remaining pins.\n# Seat the Arduino on the interface board. NB: The OpenSprints system is compatible with multiple versions of the Arduino USB device. See the [[electronics parts list]] for more info.\n# Solder RJ45 jacks to the piggyback board, one for each roller.\n# Affix the USB interface board to the bottom of the SERPAC C-6 project box with four machine screws.\n# (Optionally) cut the face plates of the project box to make openings for the USB jack and the RJ45 jack(s), and slide the face plates into place on the project box. Alternatively, omit this step.  Here are the drawings for the parts if you wanted to get them cut:\n#* Enclosure: [http://www.serpac.com/Products/Aseries/a-31.aspx Click on the User Prints tab]\n#* Ethernet Jack: [http://catalog.tycoelectronics.com/TE/bin/TE.Connect?C=1&M=BYPN&TCPN=5555164-1&RQPN=5555164-1 Click on the Product Drawings]\n#* Arduino Board:[http://arduino.cc/en/Main/ArduinoBoardDuemilanove Schematic & Reference Design]\n\n[[Image:Interface board headers.JPG|thumb|none|400px]]\n[[Image:Interface board unmounted.JPG|thumb|none|400px]]\n[[Image:Interface board mounted above 1.jpg|thumb|none|400px]]\n[[Image:Interface board mounted side 1.jpg|thumb|none|400px]]','utf-8'),(523,'\'\'Currently the software only runs on a Linux system. If you are unfamiliar with the system this can seem a bit daunting, however there are a few tips and ideas for getting the system up and running as quick as possible.\'\'\n\n= Linux =\n\nWe recommend using the Ubuntu distribution of Linux, and here are 4 ways of installing Ubuntu:\n\n# Use [http://www.pendrivelinux.com/ubuntu-810-persistent-flash-drive-install-from-live-cd/ Pen Drive Linux], aka, make a bootable 2GB USB thumb drive that you can put in any Windows computer capable of booting off a USB device.\n# [https://help.ubuntu.com/community/Installation Install Ubuntu] as your only operating system.  Use this option if you already use Linux as a desktop operating system or have an extra computer that you don\'t mind dedicating to OpenSprints.\n# [https://help.ubuntu.com/community/WindowsDualBoot Dual Boot Ubuntu and Windows].  Use this option if you have extra hard drive space to spare.\n# Use [http://wubi-installer.org Wubi] to install Ubuntu on Windows as if it were just another program.  A tutorial/memoir of the wubi/opensprints software installation process on an inexpensive acer laptop, as well as the problems encountered can be found [http://docs.google.com/Doc?id=dd4kx4mt_278gh78kgcq here].\n\nChances are that you will be promoting an event, so you don\'t want the system to fail.  With that in mind, either bring a few computers to the event as backups and use the Pen Drive method, or dedicate a laptop or two to OpenSprints and spare them from daily wear and tear.\n\n== Installing Linux ==\n\n=== Step 1: Creating a bootable Ubuntu 8.10 persistent thumbdrive ===\n\n[[Image:sandisk-4gb-cruzer-u3-micro-usb-flash-drive.jpg|thumb|right|Sandisk 4GB Cruzer U3 Micro USB Flash Drive]]\n\nThe entire Ubuntu Linux operating system as well as the other software packages can be stored on a single 2GB thumb drive and be moved to any machine with little if any changes. The persistent thumbdrive installs a special copy of ubuntu that saves all changes and software packages to the thumbdrive, so no changes are lost. If your laptop currently has a windows operating system, it will remain intact and the whole setup becomes very portable and non-intrusive.\n\n\'\'\'Pen Drive Install\'\'\'\n\n[[Image:unetbootin.jpg|UNetbootin configured to install Ubuntu 8.10 Live on the E:\\ drive which is a USB device]]\n\n# Download the latest version of [http://unetbootin.sourceforge.net/ UNetbootin] \n# Insert an empty 2GB or greater Thumb drive, [http://www.u3.com/uninstall/ delete the U3 partition] if need be.\n# Run UNetbootin\n# Select the \'\'Distribution\'\' radio button, \'\'Ubuntu\'\' dropdown option, \'\'8.**_Live\'\' dropdown option\n#* \'\'\'Optional:\'\'\' You may want to consider downloading the ISO separately, that way you don\'t have to re-download if you have to do it again.\n# Select the \'\'Show all Drives\'\' checkbox, Type \'\'USB Drive\'\', Drive ??? \'\'\'NOTE:\'\'\' You will erase whatever drive letter you pick, so pick wisely.\n# Click the \'\'OK\'\' button.\n# Goto [http://unetbootin.sourceforge.net/diskimg/ http://unetbootin.sourceforge.net/diskimg/] and download one of the files (128mb.zip, 256mb.zip, or 512mb.zip) corresponding to the amount of persistent space you want (make sure the size of the persistent disk image is smaller than the free space you have on your USB drive).\n# Now extract the file \"casper.rw\" from the zip file to your USB drive.\n# Now edit D:\\syslinux.cfg (assuming D:\\ is where your USB drive is) and add in \"persistent\" at the end of the line that begins with \"append\", and save the file, so your syslinux.cfg should look something like this:\n \'\'\'BEFORE:\'\'\' append initrd=/ubninit file=/cdrom/preseed/ubuntu.seed boot=casper quiet splash --\n \'\'\'AFTER:\'\'\' append initrd=/ubninit file=/cdrom/preseed/ubuntu.seed boot=casper quiet splash \'\'\'persistent\'\'\' --\n\nCredit for the persistent install method and additional help on installing Ubuntu can be found at [https://wiki.ubuntu.com/LiveUsbPendrivePersistent Live USB Pendrive Persistent].\n\n=== Step 2: Changing the Default Boot Order in BIOS ===\n\n[[Image:cmos_bios_usb_boot.jpg|right|thumb|Example: CMOS BIOS]]\n[[Image:PhoenixBIOS_boot_order.jpg|right|thumb|Example: PhoenixBIOS]]\n\nEvery computer with a motherboard includes a special chip referred to as the BIOS (Basic Input/Output System). One of the primary jobs of BIOS is to search through a prioritized list of hardware devices to find a bootable operating system.  Most of the time you are booting off a hard drive, where an operating system is installed.  For the purposes of OpenSprints, you will need to boot off a USB device.\n\n# Getting a machine BIOS to boot from the USB drive will differ from computer to computer, typically with in the first 5 seconds of booting your computer the on-screen instructions on how to \"Enter Setup\" or \"Enter BIOS\" will show which key(s) to press. They are commonly F2, F12, or Delete. You will have to press this key immediately after powering on your system, it\'s easy to miss and have it load windows instead, if this happens simply reboot and try again.\n# Once in the BIOS, the drive boot order list has to be located and change in order to boot from the USB drive first. Search through your BIOS options until you see the option to change the boot order from the current hard drive (Eg. ATA/IDE HDD) to the USB thumb drive (AKA: Removeable Devices, USB Mass Storage, External USB Device).\n# Make sure to save changes before exiting the BIOS (sometimes when you exit it will prompt you for this).\n# After leaving the BIOS, the next reboot should boot from the USB drive and bring up the Ubuntu operating system.\n# The Ubuntu boot screen will have options for booting \"Persistent\", select this option (In practice you will just press enter twice at the ubuntu boot screen).\n\nCongratulations, you are now running Ubuntu Linux off of your USB Thumb drive in a persistent state (meaning everything you do going forward will be saved).\n\n=== Step 3: Establish an Internet Connection ===\n\nFirst, focus on getting your network connection to work, via either wired ethernet or wireless. Ubuntu\'s [https://help.ubuntu.com/community/NetworkManager NetworkManager] was designed make this as simple as possible.\n\nIf it doesn\'t work, your wireless or ethernet card doesn\'t have driver support by default.  If you are unable to get the internet to work, please consult the [http://ubuntuforums.org/search.php ubuntu forums]. Be sure to gather as much information on your hardware and network card via the hardware manuals and manufacture website etc.\n\n=== Step 4-7 Shortcut: Installation Script ===\n\nCut and paste the following code into a file on your <code>~/Desktop/</code> and call it <code>opensprints_installer.run</code>\n\n\'\'\'NOTE:\'\'\' You may need to change permissions on the file using <code>chmod 700 ~/Desktop/opensprints_installer.run</code>\n\n #!/bin/bash\n declare -r PI=3.14159265358979\n if [\'id -u\' != \"0\" ]; then\n echo \"You should be root to run this script.\"\n exit 1\n fi\n clear\n echo \"What is your race distance in meters?\"\n read -e RACE_DISTANCE\n echo \"What is your roller diameter in inches?\"\n read -e ROLLER_DIAMETER\n # $ROLLER_CIRCUMFERENCE = awk \'{print $PI * $ROLLER_DIAMETER * 0.0254}\'\n # $ROLLER_CIRCUMFERENCE=$(($PI * $ROLLER_DIAMETER * 0.0254))\n echo $ROLLER_CIRCUMFERENCE\n sudo cp /etc/apt/sources.list /etc/apt/sources.list.backup\n sudo sed -i -e \"s/# deb/deb/g\" /etc/apt/sources.list\n sudo apt-get update\n sudo apt-get install gcc-avr avrdude avr-libc make gtkterm\n rm ~/Desktop/shoes2.run\n wget http://shoooes.net/dist/shoes2.run\n chmod 700 ~/Desktop/shoes2.run\n wget http://github.com/evanfarrar/opensprints/tarball/master\n tar -zxvf ~/Desktop/*opensprints*.tar.gz\n rm ~/Desktop/*opensprints*.tar.gz\n cd ~/Desktop/*opensprints*/firmware/arduino/basic_msg/\n make clean\n make\n # make upload\n # ~/Desktop/shoes2.run\n\nWhat does this do?\n\n* Add the universe repository and update apt-get. TODO: Limit repositories to exclude multiverse.\n* Download required software packages.\n* Download the shoes graphic library.\n* Download opensprints.\n* TODO: Ask for race distance & roller diameter, calculate and save appropriate config files.\n* Create Arduino HEX file.\n* TODO: Upload Arduino HEX file.\n\n=== Step 4: Installing necessary software packages ===\n\nThere are some software dependencies, so you will need to install a series of software packages in order to run opensprints as well as compile the necessary firmware for the Arduino controller.\n\n\'\'\'NOTE:\'\'\' If you haven\'t done so already you will need to [https://help.ubuntu.com/community/Repositories/Ubuntu add the universe repository] by uncommenting lines in /etc/apt/sources.list\n\nTo install software packages using an easy to use GUI interface:\n\n# Start and login to Ubuntu using the user you created.\n# Goto Applications --> Add / Remove\n# Select \"All available Applications\"\n# Type the package names (listed below) in the search function to find and install them.\n#* avrdude\n#* gcc-avr\n#* binutils\n#* avr-libc\n#* make\n#* gtkterm\n\nTo manually install the software packages issue the following command in a the command prompt (Applications --> Terminal):\n sudo apt-get update\n sudo apt-get install gcc-avr avrdude avr-libc make gtkterm\n\n\'\'\'NOTE:\'\'\' Avoid the temptation to upgrade existing packages, <code>sudo apt-get upgrade</code> will only fill up the free space on your USB device.\n\n=== Step 5: [http://help.shoooes.net/Installing.html Install the Graphics Library, Shoes] ===\n\n[[Image:downloading_shoes.jpg|thumb|right|Commands for downloading and executing shoes.]]\n[[Image:shoes.jpg]]\n\n# Download [http://shoooes.net/dist/shoes2.run Shoes] for Linux. <code>wget http://shoooes.net/dist/shoes2.run</code>\n# Save Shoes to the desktop (ex: ~/Desktop/shoes2.run)\n# Change file permissions: <code>chmod 700 ~/Desktop/shoes2.run</code>\n# To execute Shoes double click on the desktop icon or use the command: <code>./shoes2.run</code>\n\n== Step 6: Installing Opensprints Software ==\n\n# Download the latest version of the Opensprints software in [http://github.com/evanfarrar/opensprints/tarball/master tar] or [http://github.com/evanfarrar/opensprints/zipball/master zip] format from [http://github.com/evanfarrar/opensprints/tree/master github.com].\n# Untar or unzip the Opensprints software to ~/Desktop/opensprints/\n\n== Step 7: Programming the Arduino==\n\n[[Image:Arduino.jpg|thumb|right|Arduino USB Board]]\n\nThe Arduino microcontroller will need to be programmed with firmware. There are two firmware sources to choose from:\n\n# basic_msg -- programmed by Evan Farrar\n# advanced_msg --  programmed by Morgan (SF)\n# [http://www.arduino.cc/en/Main/Software arduino-00**] -- This is the Arduino panel software that is used to compile and burn hex firmware images to arduino MCs. It is included in the Opensprints software distribution linked above.\n\n===basic_message===\n\nBefore we can program the Arduino, we need to answer 3 math questions:\n\n# What is the \'\'race distance\'\' in meters?\n# What is the drum / \'\'roller circumference\'\' in meters?\n# How many times does the roller have to spin in order to finish the race?\n\n\'\'\'NOTE:\'\'\' If the following math is done incorrectly it will result in timing and finish errors.\n\n\'\'\'What is the race distance in meters?\'\'\'\n\nDetermine the distance you would like to race at. This is used for the animation.\n\nThis integer needs to match the \"race_distance:\" variable set in your \'\'\'[[conf.yml]]\'\'\' file, eg. in this case it would equal \"race_distance: 1400\"  If you are not familiar with this file yet, it is the main configuration file used by opensprints and is located at the root of the OS folder. The default is 200 (200 meters), so if you are just testing hardware, setting it to something low like 20 and then making sure your conf.yml matches later might make testing easier.\n\n\'\'\'What is the drum / roller circumference in meters?\'\'\'\n\nFind your roller circumference by multiplying the roller diameter by pi and converting to meters. This is for the calculations for time and winner.  Luckily Google Calculator does this for you.\n\n \'\'\'Examples:\'\'\'\n 2.25 inch (diameter) rollers: [http://www.google.com/search?q=(pi+*+2.25+in)+in+m (pi * 2.25 in) in m] = \'\'\'0.17954202 meters\'\'\'\n 3.0 inch (diameter) rollers: [http://www.google.com/search?q=(pi+*+3.0+in)+in+m (pi * 3.0 in) in m] = \'\'\'0.23938936 meters\'\'\'\n 4.5 inch (diameter) rollers: [http://www.google.com/search?q=(pi+*+4.5+in)+in+m (pi * 4.5 in) in m] = \'\'\'0.35908404 meters\'\'\'\n\nIf your roller isnt so easily calculated. Lets say its 23CM circumference. You want to err on the short side. The race animation will quit once the distance is reached and stop counting ticks. if the ticks have not been reached, the time will not be accurate or not operate at all.\n\n\n\'\'\'How many times does the roller have to spin in order to finish the race?\'\'\'\n\nWe will refer to each full rotation a \'\'tick\'\'.  Race distance (in meters) divided by the roller circumference (in meters) will give you the total number of ticks required to finish a race.  Here are some examples using Google Calculator and the earlier numbers:\n\n200 meter race distance divided by the circumference of 2.25 inch (diameter) rollers:\n [http://www.google.com/search?q=200+m+%2F+0.17954202+m 200 m / 0.17954202 m] = \'\'\'1,113.94536 ticks\'\'\'\n200 meter race distance divided by the circumference of 3.0 inch (diameter) rollers:\n [http://www.google.com/search?q=200+m+%2F+0.23938936+m 200 m / 0.23938936 m] = \'\'\'835.45902 ticks\'\'\'\n200 meter race distance divided by the circumference of 4.5 inch (diameter) rollers:\n [http://www.google.com/search?q=200+m+%2F+0.35908404+m 200 m / 0.35908404 m] = \'\'\'556.97268 ticks\'\'\'\n\n\'\'\'Programming the Arduino with basic_message\'\'\'\n\nFinally!  Now open a terminal window and change directory to the folder.\n  cd ~/Desktop/opensprints/firmware/arduino/basic_msg\n\nopen the basic_msg.pde with your favorite text editor (vim, nano)\n\nRound off the answer to our, \'\'how many times does the roller have to spin in order to finish the race\'\' question, edit the following line:\n  int raceLengthTicks = 1400;\n\n\'\'\'NOTE:\'\'\' This can\'t be a float / decimal value, it has to be a whole number!\n\nAlthough the distance can be changed easily once shoes is running a race, the race will not end until the determined amount of ticks is reached. \n\nNow to compile and upload your firmware to the arduino:\n# Go to the firmware directory (ex: ~/Desktop/opensprints/firmware/arduino/basic_msg/)\n# Type the \'\'\'make clean\'\'\' command.\n# Type the \'\'\'make\'\'\' command.\n# Attach the Arduino to your computer.\n# Run the command \'\'\'make upload\'\'\'.\n# You are now ready to run OpenSprints!\n\n\'\'\'NOTE:\'\'\' If \'\'make\'\' fails, you may have made a typo while editing the basic_message.pde file or some of your dependencies may be missing.\n\n===advanced_message BETA===\n\n\'\'\'NOTE:\'\'\' This version is still in testing, proceed at your own risk.\n\nDoes not require the above editing of source code. Just compile and upload your firmware to the arduino. From the firmware directory, type the \"make\" command. If that fails some of your dependencies may be missing.\n\nIf that is successful, attach the arduino to your computer and run the command \"make upload\". If that is successful, you are ready to run opensprints.\n\n==  Verifying the hardware ==\n\nConnect all the hardware together: the sensors connected to the interface board with ethernet cables, the programmed Arduino mounted on the interface board, and the Arduino connected to the computer with a USB cable.\n\n=== Setup for testing under Linux ===\n# Run \'\'gtkterm\'\'\n# Configure the port (Configuration -> Port) and select the following values:\n#* Port: \'\'/dev/ttyUSB0\'\'\n#* Speed: \'\'115200\'\'\n#* Parity: \'\'none\'\'\n#* Bits: \'\'8\'\'\n#* Stopbits: \'\'1\'\'\n#* Flow Control: \'\'none\'\'\n#* End of line delay: \'\'0\'\'\n\n=== Setup for testing under Mac OS X ===\n\n=== Setup for testing under Windows ===\n\n* Install and run [http://www.chiark.greenend.org.uk/~sgtatham/putty/download.html PuTTY].\n* With the Arduino connect to the PC, go to Hardware Manager and determine which COM port the Arduino is connected to.\n* Configure the port:\n** Click on the \'\'Serial\'\' radio button.\n** \'\'COM?\'\', as determined in previous step.\n** As far as I remember, everything else should be default.\n\n=== Running a fake race ===\n\nOnce the chosen terminal is configured as per the previous step, you should see a cursor with nothing going on. Type the letter \'g\' on the keyboard. Nothing should happen for a few seconds (during the countdown - \"4, 3, 2, 1, 0, go!\"). Then you should see a stream of numbers and letters filling the screen.\n\nThis is an example of what you might see in the terminal at an instant:\n<pre>\n1: 0\n2: 0\n3: 0\n4: 0\nt: 15311\n</pre>\n\nTest the hardware by waving a magnet in front of the hall effect sensor. (Turn the magnet around until the \'\'tick\'\' LED flashes. That will be the correct orientation of the magnet.)\n\nEvery time you wave a magnet in front of the hall effect sensor you will see the number following the corresponding sensor increment. So if you caused a tick on sensor 2, the following report will look like this:\n<pre>\n1: 0\n2: 1\n3: 0\n4: 0\nt: 15562\n</pre>\n\nAt this point, if all the sensors are behaving as expected, it\'s time to install and start running the PC application. Check out the page on [[Software Installation|software installation]].\n\n== Finally! Execute the Opensprints GUI ==\n\n# Simply run shoes by double-clicking it on your desktop\n# Then click \"Open an app\"\n# Browse to ~/opensprints/main.rb\n\n== Common faults ==\n\n= Mac OS X =\n\n# Grab a copy of the latest code: http://github.com/evanfarrar/opensprints/zipball/master\n# Get the serproxy program from Arduino\'s website and extract it somewhere like the opensprints directory: http://download.berlios.de/arduino/serproxy-0.1.3-3.bin.macosx.zip\n# Install the Arduino Development suite and the USB Serial Drivers: http://arduino.cc/en/Guide/MacOSX\n# Edit the serproxy.cfg  included in opensprints\' main directory to use your arduino\'s address. There is a line that says \"serial_device1=/dev/ttyUSB0\". Change it to something like \"/dev/cu.usbserial-A9005fET\" (if you browse around in the finder you should be able to find the exact address).\n# run the serproxy program from a terminal: \"cd ~/Desktop/opensprints; ./serproxy serproxy.cfg\"\n# edit your conf.yml to use the sensor named \"network\"\n# Get the latest version of shoes and use it to open \"opensprints/main.rb\" : http://shoooes.net/dist/shoes2.dmg\n\n= Windows =\n\n# Grab a copy of the latest code: http://github.com/evanfarrar/opensprints/zipball/master\n# Get the serproxy program from the Arduino [http://www.arduino.cc/en/Main/Software website] and extract it somewhere like the opensprints directory.\n# Get the Arduino Development platform and USB serial drivers: http://arduino.cc/en/Guide/Windows\n# Get shoes: http://shoooes.net/','utf-8'),(524,'\'\'Currently the software only runs on a Linux system. If you are unfamiliar with the system this can seem a bit daunting, however there are a few tips and ideas for getting the system up and running as quick as possible.\'\'\n\n= Linux =\n\nWe recommend using the Ubuntu distribution of Linux, and here are 4 ways of installing Ubuntu:\n\n# Use [http://www.pendrivelinux.com/ubuntu-810-persistent-flash-drive-install-from-live-cd/ Pen Drive Linux], aka, make a bootable 2GB USB thumb drive that you can put in any Windows computer capable of booting off a USB device.\n# [https://help.ubuntu.com/community/Installation Install Ubuntu] as your only operating system.  Use this option if you already use Linux as a desktop operating system or have an extra computer that you don\'t mind dedicating to OpenSprints.\n# [https://help.ubuntu.com/community/WindowsDualBoot Dual Boot Ubuntu and Windows].  Use this option if you have extra hard drive space to spare.\n# Use [http://wubi-installer.org Wubi] to install Ubuntu on Windows as if it were just another program.  A tutorial/memoir of the wubi/opensprints software installation process on an inexpensive acer laptop, as well as the problems encountered can be found [http://docs.google.com/Doc?id=dd4kx4mt_278gh78kgcq here].\n\nChances are that you will be promoting an event, so you don\'t want the system to fail.  With that in mind, either bring a few computers to the event as backups and use the Pen Drive method, or dedicate a laptop or two to OpenSprints and spare them from daily wear and tear.\n\n== Installing Linux ==\n\n=== Step 1: Creating a bootable Ubuntu 8.10 persistent thumbdrive ===\n\n[[Image:sandisk-4gb-cruzer-u3-micro-usb-flash-drive.jpg|thumb|right|Sandisk 4GB Cruzer U3 Micro USB Flash Drive]]\n\nThe entire Ubuntu Linux operating system as well as the other software packages can be stored on a single 2GB thumb drive and be moved to any machine with little if any changes. The persistent thumbdrive installs a special copy of ubuntu that saves all changes and software packages to the thumbdrive, so no changes are lost. If your laptop currently has a windows operating system, it will remain intact and the whole setup becomes very portable and non-intrusive.\n\n\'\'\'Pen Drive Install\'\'\'\n\n[[Image:unetbootin.jpg|UNetbootin configured to install Ubuntu 8.10 Live on the E:\\ drive which is a USB device]]\n\n# Download the latest version of [http://unetbootin.sourceforge.net/ UNetbootin] \n# Insert an empty 2GB or greater Thumb drive, [http://www.u3.com/uninstall/ delete the U3 partition] if need be.\n# Run UNetbootin\n# Select the \'\'Distribution\'\' radio button, \'\'Ubuntu\'\' dropdown option, \'\'8.**_Live\'\' dropdown option\n#* \'\'\'Optional:\'\'\' You may want to consider downloading the ISO separately, that way you don\'t have to re-download if you have to do it again.\n# Select the \'\'Show all Drives\'\' checkbox, Type \'\'USB Drive\'\', Drive ??? \'\'\'NOTE:\'\'\' You will erase whatever drive letter you pick, so pick wisely.\n# Click the \'\'OK\'\' button.\n# Goto [http://unetbootin.sourceforge.net/diskimg/ http://unetbootin.sourceforge.net/diskimg/] and download one of the files (128mb.zip, 256mb.zip, or 512mb.zip) corresponding to the amount of persistent space you want (make sure the size of the persistent disk image is smaller than the free space you have on your USB drive).\n# Now extract the file \"casper.rw\" from the zip file to your USB drive.\n# Now edit D:\\syslinux.cfg (assuming D:\\ is where your USB drive is) and add in \"persistent\" at the end of the line that begins with \"append\", and save the file, so your syslinux.cfg should look something like this:\n \'\'\'BEFORE:\'\'\' append initrd=/ubninit file=/cdrom/preseed/ubuntu.seed boot=casper quiet splash --\n \'\'\'AFTER:\'\'\' append initrd=/ubninit file=/cdrom/preseed/ubuntu.seed boot=casper quiet splash \'\'\'persistent\'\'\' --\n\nCredit for the persistent install method and additional help on installing Ubuntu can be found at [https://wiki.ubuntu.com/LiveUsbPendrivePersistent Live USB Pendrive Persistent].\n\n=== Step 2: Changing the Default Boot Order in BIOS ===\n\n[[Image:cmos_bios_usb_boot.jpg|right|thumb|Example: CMOS BIOS]]\n[[Image:PhoenixBIOS_boot_order.jpg|right|thumb|Example: PhoenixBIOS]]\n\nEvery computer with a motherboard includes a special chip referred to as the BIOS (Basic Input/Output System). One of the primary jobs of BIOS is to search through a prioritized list of hardware devices to find a bootable operating system.  Most of the time you are booting off a hard drive, where an operating system is installed.  For the purposes of OpenSprints, you will need to boot off a USB device.\n\n# Getting a machine BIOS to boot from the USB drive will differ from computer to computer, typically with in the first 5 seconds of booting your computer the on-screen instructions on how to \"Enter Setup\" or \"Enter BIOS\" will show which key(s) to press. They are commonly F2, F12, or Delete. You will have to press this key immediately after powering on your system, it\'s easy to miss and have it load windows instead, if this happens simply reboot and try again.\n# Once in the BIOS, the drive boot order list has to be located and change in order to boot from the USB drive first. Search through your BIOS options until you see the option to change the boot order from the current hard drive (Eg. ATA/IDE HDD) to the USB thumb drive (AKA: Removeable Devices, USB Mass Storage, External USB Device).\n# Make sure to save changes before exiting the BIOS (sometimes when you exit it will prompt you for this).\n# After leaving the BIOS, the next reboot should boot from the USB drive and bring up the Ubuntu operating system.\n# The Ubuntu boot screen will have options for booting \"Persistent\", select this option (In practice you will just press enter twice at the ubuntu boot screen).\n\nCongratulations, you are now running Ubuntu Linux off of your USB Thumb drive in a persistent state (meaning everything you do going forward will be saved).\n\n=== Step 3: Establish an Internet Connection ===\n\nFirst, focus on getting your network connection to work, via either wired ethernet or wireless. Ubuntu\'s [https://help.ubuntu.com/community/NetworkManager NetworkManager] was designed make this as simple as possible.\n\nIf it doesn\'t work, your wireless or ethernet card doesn\'t have driver support by default.  If you are unable to get the internet to work, please consult the [http://ubuntuforums.org/search.php ubuntu forums]. Be sure to gather as much information on your hardware and network card via the hardware manuals and manufacture website etc.\n\n=== Step 4-7 Shortcut: Installation Script ===\n\nCut and paste the following code into a file on your <code>~/Desktop/</code> and call it <code>opensprints_installer.run</code>\n\n\'\'\'NOTE:\'\'\' You may need to change permissions on the file using <code>chmod 700 ~/Desktop/opensprints_installer.run</code>\n\n #!/bin/bash\n declare -r PI=3.14159265358979\n if [\'id -u\' != \"0\" ]; then\n echo \"You should be root to run this script.\"\n exit 1\n fi\n clear\n echo \"What is your race distance in meters?\"\n read -e RACE_DISTANCE\n echo \"What is your roller diameter in inches?\"\n read -e ROLLER_DIAMETER\n # $ROLLER_CIRCUMFERENCE = awk \'{print $PI * $ROLLER_DIAMETER * 0.0254}\'\n # $ROLLER_CIRCUMFERENCE=$(($PI * $ROLLER_DIAMETER * 0.0254))\n echo $ROLLER_CIRCUMFERENCE\n sudo cp /etc/apt/sources.list /etc/apt/sources.list.backup\n sudo sed -i -e \"s/# deb/deb/g\" /etc/apt/sources.list\n sudo apt-get update\n sudo apt-get -y install gcc-avr avrdude avr-libc make gtkterm\n rm ~/Desktop/shoes2.run\n wget http://shoooes.net/dist/shoes2.run\n chmod 700 ~/Desktop/shoes2.run\n wget http://github.com/evanfarrar/opensprints/tarball/master\n tar -zxvf ~/Desktop/*opensprints*.tar.gz\n rm ~/Desktop/*opensprints*.tar.gz\n cd ~/Desktop/*opensprints*/firmware/arduino/basic_msg/\n make clean\n make\n # make upload\n # ~/Desktop/shoes2.run\n\n\'\'\'What does this do?\'\'\'\n\n* Add the universe repository and update apt-get. TODO: Limit repositories to exclude multiverse.\n* Download required software packages.\n* Download the shoes graphic library.\n* Download opensprints.\n* TODO: Ask for race distance & roller diameter, calculate and save appropriate config files.\n* Create Arduino HEX file.\n* TODO: Upload Arduino HEX file.\n\n=== Step 4: Installing necessary software packages ===\n\nThere are some software dependencies, so you will need to install a series of software packages in order to run opensprints as well as compile the necessary firmware for the Arduino controller.\n\n\'\'\'NOTE:\'\'\' If you haven\'t done so already you will need to [https://help.ubuntu.com/community/Repositories/Ubuntu add the universe repository] by uncommenting lines in /etc/apt/sources.list\n\nTo install software packages using an easy to use GUI interface:\n\n# Start and login to Ubuntu using the user you created.\n# Goto Applications --> Add / Remove\n# Select \"All available Applications\"\n# Type the package names (listed below) in the search function to find and install them.\n#* avrdude\n#* gcc-avr\n#* binutils\n#* avr-libc\n#* make\n#* gtkterm\n\nTo manually install the software packages issue the following command in a the command prompt (Applications --> Terminal):\n sudo apt-get update\n sudo apt-get install gcc-avr avrdude avr-libc make gtkterm\n\n\'\'\'NOTE:\'\'\' Avoid the temptation to upgrade existing packages, <code>sudo apt-get upgrade</code> will only fill up the free space on your USB device.\n\n=== Step 5: [http://help.shoooes.net/Installing.html Install the Graphics Library, Shoes] ===\n\n[[Image:downloading_shoes.jpg|thumb|right|Commands for downloading and executing shoes.]]\n[[Image:shoes.jpg]]\n\n# Download [http://shoooes.net/dist/shoes2.run Shoes] for Linux. <code>wget http://shoooes.net/dist/shoes2.run</code>\n# Save Shoes to the desktop (ex: ~/Desktop/shoes2.run)\n# Change file permissions: <code>chmod 700 ~/Desktop/shoes2.run</code>\n# To execute Shoes double click on the desktop icon or use the command: <code>./shoes2.run</code>\n\n== Step 6: Installing Opensprints Software ==\n\n# Download the latest version of the Opensprints software in [http://github.com/evanfarrar/opensprints/tarball/master tar] or [http://github.com/evanfarrar/opensprints/zipball/master zip] format from [http://github.com/evanfarrar/opensprints/tree/master github.com].\n# Untar or unzip the Opensprints software to ~/Desktop/opensprints/\n\n== Step 7: Programming the Arduino==\n\n[[Image:Arduino.jpg|thumb|right|Arduino USB Board]]\n\nThe Arduino microcontroller will need to be programmed with firmware. There are two firmware sources to choose from:\n\n# basic_msg -- programmed by Evan Farrar\n# advanced_msg --  programmed by Morgan (SF)\n# [http://www.arduino.cc/en/Main/Software arduino-00**] -- This is the Arduino panel software that is used to compile and burn hex firmware images to arduino MCs. It is included in the Opensprints software distribution linked above.\n\n===basic_message===\n\nBefore we can program the Arduino, we need to answer 3 math questions:\n\n# What is the \'\'race distance\'\' in meters?\n# What is the drum / \'\'roller circumference\'\' in meters?\n# How many times does the roller have to spin in order to finish the race?\n\n\'\'\'NOTE:\'\'\' If the following math is done incorrectly it will result in timing and finish errors.\n\n\'\'\'What is the race distance in meters?\'\'\'\n\nDetermine the distance you would like to race at. This is used for the animation.\n\nThis integer needs to match the \"race_distance:\" variable set in your \'\'\'[[conf.yml]]\'\'\' file, eg. in this case it would equal \"race_distance: 1400\"  If you are not familiar with this file yet, it is the main configuration file used by opensprints and is located at the root of the OS folder. The default is 200 (200 meters), so if you are just testing hardware, setting it to something low like 20 and then making sure your conf.yml matches later might make testing easier.\n\n\'\'\'What is the drum / roller circumference in meters?\'\'\'\n\nFind your roller circumference by multiplying the roller diameter by pi and converting to meters. This is for the calculations for time and winner.  Luckily Google Calculator does this for you.\n\n \'\'\'Examples:\'\'\'\n 2.25 inch (diameter) rollers: [http://www.google.com/search?q=(pi+*+2.25+in)+in+m (pi * 2.25 in) in m] = \'\'\'0.17954202 meters\'\'\'\n 3.0 inch (diameter) rollers: [http://www.google.com/search?q=(pi+*+3.0+in)+in+m (pi * 3.0 in) in m] = \'\'\'0.23938936 meters\'\'\'\n 4.5 inch (diameter) rollers: [http://www.google.com/search?q=(pi+*+4.5+in)+in+m (pi * 4.5 in) in m] = \'\'\'0.35908404 meters\'\'\'\n\nIf your roller isnt so easily calculated. Lets say its 23CM circumference. You want to err on the short side. The race animation will quit once the distance is reached and stop counting ticks. if the ticks have not been reached, the time will not be accurate or not operate at all.\n\n\n\'\'\'How many times does the roller have to spin in order to finish the race?\'\'\'\n\nWe will refer to each full rotation a \'\'tick\'\'.  Race distance (in meters) divided by the roller circumference (in meters) will give you the total number of ticks required to finish a race.  Here are some examples using Google Calculator and the earlier numbers:\n\n200 meter race distance divided by the circumference of 2.25 inch (diameter) rollers:\n [http://www.google.com/search?q=200+m+%2F+0.17954202+m 200 m / 0.17954202 m] = \'\'\'1,113.94536 ticks\'\'\'\n200 meter race distance divided by the circumference of 3.0 inch (diameter) rollers:\n [http://www.google.com/search?q=200+m+%2F+0.23938936+m 200 m / 0.23938936 m] = \'\'\'835.45902 ticks\'\'\'\n200 meter race distance divided by the circumference of 4.5 inch (diameter) rollers:\n [http://www.google.com/search?q=200+m+%2F+0.35908404+m 200 m / 0.35908404 m] = \'\'\'556.97268 ticks\'\'\'\n\n\'\'\'Programming the Arduino with basic_message\'\'\'\n\nFinally!  Now open a terminal window and change directory to the folder.\n  cd ~/Desktop/opensprints/firmware/arduino/basic_msg\n\nopen the basic_msg.pde with your favorite text editor (vim, nano)\n\nRound off the answer to our, \'\'how many times does the roller have to spin in order to finish the race\'\' question, edit the following line:\n  int raceLengthTicks = 1400;\n\n\'\'\'NOTE:\'\'\' This can\'t be a float / decimal value, it has to be a whole number!\n\nAlthough the distance can be changed easily once shoes is running a race, the race will not end until the determined amount of ticks is reached. \n\nNow to compile and upload your firmware to the arduino:\n# Go to the firmware directory (ex: ~/Desktop/opensprints/firmware/arduino/basic_msg/)\n# Type the \'\'\'make clean\'\'\' command.\n# Type the \'\'\'make\'\'\' command.\n# Attach the Arduino to your computer.\n# Run the command \'\'\'make upload\'\'\'.\n# You are now ready to run OpenSprints!\n\n\'\'\'NOTE:\'\'\' If \'\'make\'\' fails, you may have made a typo while editing the basic_message.pde file or some of your dependencies may be missing.\n\n===advanced_message BETA===\n\n\'\'\'NOTE:\'\'\' This version is still in testing, proceed at your own risk.\n\nDoes not require the above editing of source code. Just compile and upload your firmware to the arduino. From the firmware directory, type the \"make\" command. If that fails some of your dependencies may be missing.\n\nIf that is successful, attach the arduino to your computer and run the command \"make upload\". If that is successful, you are ready to run opensprints.\n\n==  Verifying the hardware ==\n\nConnect all the hardware together: the sensors connected to the interface board with ethernet cables, the programmed Arduino mounted on the interface board, and the Arduino connected to the computer with a USB cable.\n\n=== Setup for testing under Linux ===\n# Run \'\'gtkterm\'\'\n# Configure the port (Configuration -> Port) and select the following values:\n#* Port: \'\'/dev/ttyUSB0\'\'\n#* Speed: \'\'115200\'\'\n#* Parity: \'\'none\'\'\n#* Bits: \'\'8\'\'\n#* Stopbits: \'\'1\'\'\n#* Flow Control: \'\'none\'\'\n#* End of line delay: \'\'0\'\'\n\n=== Setup for testing under Mac OS X ===\n\n=== Setup for testing under Windows ===\n\n* Install and run [http://www.chiark.greenend.org.uk/~sgtatham/putty/download.html PuTTY].\n* With the Arduino connect to the PC, go to Hardware Manager and determine which COM port the Arduino is connected to.\n* Configure the port:\n** Click on the \'\'Serial\'\' radio button.\n** \'\'COM?\'\', as determined in previous step.\n** As far as I remember, everything else should be default.\n\n=== Running a fake race ===\n\nOnce the chosen terminal is configured as per the previous step, you should see a cursor with nothing going on. Type the letter \'g\' on the keyboard. Nothing should happen for a few seconds (during the countdown - \"4, 3, 2, 1, 0, go!\"). Then you should see a stream of numbers and letters filling the screen.\n\nThis is an example of what you might see in the terminal at an instant:\n<pre>\n1: 0\n2: 0\n3: 0\n4: 0\nt: 15311\n</pre>\n\nTest the hardware by waving a magnet in front of the hall effect sensor. (Turn the magnet around until the \'\'tick\'\' LED flashes. That will be the correct orientation of the magnet.)\n\nEvery time you wave a magnet in front of the hall effect sensor you will see the number following the corresponding sensor increment. So if you caused a tick on sensor 2, the following report will look like this:\n<pre>\n1: 0\n2: 1\n3: 0\n4: 0\nt: 15562\n</pre>\n\nAt this point, if all the sensors are behaving as expected, it\'s time to install and start running the PC application. Check out the page on [[Software Installation|software installation]].\n\n== Finally! Execute the Opensprints GUI ==\n\n# Simply run shoes by double-clicking it on your desktop\n# Then click \"Open an app\"\n# Browse to ~/opensprints/main.rb\n\n== Common faults ==\n\n= Mac OS X =\n\n# Grab a copy of the latest code: http://github.com/evanfarrar/opensprints/zipball/master\n# Get the serproxy program from Arduino\'s website and extract it somewhere like the opensprints directory: http://download.berlios.de/arduino/serproxy-0.1.3-3.bin.macosx.zip\n# Install the Arduino Development suite and the USB Serial Drivers: http://arduino.cc/en/Guide/MacOSX\n# Edit the serproxy.cfg  included in opensprints\' main directory to use your arduino\'s address. There is a line that says \"serial_device1=/dev/ttyUSB0\". Change it to something like \"/dev/cu.usbserial-A9005fET\" (if you browse around in the finder you should be able to find the exact address).\n# run the serproxy program from a terminal: \"cd ~/Desktop/opensprints; ./serproxy serproxy.cfg\"\n# edit your conf.yml to use the sensor named \"network\"\n# Get the latest version of shoes and use it to open \"opensprints/main.rb\" : http://shoooes.net/dist/shoes2.dmg\n\n= Windows =\n\n# Grab a copy of the latest code: http://github.com/evanfarrar/opensprints/zipball/master\n# Get the serproxy program from the Arduino [http://www.arduino.cc/en/Main/Software website] and extract it somewhere like the opensprints directory.\n# Get the Arduino Development platform and USB serial drivers: http://arduino.cc/en/Guide/Windows\n# Get shoes: http://shoooes.net/','utf-8'),(525,'\'\'Currently the software only runs on a Linux system. If you are unfamiliar with the system this can seem a bit daunting, however there are a few tips and ideas for getting the system up and running as quick as possible.\'\'\n\n= Linux =\n\nWe recommend using the Ubuntu distribution of Linux, and here are 4 ways of installing Ubuntu:\n\n# Use [http://www.pendrivelinux.com/ubuntu-810-persistent-flash-drive-install-from-live-cd/ Pen Drive Linux], aka, make a bootable 2GB USB thumb drive that you can put in any Windows computer capable of booting off a USB device.\n# [https://help.ubuntu.com/community/Installation Install Ubuntu] as your only operating system.  Use this option if you already use Linux as a desktop operating system or have an extra computer that you don\'t mind dedicating to OpenSprints.\n# [https://help.ubuntu.com/community/WindowsDualBoot Dual Boot Ubuntu and Windows].  Use this option if you have extra hard drive space to spare.\n# Use [http://wubi-installer.org Wubi] to install Ubuntu on Windows as if it were just another program.  A tutorial/memoir of the wubi/opensprints software installation process on an inexpensive acer laptop, as well as the problems encountered can be found [http://docs.google.com/Doc?id=dd4kx4mt_278gh78kgcq here].\n\nChances are that you will be promoting an event, so you don\'t want the system to fail.  With that in mind, either bring a few computers to the event as backups and use the Pen Drive method, or dedicate a laptop or two to OpenSprints and spare them from daily wear and tear.\n\n== Installing Linux ==\n\n=== Step 1: Creating a bootable Ubuntu 8.10 persistent thumbdrive ===\n\n[[Image:sandisk-4gb-cruzer-u3-micro-usb-flash-drive.jpg|thumb|right|Sandisk 4GB Cruzer U3 Micro USB Flash Drive]]\n\nThe entire Ubuntu Linux operating system as well as the other software packages can be stored on a single 2GB thumb drive and be moved to any machine with little if any changes. The persistent thumbdrive installs a special copy of ubuntu that saves all changes and software packages to the thumbdrive, so no changes are lost. If your laptop currently has a windows operating system, it will remain intact and the whole setup becomes very portable and non-intrusive.\n\n\'\'\'Pen Drive Install\'\'\'\n\n[[Image:unetbootin.jpg|UNetbootin configured to install Ubuntu 8.10 Live on the E:\\ drive which is a USB device]]\n\n# Download the latest version of [http://unetbootin.sourceforge.net/ UNetbootin] \n# Insert an empty 2GB or greater Thumb drive, [http://www.u3.com/uninstall/ delete the U3 partition] if need be.\n# Run UNetbootin\n# Select the \'\'Distribution\'\' radio button, \'\'Ubuntu\'\' dropdown option, \'\'8.**_Live\'\' dropdown option\n#* \'\'\'Optional:\'\'\' You may want to consider downloading the ISO separately, that way you don\'t have to re-download if you have to do it again.\n# Select the \'\'Show all Drives\'\' checkbox, Type \'\'USB Drive\'\', Drive ??? \'\'\'NOTE:\'\'\' You will erase whatever drive letter you pick, so pick wisely.\n# Click the \'\'OK\'\' button.\n# Goto [http://unetbootin.sourceforge.net/diskimg/ http://unetbootin.sourceforge.net/diskimg/] and download one of the files (128mb.zip, 256mb.zip, or 512mb.zip) corresponding to the amount of persistent space you want (make sure the size of the persistent disk image is smaller than the free space you have on your USB drive).\n# Now extract the file \"casper.rw\" from the zip file to your USB drive.\n# Now edit D:\\syslinux.cfg (assuming D:\\ is where your USB drive is) and add in \"persistent\" at the end of the line that begins with \"append\", and save the file, so your syslinux.cfg should look something like this:\n \'\'\'BEFORE:\'\'\' append initrd=/ubninit file=/cdrom/preseed/ubuntu.seed boot=casper quiet splash --\n \'\'\'AFTER:\'\'\' append initrd=/ubninit file=/cdrom/preseed/ubuntu.seed boot=casper quiet splash \'\'\'persistent\'\'\' --\n\nCredit for the persistent install method and additional help on installing Ubuntu can be found at [https://wiki.ubuntu.com/LiveUsbPendrivePersistent Live USB Pendrive Persistent].\n\n=== Step 2: Changing the Default Boot Order in BIOS ===\n\n[[Image:cmos_bios_usb_boot.jpg|right|thumb|Example: CMOS BIOS]]\n[[Image:PhoenixBIOS_boot_order.jpg|right|thumb|Example: PhoenixBIOS]]\n\nEvery computer with a motherboard includes a special chip referred to as the BIOS (Basic Input/Output System). One of the primary jobs of BIOS is to search through a prioritized list of hardware devices to find a bootable operating system.  Most of the time you are booting off a hard drive, where an operating system is installed.  For the purposes of OpenSprints, you will need to boot off a USB device.\n\n# Getting a machine BIOS to boot from the USB drive will differ from computer to computer, typically with in the first 5 seconds of booting your computer the on-screen instructions on how to \"Enter Setup\" or \"Enter BIOS\" will show which key(s) to press. They are commonly F2, F12, or Delete. You will have to press this key immediately after powering on your system, it\'s easy to miss and have it load windows instead, if this happens simply reboot and try again.\n# Once in the BIOS, the drive boot order list has to be located and change in order to boot from the USB drive first. Search through your BIOS options until you see the option to change the boot order from the current hard drive (Eg. ATA/IDE HDD) to the USB thumb drive (AKA: Removeable Devices, USB Mass Storage, External USB Device).\n# Make sure to save changes before exiting the BIOS (sometimes when you exit it will prompt you for this).\n# After leaving the BIOS, the next reboot should boot from the USB drive and bring up the Ubuntu operating system.\n# The Ubuntu boot screen will have options for booting \"Persistent\", select this option (In practice you will just press enter twice at the ubuntu boot screen).\n\nCongratulations, you are now running Ubuntu Linux off of your USB Thumb drive in a persistent state (meaning everything you do going forward will be saved).\n\n=== Step 3: Establish an Internet Connection ===\n\nFirst, focus on getting your network connection to work, via either wired ethernet or wireless. Ubuntu\'s [https://help.ubuntu.com/community/NetworkManager NetworkManager] was designed make this as simple as possible.\n\nIf it doesn\'t work, your wireless or ethernet card doesn\'t have driver support by default.  If you are unable to get the internet to work, please consult the [http://ubuntuforums.org/search.php ubuntu forums]. Be sure to gather as much information on your hardware and network card via the hardware manuals and manufacture website etc.\n\n=== Step 4-7 Shortcut: Installation Script ===\n\nCut and paste the following code into a file on your <code>~/Desktop/</code> and call it <code>opensprints_installer.run</code>\n\n\'\'\'NOTE:\'\'\' You may need to change permissions on the file using <code>chmod 700 ~/Desktop/opensprints_installer.run</code>\n\n\'\'\'NOTE:\'\'\' Have your [[Main Board]] and USB 2.0 A / B Cable handy and ready to go.\n\n #!/bin/bash\n declare -r PI=3.14159265358979\n if [\'id -u\' != \"0\" ]; then\n echo \"You should be root to run this script.\"\n exit 1\n fi\n clear\n echo \"What is your race distance in meters?\"\n read -e RACE_DISTANCE\n echo \"What is your roller diameter in inches?\"\n read -e ROLLER_DIAMETER\n declare -r ROLLER_CIRCUMFERENCE = `echo $PI, $ROLLER_DIAMETER|awk \'{print 0.0254000 * $1 * $2}\'`\n declare -r RACE_LENGTH_TICKS = `echo $PI, $ROLLER_DIAMETER, $RACE_DISTANCE|awk \'{print $3 / (0.0254000 * $1 * $2)}\'`\n echo $ROLLER_CIRCUMFERENCE\n echo $RACE_LENGTH_TICKS\n sudo cp /etc/apt/sources.list /etc/apt/sources.list.backup\n sudo sed -i -e \"s/# deb/deb/g\" /etc/apt/sources.list\n sudo apt-get update\n sudo apt-get -y install gcc-avr avrdude avr-libc make gtkterm\n rm ~/Desktop/shoes2.run\n wget http://shoooes.net/dist/shoes2.run\n chmod 700 ~/Desktop/shoes2.run\n wget http://github.com/evanfarrar/opensprints/tarball/master\n tar -zxf ~/Desktop/*opensprints*.tar.gz\n rm ~/Desktop/*opensprints*.tar.gz\n cd ~/Desktop/*opensprints*/\n #TODO: Set race_distance in conf_sample.yml to $RACE_DISTANCE\n #TODO: Set roller_circumference in conf_sample.yml to $ROLLER_CIRCUMFERENCE\n cd ~/Desktop/*opensprints*/firmware/arduino/basic_msg/\n #TODO: Set raceLenthTicks in basic_msg.pde to $RACE_LENGTH_TICKS\n make clean\n make\n echo \"Connect the Arduino via USB and hit <enter>\"\n read continue\n make upload\n ~/Desktop/shoes2.run\n exit 0\n\n\'\'\'What does this do?\'\'\'\n\n* Add the universe repository and update apt-get. TODO: Limit repositories to exclude multiverse.\n* Download required software packages.\n* Download the shoes graphic library.\n* Download opensprints.\n* TODO: Ask for race distance & roller diameter, calculate and save appropriate config files.\n* Create Arduino HEX file.\n* TODO: Upload Arduino HEX file.\n\n=== Step 4: Installing necessary software packages ===\n\nThere are some software dependencies, so you will need to install a series of software packages in order to run opensprints as well as compile the necessary firmware for the Arduino controller.\n\n\'\'\'NOTE:\'\'\' If you haven\'t done so already you will need to [https://help.ubuntu.com/community/Repositories/Ubuntu add the universe repository] by uncommenting lines in /etc/apt/sources.list\n\nTo install software packages using an easy to use GUI interface:\n\n# Start and login to Ubuntu using the user you created.\n# Goto Applications --> Add / Remove\n# Select \"All available Applications\"\n# Type the package names (listed below) in the search function to find and install them.\n#* avrdude\n#* gcc-avr\n#* binutils\n#* avr-libc\n#* make\n#* gtkterm\n\nTo manually install the software packages issue the following command in a the command prompt (Applications --> Terminal):\n sudo apt-get update\n sudo apt-get install gcc-avr avrdude avr-libc make gtkterm\n\n\'\'\'NOTE:\'\'\' Avoid the temptation to upgrade existing packages, <code>sudo apt-get upgrade</code> will only fill up the free space on your USB device.\n\n=== Step 5: [http://help.shoooes.net/Installing.html Install the Graphics Library, Shoes] ===\n\n[[Image:downloading_shoes.jpg|thumb|right|Commands for downloading and executing shoes.]]\n[[Image:shoes.jpg]]\n\n# Download [http://shoooes.net/dist/shoes2.run Shoes] for Linux. <code>wget http://shoooes.net/dist/shoes2.run</code>\n# Save Shoes to the desktop (ex: ~/Desktop/shoes2.run)\n# Change file permissions: <code>chmod 700 ~/Desktop/shoes2.run</code>\n# To execute Shoes double click on the desktop icon or use the command: <code>./shoes2.run</code>\n\n== Step 6: Installing Opensprints Software ==\n\n# Download the latest version of the Opensprints software in [http://github.com/evanfarrar/opensprints/tarball/master tar] or [http://github.com/evanfarrar/opensprints/zipball/master zip] format from [http://github.com/evanfarrar/opensprints/tree/master github.com].\n# Untar or unzip the Opensprints software to ~/Desktop/opensprints/\n\n== Step 7: Programming the Arduino==\n\n[[Image:Arduino.jpg|thumb|right|Arduino USB Board]]\n\nThe Arduino microcontroller will need to be programmed with firmware. There are two firmware sources to choose from:\n\n# basic_msg -- programmed by Evan Farrar\n# advanced_msg --  programmed by Morgan (SF)\n# [http://www.arduino.cc/en/Main/Software arduino-00**] -- This is the Arduino panel software that is used to compile and burn hex firmware images to arduino MCs. It is included in the Opensprints software distribution linked above.\n\n===basic_message===\n\nBefore we can program the Arduino, we need to answer 3 math questions:\n\n# What is the \'\'race distance\'\' in meters?\n# What is the drum / \'\'roller circumference\'\' in meters?\n# How many times does the roller have to spin in order to finish the race?\n\n\'\'\'NOTE:\'\'\' If the following math is done incorrectly it will result in timing and finish errors.\n\n\'\'\'What is the race distance in meters?\'\'\'\n\nDetermine the distance you would like to race at. This is used for the animation.\n\nThis integer needs to match the \"race_distance:\" variable set in your \'\'\'[[conf.yml]]\'\'\' file, eg. in this case it would equal \"race_distance: 1400\"  If you are not familiar with this file yet, it is the main configuration file used by opensprints and is located at the root of the OS folder. The default is 200 (200 meters), so if you are just testing hardware, setting it to something low like 20 and then making sure your conf.yml matches later might make testing easier.\n\n\'\'\'What is the drum / roller circumference in meters?\'\'\'\n\nFind your roller circumference by multiplying the roller diameter by pi and converting to meters. This is for the calculations for time and winner.  Luckily Google Calculator does this for you.\n\n \'\'\'Examples:\'\'\'\n 2.25 inch (diameter) rollers: [http://www.google.com/search?q=(pi+*+2.25+in)+in+m (pi * 2.25 in) in m] = \'\'\'0.17954202 meters\'\'\'\n 3.0 inch (diameter) rollers: [http://www.google.com/search?q=(pi+*+3.0+in)+in+m (pi * 3.0 in) in m] = \'\'\'0.23938936 meters\'\'\'\n 4.5 inch (diameter) rollers: [http://www.google.com/search?q=(pi+*+4.5+in)+in+m (pi * 4.5 in) in m] = \'\'\'0.35908404 meters\'\'\'\n\nIf your roller isnt so easily calculated. Lets say its 23CM circumference. You want to err on the short side. The race animation will quit once the distance is reached and stop counting ticks. if the ticks have not been reached, the time will not be accurate or not operate at all.\n\n\n\'\'\'How many times does the roller have to spin in order to finish the race?\'\'\'\n\nWe will refer to each full rotation a \'\'tick\'\'.  Race distance (in meters) divided by the roller circumference (in meters) will give you the total number of ticks required to finish a race.  Here are some examples using Google Calculator and the earlier numbers:\n\n200 meter race distance divided by the circumference of 2.25 inch (diameter) rollers:\n [http://www.google.com/search?q=200+m+%2F+0.17954202+m 200 m / 0.17954202 m] = \'\'\'1,113.94536 ticks\'\'\'\n200 meter race distance divided by the circumference of 3.0 inch (diameter) rollers:\n [http://www.google.com/search?q=200+m+%2F+0.23938936+m 200 m / 0.23938936 m] = \'\'\'835.45902 ticks\'\'\'\n200 meter race distance divided by the circumference of 4.5 inch (diameter) rollers:\n [http://www.google.com/search?q=200+m+%2F+0.35908404+m 200 m / 0.35908404 m] = \'\'\'556.97268 ticks\'\'\'\n\n\'\'\'Programming the Arduino with basic_message\'\'\'\n\nFinally!  Now open a terminal window and change directory to the folder.\n  cd ~/Desktop/opensprints/firmware/arduino/basic_msg\n\nopen the basic_msg.pde with your favorite text editor (vim, nano)\n\nRound off the answer to our, \'\'how many times does the roller have to spin in order to finish the race\'\' question, edit the following line:\n  int raceLengthTicks = 1400;\n\n\'\'\'NOTE:\'\'\' This can\'t be a float / decimal value, it has to be a whole number!\n\nAlthough the distance can be changed easily once shoes is running a race, the race will not end until the determined amount of ticks is reached. \n\nNow to compile and upload your firmware to the arduino:\n# Go to the firmware directory (ex: ~/Desktop/opensprints/firmware/arduino/basic_msg/)\n# Type the \'\'\'make clean\'\'\' command.\n# Type the \'\'\'make\'\'\' command.\n# Attach the Arduino to your computer.\n# Run the command \'\'\'make upload\'\'\'.\n# You are now ready to run OpenSprints!\n\n\'\'\'NOTE:\'\'\' If \'\'make\'\' fails, you may have made a typo while editing the basic_message.pde file or some of your dependencies may be missing.\n\n===advanced_message BETA===\n\n\'\'\'NOTE:\'\'\' This version is still in testing, proceed at your own risk.\n\nDoes not require the above editing of source code. Just compile and upload your firmware to the arduino. From the firmware directory, type the \"make\" command. If that fails some of your dependencies may be missing.\n\nIf that is successful, attach the arduino to your computer and run the command \"make upload\". If that is successful, you are ready to run opensprints.\n\n==  Verifying the hardware ==\n\nConnect all the hardware together: the sensors connected to the interface board with ethernet cables, the programmed Arduino mounted on the interface board, and the Arduino connected to the computer with a USB cable.\n\n=== Setup for testing under Linux ===\n# Run \'\'gtkterm\'\'\n# Configure the port (Configuration -> Port) and select the following values:\n#* Port: \'\'/dev/ttyUSB0\'\'\n#* Speed: \'\'115200\'\'\n#* Parity: \'\'none\'\'\n#* Bits: \'\'8\'\'\n#* Stopbits: \'\'1\'\'\n#* Flow Control: \'\'none\'\'\n#* End of line delay: \'\'0\'\'\n\n=== Setup for testing under Mac OS X ===\n\n=== Setup for testing under Windows ===\n\n* Install and run [http://www.chiark.greenend.org.uk/~sgtatham/putty/download.html PuTTY].\n* With the Arduino connect to the PC, go to Hardware Manager and determine which COM port the Arduino is connected to.\n* Configure the port:\n** Click on the \'\'Serial\'\' radio button.\n** \'\'COM?\'\', as determined in previous step.\n** As far as I remember, everything else should be default.\n\n=== Running a fake race ===\n\nOnce the chosen terminal is configured as per the previous step, you should see a cursor with nothing going on. Type the letter \'g\' on the keyboard. Nothing should happen for a few seconds (during the countdown - \"4, 3, 2, 1, 0, go!\"). Then you should see a stream of numbers and letters filling the screen.\n\nThis is an example of what you might see in the terminal at an instant:\n<pre>\n1: 0\n2: 0\n3: 0\n4: 0\nt: 15311\n</pre>\n\nTest the hardware by waving a magnet in front of the hall effect sensor. (Turn the magnet around until the \'\'tick\'\' LED flashes. That will be the correct orientation of the magnet.)\n\nEvery time you wave a magnet in front of the hall effect sensor you will see the number following the corresponding sensor increment. So if you caused a tick on sensor 2, the following report will look like this:\n<pre>\n1: 0\n2: 1\n3: 0\n4: 0\nt: 15562\n</pre>\n\nAt this point, if all the sensors are behaving as expected, it\'s time to install and start running the PC application. Check out the page on [[Software Installation|software installation]].\n\n== Finally! Execute the Opensprints GUI ==\n\n# Simply run shoes by double-clicking it on your desktop\n# Then click \"Open an app\"\n# Browse to ~/opensprints/main.rb\n\n== Common faults ==\n\n= Mac OS X =\n\n# Grab a copy of the latest code: http://github.com/evanfarrar/opensprints/zipball/master\n# Get the serproxy program from Arduino\'s website and extract it somewhere like the opensprints directory: http://download.berlios.de/arduino/serproxy-0.1.3-3.bin.macosx.zip\n# Install the Arduino Development suite and the USB Serial Drivers: http://arduino.cc/en/Guide/MacOSX\n# Edit the serproxy.cfg  included in opensprints\' main directory to use your arduino\'s address. There is a line that says \"serial_device1=/dev/ttyUSB0\". Change it to something like \"/dev/cu.usbserial-A9005fET\" (if you browse around in the finder you should be able to find the exact address).\n# run the serproxy program from a terminal: \"cd ~/Desktop/opensprints; ./serproxy serproxy.cfg\"\n# edit your conf.yml to use the sensor named \"network\"\n# Get the latest version of shoes and use it to open \"opensprints/main.rb\" : http://shoooes.net/dist/shoes2.dmg\n\n= Windows =\n\n# Grab a copy of the latest code: http://github.com/evanfarrar/opensprints/zipball/master\n# Get the serproxy program from the Arduino [http://www.arduino.cc/en/Main/Software website] and extract it somewhere like the opensprints directory.\n# Get the Arduino Development platform and USB serial drivers: http://arduino.cc/en/Guide/Windows\n# Get shoes: http://shoooes.net/','utf-8'),(526,'\'\'Currently the software only runs on a Linux system. If you are unfamiliar with the system this can seem a bit daunting, however there are a few tips and ideas for getting the system up and running as quick as possible.\'\'\n\n= Linux =\n\nWe recommend using the Ubuntu distribution of Linux, and here are 4 ways of installing Ubuntu:\n\n# Use [http://www.pendrivelinux.com/ubuntu-810-persistent-flash-drive-install-from-live-cd/ Pen Drive Linux], aka, make a bootable 2GB USB thumb drive that you can put in any Windows computer capable of booting off a USB device.\n# [https://help.ubuntu.com/community/Installation Install Ubuntu] as your only operating system.  Use this option if you already use Linux as a desktop operating system or have an extra computer that you don\'t mind dedicating to OpenSprints.\n# [https://help.ubuntu.com/community/WindowsDualBoot Dual Boot Ubuntu and Windows].  Use this option if you have extra hard drive space to spare.\n# Use [http://wubi-installer.org Wubi] to install Ubuntu on Windows as if it were just another program.  A tutorial/memoir of the wubi/opensprints software installation process on an inexpensive acer laptop, as well as the problems encountered can be found [http://docs.google.com/Doc?id=dd4kx4mt_278gh78kgcq here].\n\nChances are that you will be promoting an event, so you don\'t want the system to fail.  With that in mind, either bring a few computers to the event as backups and use the Pen Drive method, or dedicate a laptop or two to OpenSprints and spare them from daily wear and tear.\n\n== Installing Linux ==\n\n=== Step 1: Creating a bootable Ubuntu 8.10 persistent thumbdrive ===\n\n[[Image:sandisk-4gb-cruzer-u3-micro-usb-flash-drive.jpg|thumb|right|Sandisk 4GB Cruzer U3 Micro USB Flash Drive]]\n\nThe entire Ubuntu Linux operating system as well as the other software packages can be stored on a single 2GB thumb drive and be moved to any machine with little if any changes. The persistent thumbdrive installs a special copy of ubuntu that saves all changes and software packages to the thumbdrive, so no changes are lost. If your laptop currently has a windows operating system, it will remain intact and the whole setup becomes very portable and non-intrusive.\n\n\'\'\'Pen Drive Install\'\'\'\n\n[[Image:unetbootin.jpg|UNetbootin configured to install Ubuntu 8.10 Live on the E:\\ drive which is a USB device]]\n\n# Download the latest version of [http://unetbootin.sourceforge.net/ UNetbootin] \n# Insert an empty 2GB or greater Thumb drive, [http://www.u3.com/uninstall/ delete the U3 partition] if need be.\n# Run UNetbootin\n# Select the \'\'Distribution\'\' radio button, \'\'Ubuntu\'\' dropdown option, \'\'8.**_Live\'\' dropdown option\n#* \'\'\'Optional:\'\'\' You may want to consider downloading the ISO separately, that way you don\'t have to re-download if you have to do it again.\n# Select the \'\'Show all Drives\'\' checkbox, Type \'\'USB Drive\'\', Drive ??? \'\'\'NOTE:\'\'\' You will erase whatever drive letter you pick, so pick wisely.\n# Click the \'\'OK\'\' button.\n# Goto [http://unetbootin.sourceforge.net/diskimg/ http://unetbootin.sourceforge.net/diskimg/] and download one of the files (128mb.zip, 256mb.zip, or 512mb.zip) corresponding to the amount of persistent space you want (make sure the size of the persistent disk image is smaller than the free space you have on your USB drive).\n# Now extract the file \"casper.rw\" from the zip file to your USB drive.\n# Now edit D:\\syslinux.cfg (assuming D:\\ is where your USB drive is) and add in \"persistent\" at the end of the line that begins with \"append\", and save the file, so your syslinux.cfg should look something like this:\n \'\'\'BEFORE:\'\'\' append initrd=/ubninit file=/cdrom/preseed/ubuntu.seed boot=casper quiet splash --\n \'\'\'AFTER:\'\'\' append initrd=/ubninit file=/cdrom/preseed/ubuntu.seed boot=casper quiet splash \'\'\'persistent\'\'\' --\n\nCredit for the persistent install method and additional help on installing Ubuntu can be found at [https://wiki.ubuntu.com/LiveUsbPendrivePersistent Live USB Pendrive Persistent].\n\n=== Step 2: Changing the Default Boot Order in BIOS ===\n\n[[Image:cmos_bios_usb_boot.jpg|right|thumb|Example: CMOS BIOS]]\n[[Image:PhoenixBIOS_boot_order.jpg|right|thumb|Example: PhoenixBIOS]]\n\nEvery computer with a motherboard includes a special chip referred to as the BIOS (Basic Input/Output System). One of the primary jobs of BIOS is to search through a prioritized list of hardware devices to find a bootable operating system.  Most of the time you are booting off a hard drive, where an operating system is installed.  For the purposes of OpenSprints, you will need to boot off a USB device.\n\n# Getting a machine BIOS to boot from the USB drive will differ from computer to computer, typically with in the first 5 seconds of booting your computer the on-screen instructions on how to \"Enter Setup\" or \"Enter BIOS\" will show which key(s) to press. They are commonly F2, F12, or Delete. You will have to press this key immediately after powering on your system, it\'s easy to miss and have it load windows instead, if this happens simply reboot and try again.\n# Once in the BIOS, the drive boot order list has to be located and change in order to boot from the USB drive first. Search through your BIOS options until you see the option to change the boot order from the current hard drive (Eg. ATA/IDE HDD) to the USB thumb drive (AKA: Removeable Devices, USB Mass Storage, External USB Device).\n# Make sure to save changes before exiting the BIOS (sometimes when you exit it will prompt you for this).\n# After leaving the BIOS, the next reboot should boot from the USB drive and bring up the Ubuntu operating system.\n# The Ubuntu boot screen will have options for booting \"Persistent\", select this option (In practice you will just press enter twice at the ubuntu boot screen).\n\nCongratulations, you are now running Ubuntu Linux off of your USB Thumb drive in a persistent state (meaning everything you do going forward will be saved).\n\n=== Step 3: Establish an Internet Connection ===\n\nFirst, focus on getting your network connection to work, via either wired ethernet or wireless. Ubuntu\'s [https://help.ubuntu.com/community/NetworkManager NetworkManager] was designed make this as simple as possible.\n\nIf it doesn\'t work, your wireless or ethernet card doesn\'t have driver support by default.  If you are unable to get the internet to work, please consult the [http://ubuntuforums.org/search.php ubuntu forums]. Be sure to gather as much information on your hardware and network card via the hardware manuals and manufacture website etc.\n\n=== Step 4-7 Shortcut: Installation Script ===\n\nCut and paste the following code into a file on your <code>~/Desktop/</code> and call it <code>opensprints_installer.run</code>\n\n\'\'\'NOTE:\'\'\' You may need to change permissions on the file using <code>chmod 700 ~/Desktop/opensprints_installer.run</code>\n\n\'\'\'NOTE:\'\'\' Have your [[Main Board]] and USB 2.0 A / B Cable handy and ready to go.\n\n #!/bin/bash\n declare -r PI=3.14159265358979\n if [\'id -u\' != \"0\" ]; then\n echo \"You should be root to run this script.\"\n exit 1\n fi\n clear\n echo \"What is your race distance in meters?\"\n read -e RACE_DISTANCE\n echo \"What is your roller diameter in inches?\"\n read -e ROLLER_DIAMETER\n declare -r ROLLER_CIRCUMFERENCE = `echo $PI, $ROLLER_DIAMETER|awk \'{print 0.0254000 * $1 * $2}\'`\n declare -r RACE_LENGTH_TICKS = `echo $PI, $ROLLER_DIAMETER, $RACE_DISTANCE|awk \'{print $3 / (0.0254000 * $1 * $2)}\'`\n echo $ROLLER_CIRCUMFERENCE\n echo $RACE_LENGTH_TICKS\n sudo cp /etc/apt/sources.list /etc/apt/sources.list.backup\n sudo sed -i -e \"s/# deb/deb/g\" /etc/apt/sources.list\n sudo apt-get update\n sudo apt-get -y install gcc-avr avrdude avr-libc make gtkterm\n rm ~/Desktop/shoes2.run\n wget http://shoooes.net/dist/shoes2.run\n chmod 700 ~/Desktop/shoes2.run\n wget http://github.com/evanfarrar/opensprints/tarball/master\n tar -zxf ~/Desktop/*opensprints*.tar.gz\n rm ~/Desktop/*opensprints*.tar.gz\n mv ~/Desktop/*opensprints*/ ~/Desktop/opensprints\n #TODO: Set race_distance in conf-sample.yml to $RACE_DISTANCE\n sudo sed -i \'s/\"race_distance: 200\"/\"race_distance: $RACE_DISTANCE\"/g\' ~/Desktop/opensprints/conf-sample.yml\n #TODO: Set roller_circumference in conf-sample.yml to $ROLLER_CIRCUMFERENCE\n sudo sed -i \'s/\"roller_circumference: 1.0\"/\"roller_circumference: $ROLLER_CIRCUMFERENCE\"/g\' ~/Desktop/opensprints/conf-sample.yml\n cd ~/Desktop/opensprints/firmware/arduino/basic_msg/\n #TODO: Set raceLengthTicks in basic_msg.pde to $RACE_LENGTH_TICKS\n sudo sed -i \'s/\"raceLengthTicks=16\"/\"raceLengthTicks=$RACE_LENTH_TICKS\"/g\' ~/Desktop/opensprints/firmware/arduino/basic_msg/basic_msg.pde\n make clean\n make\n echo \"Connect the Arduino via USB and hit <enter>\"\n read continue\n make upload\n cd ~/Desktop/opensprints/\n xrandr --auto\n ~/Desktop/shoes2.run\n exit 0\n\n\'\'\'What does this do?\'\'\'\n\n* Add the universe repository and update apt-get. TODO: Limit repositories to exclude multiverse.\n* Download required software packages.\n* Download the shoes graphic library.\n* Download opensprints.\n* TODO: Ask for race distance & roller diameter, calculate and save appropriate config files.\n* Create Arduino HEX file.\n* TODO: Upload Arduino HEX file.\n\n=== Step 4: Installing necessary software packages ===\n\nThere are some software dependencies, so you will need to install a series of software packages in order to run opensprints as well as compile the necessary firmware for the Arduino controller.\n\n\'\'\'NOTE:\'\'\' If you haven\'t done so already you will need to [https://help.ubuntu.com/community/Repositories/Ubuntu add the universe repository] by uncommenting lines in /etc/apt/sources.list\n\nTo install software packages using an easy to use GUI interface:\n\n# Start and login to Ubuntu using the user you created.\n# Goto Applications --> Add / Remove\n# Select \"All available Applications\"\n# Type the package names (listed below) in the search function to find and install them.\n#* avrdude\n#* gcc-avr\n#* binutils\n#* avr-libc\n#* make\n#* gtkterm\n\nTo manually install the software packages issue the following command in a the command prompt (Applications --> Terminal):\n sudo apt-get update\n sudo apt-get install gcc-avr avrdude avr-libc make gtkterm\n\n\'\'\'NOTE:\'\'\' Avoid the temptation to upgrade existing packages, <code>sudo apt-get upgrade</code> will only fill up the free space on your USB device.\n\n=== Step 5: [http://help.shoooes.net/Installing.html Install the Graphics Library, Shoes] ===\n\n[[Image:downloading_shoes.jpg|thumb|right|Commands for downloading and executing shoes.]]\n[[Image:shoes.jpg]]\n\n# Download [http://shoooes.net/dist/shoes2.run Shoes] for Linux. <code>wget http://shoooes.net/dist/shoes2.run</code>\n# Save Shoes to the desktop (ex: ~/Desktop/shoes2.run)\n# Change file permissions: <code>chmod 700 ~/Desktop/shoes2.run</code>\n# To execute Shoes double click on the desktop icon or use the command: <code>./shoes2.run</code>\n\n== Step 6: Installing Opensprints Software ==\n\n# Download the latest version of the Opensprints software in [http://github.com/evanfarrar/opensprints/tarball/master tar] or [http://github.com/evanfarrar/opensprints/zipball/master zip] format from [http://github.com/evanfarrar/opensprints/tree/master github.com].\n# Untar or unzip the Opensprints software to ~/Desktop/opensprints/\n\n== Step 7: Programming the Arduino==\n\n[[Image:Arduino.jpg|thumb|right|Arduino USB Board]]\n\nThe Arduino microcontroller will need to be programmed with firmware. There are two firmware sources to choose from:\n\n# basic_msg -- programmed by Evan Farrar\n# advanced_msg --  programmed by Morgan (SF)\n# [http://www.arduino.cc/en/Main/Software arduino-00**] -- This is the Arduino panel software that is used to compile and burn hex firmware images to arduino MCs. It is included in the Opensprints software distribution linked above.\n\n===basic_message===\n\nBefore we can program the Arduino, we need to answer 3 math questions:\n\n# What is the \'\'race distance\'\' in meters?\n# What is the drum / \'\'roller circumference\'\' in meters?\n# How many times does the roller have to spin in order to finish the race?\n\n\'\'\'NOTE:\'\'\' If the following math is done incorrectly it will result in timing and finish errors.\n\n\'\'\'What is the race distance in meters?\'\'\'\n\nDetermine the distance you would like to race at. This is used for the animation.\n\nThis integer needs to match the \"race_distance:\" variable set in your \'\'\'[[conf.yml]]\'\'\' file, eg. in this case it would equal \"race_distance: 1400\"  If you are not familiar with this file yet, it is the main configuration file used by opensprints and is located at the root of the OS folder. The default is 200 (200 meters), so if you are just testing hardware, setting it to something low like 20 and then making sure your conf.yml matches later might make testing easier.\n\n\'\'\'What is the drum / roller circumference in meters?\'\'\'\n\nFind your roller circumference by multiplying the roller diameter by pi and converting to meters. This is for the calculations for time and winner.  Luckily Google Calculator does this for you.\n\n \'\'\'Examples:\'\'\'\n 2.25 inch (diameter) rollers: [http://www.google.com/search?q=(pi+*+2.25+in)+in+m (pi * 2.25 in) in m] = \'\'\'0.17954202 meters\'\'\'\n 3.0 inch (diameter) rollers: [http://www.google.com/search?q=(pi+*+3.0+in)+in+m (pi * 3.0 in) in m] = \'\'\'0.23938936 meters\'\'\'\n 4.5 inch (diameter) rollers: [http://www.google.com/search?q=(pi+*+4.5+in)+in+m (pi * 4.5 in) in m] = \'\'\'0.35908404 meters\'\'\'\n\nIf your roller isnt so easily calculated. Lets say its 23CM circumference. You want to err on the short side. The race animation will quit once the distance is reached and stop counting ticks. if the ticks have not been reached, the time will not be accurate or not operate at all.\n\n\n\'\'\'How many times does the roller have to spin in order to finish the race?\'\'\'\n\nWe will refer to each full rotation a \'\'tick\'\'.  Race distance (in meters) divided by the roller circumference (in meters) will give you the total number of ticks required to finish a race.  Here are some examples using Google Calculator and the earlier numbers:\n\n200 meter race distance divided by the circumference of 2.25 inch (diameter) rollers:\n [http://www.google.com/search?q=200+m+%2F+0.17954202+m 200 m / 0.17954202 m] = \'\'\'1,113.94536 ticks\'\'\'\n200 meter race distance divided by the circumference of 3.0 inch (diameter) rollers:\n [http://www.google.com/search?q=200+m+%2F+0.23938936+m 200 m / 0.23938936 m] = \'\'\'835.45902 ticks\'\'\'\n200 meter race distance divided by the circumference of 4.5 inch (diameter) rollers:\n [http://www.google.com/search?q=200+m+%2F+0.35908404+m 200 m / 0.35908404 m] = \'\'\'556.97268 ticks\'\'\'\n\n\'\'\'Programming the Arduino with basic_message\'\'\'\n\nFinally!  Now open a terminal window and change directory to the folder.\n  cd ~/Desktop/opensprints/firmware/arduino/basic_msg\n\nopen the basic_msg.pde with your favorite text editor (vim, nano)\n\nRound off the answer to our, \'\'how many times does the roller have to spin in order to finish the race\'\' question, edit the following line:\n  int raceLengthTicks = 1400;\n\n\'\'\'NOTE:\'\'\' This can\'t be a float / decimal value, it has to be a whole number!\n\nAlthough the distance can be changed easily once shoes is running a race, the race will not end until the determined amount of ticks is reached. \n\nNow to compile and upload your firmware to the arduino:\n# Go to the firmware directory (ex: ~/Desktop/opensprints/firmware/arduino/basic_msg/)\n# Type the \'\'\'make clean\'\'\' command.\n# Type the \'\'\'make\'\'\' command.\n# Attach the Arduino to your computer.\n# Run the command \'\'\'make upload\'\'\'.\n# You are now ready to run OpenSprints!\n\n\'\'\'NOTE:\'\'\' If \'\'make\'\' fails, you may have made a typo while editing the basic_message.pde file or some of your dependencies may be missing.\n\n===advanced_message BETA===\n\n\'\'\'NOTE:\'\'\' This version is still in testing, proceed at your own risk.\n\nDoes not require the above editing of source code. Just compile and upload your firmware to the arduino. From the firmware directory, type the \"make\" command. If that fails some of your dependencies may be missing.\n\nIf that is successful, attach the arduino to your computer and run the command \"make upload\". If that is successful, you are ready to run opensprints.\n\n==  Verifying the hardware ==\n\nConnect all the hardware together: the sensors connected to the interface board with ethernet cables, the programmed Arduino mounted on the interface board, and the Arduino connected to the computer with a USB cable.\n\n=== Setup for testing under Linux ===\n# Run \'\'gtkterm\'\'\n# Configure the port (Configuration -> Port) and select the following values:\n#* Port: \'\'/dev/ttyUSB0\'\'\n#* Speed: \'\'115200\'\'\n#* Parity: \'\'none\'\'\n#* Bits: \'\'8\'\'\n#* Stopbits: \'\'1\'\'\n#* Flow Control: \'\'none\'\'\n#* End of line delay: \'\'0\'\'\n\n=== Setup for testing under Mac OS X ===\n\n=== Setup for testing under Windows ===\n\n* Install and run [http://www.chiark.greenend.org.uk/~sgtatham/putty/download.html PuTTY].\n* With the Arduino connect to the PC, go to Hardware Manager and determine which COM port the Arduino is connected to.\n* Configure the port:\n** Click on the \'\'Serial\'\' radio button.\n** \'\'COM?\'\', as determined in previous step.\n** As far as I remember, everything else should be default.\n\n=== Running a fake race ===\n\nOnce the chosen terminal is configured as per the previous step, you should see a cursor with nothing going on. Type the letter \'g\' on the keyboard. Nothing should happen for a few seconds (during the countdown - \"4, 3, 2, 1, 0, go!\"). Then you should see a stream of numbers and letters filling the screen.\n\nThis is an example of what you might see in the terminal at an instant:\n<pre>\n1: 0\n2: 0\n3: 0\n4: 0\nt: 15311\n</pre>\n\nTest the hardware by waving a magnet in front of the hall effect sensor. (Turn the magnet around until the \'\'tick\'\' LED flashes. That will be the correct orientation of the magnet.)\n\nEvery time you wave a magnet in front of the hall effect sensor you will see the number following the corresponding sensor increment. So if you caused a tick on sensor 2, the following report will look like this:\n<pre>\n1: 0\n2: 1\n3: 0\n4: 0\nt: 15562\n</pre>\n\nAt this point, if all the sensors are behaving as expected, it\'s time to install and start running the PC application. Check out the page on [[Software Installation|software installation]].\n\n== Finally! Execute the Opensprints GUI ==\n\n# Simply run shoes by double-clicking it on your desktop\n# Then click \"Open an app\"\n# Browse to ~/opensprints/main.rb\n\n== Common faults ==\n\n= Mac OS X =\n\n# Grab a copy of the latest code: http://github.com/evanfarrar/opensprints/zipball/master\n# Get the serproxy program from Arduino\'s website and extract it somewhere like the opensprints directory: http://download.berlios.de/arduino/serproxy-0.1.3-3.bin.macosx.zip\n# Install the Arduino Development suite and the USB Serial Drivers: http://arduino.cc/en/Guide/MacOSX\n# Edit the serproxy.cfg  included in opensprints\' main directory to use your arduino\'s address. There is a line that says \"serial_device1=/dev/ttyUSB0\". Change it to something like \"/dev/cu.usbserial-A9005fET\" (if you browse around in the finder you should be able to find the exact address).\n# run the serproxy program from a terminal: \"cd ~/Desktop/opensprints; ./serproxy serproxy.cfg\"\n# edit your conf.yml to use the sensor named \"network\"\n# Get the latest version of shoes and use it to open \"opensprints/main.rb\" : http://shoooes.net/dist/shoes2.dmg\n\n= Windows =\n\n# Grab a copy of the latest code: http://github.com/evanfarrar/opensprints/zipball/master\n# Get the serproxy program from the Arduino [http://www.arduino.cc/en/Main/Software website] and extract it somewhere like the opensprints directory.\n# Get the Arduino Development platform and USB serial drivers: http://arduino.cc/en/Guide/Windows\n# Get shoes: http://shoooes.net/','utf-8'),(527,'\'\'Currently the software only runs on a Linux system. If you are unfamiliar with the system this can seem a bit daunting, however there are a few tips and ideas for getting the system up and running as quick as possible.\'\'\n\n= Linux =\n\nWe recommend using the Ubuntu distribution of Linux, and here are 4 ways of installing Ubuntu:\n\n# Use [http://www.pendrivelinux.com/ubuntu-810-persistent-flash-drive-install-from-live-cd/ Pen Drive Linux], aka, make a bootable 2GB USB thumb drive that you can put in any Windows computer capable of booting off a USB device.\n# [https://help.ubuntu.com/community/Installation Install Ubuntu] as your only operating system.  Use this option if you already use Linux as a desktop operating system or have an extra computer that you don\'t mind dedicating to OpenSprints.\n# [https://help.ubuntu.com/community/WindowsDualBoot Dual Boot Ubuntu and Windows].  Use this option if you have extra hard drive space to spare.\n# Use [http://wubi-installer.org Wubi] to install Ubuntu on Windows as if it were just another program.  A tutorial/memoir of the wubi/opensprints software installation process on an inexpensive acer laptop, as well as the problems encountered can be found [http://docs.google.com/Doc?id=dd4kx4mt_278gh78kgcq here].\n\nChances are that you will be promoting an event, so you don\'t want the system to fail.  With that in mind, either bring a few computers to the event as backups and use the Pen Drive method, or dedicate a laptop or two to OpenSprints and spare them from daily wear and tear.\n\n== Installing Linux ==\n\n=== Step 1: Creating a bootable Ubuntu 8.10 persistent thumbdrive ===\n\n[[Image:sandisk-4gb-cruzer-u3-micro-usb-flash-drive.jpg|thumb|right|Sandisk 4GB Cruzer U3 Micro USB Flash Drive]]\n\nThe entire Ubuntu Linux operating system as well as the other software packages can be stored on a single 2GB thumb drive and be moved to any machine with little if any changes. The persistent thumbdrive installs a special copy of ubuntu that saves all changes and software packages to the thumbdrive, so no changes are lost. If your laptop currently has a windows operating system, it will remain intact and the whole setup becomes very portable and non-intrusive.\n\n\'\'\'Pen Drive Install\'\'\'\n\n[[Image:unetbootin.jpg|UNetbootin configured to install Ubuntu 8.10 Live on the E:\\ drive which is a USB device]]\n\n# Download the latest version of [http://unetbootin.sourceforge.net/ UNetbootin] \n# Insert an empty 2GB or greater Thumb drive, [http://www.u3.com/uninstall/ delete the U3 partition] if need be.\n# Run UNetbootin\n# Select the \'\'Distribution\'\' radio button, \'\'Ubuntu\'\' dropdown option, \'\'8.**_Live\'\' dropdown option\n#* \'\'\'Optional:\'\'\' You may want to consider downloading the ISO separately, that way you don\'t have to re-download if you have to do it again.\n# Select the \'\'Show all Drives\'\' checkbox, Type \'\'USB Drive\'\', Drive ??? \'\'\'NOTE:\'\'\' You will erase whatever drive letter you pick, so pick wisely.\n# Click the \'\'OK\'\' button.\n# Goto [http://unetbootin.sourceforge.net/diskimg/ http://unetbootin.sourceforge.net/diskimg/] and download one of the files (128mb.zip, 256mb.zip, or 512mb.zip) corresponding to the amount of persistent space you want (make sure the size of the persistent disk image is smaller than the free space you have on your USB drive).\n# Now extract the file \"casper.rw\" from the zip file to your USB drive.\n# Now edit D:\\syslinux.cfg (assuming D:\\ is where your USB drive is) and add in \"persistent\" at the end of the line that begins with \"append\", and save the file, so your syslinux.cfg should look something like this:\n \'\'\'BEFORE:\'\'\' append initrd=/ubninit file=/cdrom/preseed/ubuntu.seed boot=casper quiet splash --\n \'\'\'AFTER:\'\'\' append initrd=/ubninit file=/cdrom/preseed/ubuntu.seed boot=casper quiet splash \'\'\'persistent\'\'\' --\n\nCredit for the persistent install method and additional help on installing Ubuntu can be found at [https://wiki.ubuntu.com/LiveUsbPendrivePersistent Live USB Pendrive Persistent].\n\n=== Step 2: Changing the Default Boot Order in BIOS ===\n\n[[Image:cmos_bios_usb_boot.jpg|right|thumb|Example: CMOS BIOS]]\n[[Image:PhoenixBIOS_boot_order.jpg|right|thumb|Example: PhoenixBIOS]]\n\nEvery computer with a motherboard includes a special chip referred to as the BIOS (Basic Input/Output System). One of the primary jobs of BIOS is to search through a prioritized list of hardware devices to find a bootable operating system.  Most of the time you are booting off a hard drive, where an operating system is installed.  For the purposes of OpenSprints, you will need to boot off a USB device.\n\n# Getting a machine BIOS to boot from the USB drive will differ from computer to computer, typically with in the first 5 seconds of booting your computer the on-screen instructions on how to \"Enter Setup\" or \"Enter BIOS\" will show which key(s) to press. They are commonly F2, F12, or Delete. You will have to press this key immediately after powering on your system, it\'s easy to miss and have it load windows instead, if this happens simply reboot and try again.\n# Once in the BIOS, the drive boot order list has to be located and change in order to boot from the USB drive first. Search through your BIOS options until you see the option to change the boot order from the current hard drive (Eg. ATA/IDE HDD) to the USB thumb drive (AKA: Removeable Devices, USB Mass Storage, External USB Device).\n# Make sure to save changes before exiting the BIOS (sometimes when you exit it will prompt you for this).\n# After leaving the BIOS, the next reboot should boot from the USB drive and bring up the Ubuntu operating system.\n# The Ubuntu boot screen will have options for booting \"Persistent\", select this option (In practice you will just press enter twice at the ubuntu boot screen).\n\nCongratulations, you are now running Ubuntu Linux off of your USB Thumb drive in a persistent state (meaning everything you do going forward will be saved).\n\n=== Step 3: Establish an Internet Connection ===\n\nFirst, focus on getting your network connection to work, via either wired ethernet or wireless. Ubuntu\'s [https://help.ubuntu.com/community/NetworkManager NetworkManager] was designed make this as simple as possible.\n\nIf it doesn\'t work, your wireless or ethernet card doesn\'t have driver support by default.  If you are unable to get the internet to work, please consult the [http://ubuntuforums.org/search.php ubuntu forums]. Be sure to gather as much information on your hardware and network card via the hardware manuals and manufacture website etc.\n\n=== Step 4-7 Shortcut: Installation Script ===\n\nCut and paste the following code into a file on your <code>~/Desktop/</code> and call it <code>opensprints_installer.run</code>\n\n\'\'\'NOTE:\'\'\' You may need to change permissions on the file using <code>chmod 700 ~/Desktop/opensprints_installer.run</code>\n\n\'\'\'NOTE:\'\'\' Have your [[Main Board]] and USB 2.0 A / B Cable handy and ready to go.\n\n #!/bin/bash\n declare -r PI=3.14159265358979\n if [\'id -u\' != \"0\" ]; then\n echo \"You should be root to run this script.\"\n exit 1\n fi\n clear\n echo \"What is your race distance in meters?\"\n read -e RACE_DISTANCE\n echo \"What is your roller diameter in inches?\"\n read -e ROLLER_DIAMETER\n declare -r ROLLER_CIRCUMFERENCE = `echo $PI, $ROLLER_DIAMETER|awk \'{print 0.0254000 * $1 * $2}\'`\n declare -r RACE_LENGTH_TICKS = `echo $PI, $ROLLER_DIAMETER, $RACE_DISTANCE|awk \'{print $3 / (0.0254000 * $1 * $2)}\'`\n echo $ROLLER_CIRCUMFERENCE\n echo $RACE_LENGTH_TICKS\n sudo cp /etc/apt/sources.list /etc/apt/sources.list.backup\n sudo sed -i -e \"s/# deb/deb/g\" /etc/apt/sources.list\n sudo apt-get update\n sudo apt-get -y install gcc-avr avrdude avr-libc make gtkterm\n rm ~/Desktop/shoes2.run\n wget http://shoooes.net/dist/shoes2.run\n chmod 700 ~/Desktop/shoes2.run\n wget http://github.com/evanfarrar/opensprints/tarball/master\n tar -zxf ~/Desktop/*opensprints*.tar.gz\n rm ~/Desktop/*opensprints*.tar.gz\n mv ~/Desktop/*opensprints*/ ~/Desktop/opensprints\n #TODO: Set race_distance in conf-sample.yml to $RACE_DISTANCE\n sudo sed -i \"s/\'race_distance: 200\'/\'race_distance: $RACE_DISTANCE\'/g\" ~/Desktop/opensprints/conf-sample.yml\n #TODO: Set roller_circumference in conf-sample.yml to $ROLLER_CIRCUMFERENCE\n sudo sed -i \"s/\'roller_circumference: 1.0\'/\'roller_circumference: $ROLLER_CIRCUMFERENCE\'/g\" ~/Desktop/opensprints/conf-sample.yml\n cd ~/Desktop/opensprints/firmware/arduino/basic_msg/\n #TODO: Set raceLengthTicks in basic_msg.pde to $RACE_LENGTH_TICKS\n sudo sed -i \"s/\'raceLengthTicks=16\'/\'raceLengthTicks=$RACE_LENTH_TICKS\'/g\" ~/Desktop/opensprints/firmware/arduino/basic_msg/basic_msg.pde\n make clean\n make\n echo \"Connect the Arduino via USB and hit <enter>\"\n read continue\n make upload\n cd ~/Desktop/opensprints/\n xrandr --auto\n ~/Desktop/shoes2.run\n exit 0\n\n\'\'\'What does this do?\'\'\'\n\n* Add the universe repository and update apt-get. TODO: Limit repositories to exclude multiverse.\n* Download required software packages.\n* Download the shoes graphic library.\n* Download opensprints.\n* TODO: Ask for race distance & roller diameter, calculate and save appropriate config files.\n* Create Arduino HEX file.\n* TODO: Upload Arduino HEX file.\n\n=== Step 4: Installing necessary software packages ===\n\nThere are some software dependencies, so you will need to install a series of software packages in order to run opensprints as well as compile the necessary firmware for the Arduino controller.\n\n\'\'\'NOTE:\'\'\' If you haven\'t done so already you will need to [https://help.ubuntu.com/community/Repositories/Ubuntu add the universe repository] by uncommenting lines in /etc/apt/sources.list\n\nTo install software packages using an easy to use GUI interface:\n\n# Start and login to Ubuntu using the user you created.\n# Goto Applications --> Add / Remove\n# Select \"All available Applications\"\n# Type the package names (listed below) in the search function to find and install them.\n#* avrdude\n#* gcc-avr\n#* binutils\n#* avr-libc\n#* make\n#* gtkterm\n\nTo manually install the software packages issue the following command in a the command prompt (Applications --> Terminal):\n sudo apt-get update\n sudo apt-get install gcc-avr avrdude avr-libc make gtkterm\n\n\'\'\'NOTE:\'\'\' Avoid the temptation to upgrade existing packages, <code>sudo apt-get upgrade</code> will only fill up the free space on your USB device.\n\n=== Step 5: [http://help.shoooes.net/Installing.html Install the Graphics Library, Shoes] ===\n\n[[Image:downloading_shoes.jpg|thumb|right|Commands for downloading and executing shoes.]]\n[[Image:shoes.jpg]]\n\n# Download [http://shoooes.net/dist/shoes2.run Shoes] for Linux. <code>wget http://shoooes.net/dist/shoes2.run</code>\n# Save Shoes to the desktop (ex: ~/Desktop/shoes2.run)\n# Change file permissions: <code>chmod 700 ~/Desktop/shoes2.run</code>\n# To execute Shoes double click on the desktop icon or use the command: <code>./shoes2.run</code>\n\n== Step 6: Installing Opensprints Software ==\n\n# Download the latest version of the Opensprints software in [http://github.com/evanfarrar/opensprints/tarball/master tar] or [http://github.com/evanfarrar/opensprints/zipball/master zip] format from [http://github.com/evanfarrar/opensprints/tree/master github.com].\n# Untar or unzip the Opensprints software to ~/Desktop/opensprints/\n\n== Step 7: Programming the Arduino==\n\n[[Image:Arduino.jpg|thumb|right|Arduino USB Board]]\n\nThe Arduino microcontroller will need to be programmed with firmware. There are two firmware sources to choose from:\n\n# basic_msg -- programmed by Evan Farrar\n# advanced_msg --  programmed by Morgan (SF)\n# [http://www.arduino.cc/en/Main/Software arduino-00**] -- This is the Arduino panel software that is used to compile and burn hex firmware images to arduino MCs. It is included in the Opensprints software distribution linked above.\n\n===basic_message===\n\nBefore we can program the Arduino, we need to answer 3 math questions:\n\n# What is the \'\'race distance\'\' in meters?\n# What is the drum / \'\'roller circumference\'\' in meters?\n# How many times does the roller have to spin in order to finish the race?\n\n\'\'\'NOTE:\'\'\' If the following math is done incorrectly it will result in timing and finish errors.\n\n\'\'\'What is the race distance in meters?\'\'\'\n\nDetermine the distance you would like to race at. This is used for the animation.\n\nThis integer needs to match the \"race_distance:\" variable set in your \'\'\'[[conf.yml]]\'\'\' file, eg. in this case it would equal \"race_distance: 1400\"  If you are not familiar with this file yet, it is the main configuration file used by opensprints and is located at the root of the OS folder. The default is 200 (200 meters), so if you are just testing hardware, setting it to something low like 20 and then making sure your conf.yml matches later might make testing easier.\n\n\'\'\'What is the drum / roller circumference in meters?\'\'\'\n\nFind your roller circumference by multiplying the roller diameter by pi and converting to meters. This is for the calculations for time and winner.  Luckily Google Calculator does this for you.\n\n \'\'\'Examples:\'\'\'\n 2.25 inch (diameter) rollers: [http://www.google.com/search?q=(pi+*+2.25+in)+in+m (pi * 2.25 in) in m] = \'\'\'0.17954202 meters\'\'\'\n 3.0 inch (diameter) rollers: [http://www.google.com/search?q=(pi+*+3.0+in)+in+m (pi * 3.0 in) in m] = \'\'\'0.23938936 meters\'\'\'\n 4.5 inch (diameter) rollers: [http://www.google.com/search?q=(pi+*+4.5+in)+in+m (pi * 4.5 in) in m] = \'\'\'0.35908404 meters\'\'\'\n\nIf your roller isnt so easily calculated. Lets say its 23CM circumference. You want to err on the short side. The race animation will quit once the distance is reached and stop counting ticks. if the ticks have not been reached, the time will not be accurate or not operate at all.\n\n\n\'\'\'How many times does the roller have to spin in order to finish the race?\'\'\'\n\nWe will refer to each full rotation a \'\'tick\'\'.  Race distance (in meters) divided by the roller circumference (in meters) will give you the total number of ticks required to finish a race.  Here are some examples using Google Calculator and the earlier numbers:\n\n200 meter race distance divided by the circumference of 2.25 inch (diameter) rollers:\n [http://www.google.com/search?q=200+m+%2F+0.17954202+m 200 m / 0.17954202 m] = \'\'\'1,113.94536 ticks\'\'\'\n200 meter race distance divided by the circumference of 3.0 inch (diameter) rollers:\n [http://www.google.com/search?q=200+m+%2F+0.23938936+m 200 m / 0.23938936 m] = \'\'\'835.45902 ticks\'\'\'\n200 meter race distance divided by the circumference of 4.5 inch (diameter) rollers:\n [http://www.google.com/search?q=200+m+%2F+0.35908404+m 200 m / 0.35908404 m] = \'\'\'556.97268 ticks\'\'\'\n\n\'\'\'Programming the Arduino with basic_message\'\'\'\n\nFinally!  Now open a terminal window and change directory to the folder.\n  cd ~/Desktop/opensprints/firmware/arduino/basic_msg\n\nopen the basic_msg.pde with your favorite text editor (vim, nano)\n\nRound off the answer to our, \'\'how many times does the roller have to spin in order to finish the race\'\' question, edit the following line:\n  int raceLengthTicks = 1400;\n\n\'\'\'NOTE:\'\'\' This can\'t be a float / decimal value, it has to be a whole number!\n\nAlthough the distance can be changed easily once shoes is running a race, the race will not end until the determined amount of ticks is reached. \n\nNow to compile and upload your firmware to the arduino:\n# Go to the firmware directory (ex: ~/Desktop/opensprints/firmware/arduino/basic_msg/)\n# Type the \'\'\'make clean\'\'\' command.\n# Type the \'\'\'make\'\'\' command.\n# Attach the Arduino to your computer.\n# Run the command \'\'\'make upload\'\'\'.\n# You are now ready to run OpenSprints!\n\n\'\'\'NOTE:\'\'\' If \'\'make\'\' fails, you may have made a typo while editing the basic_message.pde file or some of your dependencies may be missing.\n\n===advanced_message BETA===\n\n\'\'\'NOTE:\'\'\' This version is still in testing, proceed at your own risk.\n\nDoes not require the above editing of source code. Just compile and upload your firmware to the arduino. From the firmware directory, type the \"make\" command. If that fails some of your dependencies may be missing.\n\nIf that is successful, attach the arduino to your computer and run the command \"make upload\". If that is successful, you are ready to run opensprints.\n\n==  Verifying the hardware ==\n\nConnect all the hardware together: the sensors connected to the interface board with ethernet cables, the programmed Arduino mounted on the interface board, and the Arduino connected to the computer with a USB cable.\n\n=== Setup for testing under Linux ===\n# Run \'\'gtkterm\'\'\n# Configure the port (Configuration -> Port) and select the following values:\n#* Port: \'\'/dev/ttyUSB0\'\'\n#* Speed: \'\'115200\'\'\n#* Parity: \'\'none\'\'\n#* Bits: \'\'8\'\'\n#* Stopbits: \'\'1\'\'\n#* Flow Control: \'\'none\'\'\n#* End of line delay: \'\'0\'\'\n\n=== Setup for testing under Mac OS X ===\n\n=== Setup for testing under Windows ===\n\n* Install and run [http://www.chiark.greenend.org.uk/~sgtatham/putty/download.html PuTTY].\n* With the Arduino connect to the PC, go to Hardware Manager and determine which COM port the Arduino is connected to.\n* Configure the port:\n** Click on the \'\'Serial\'\' radio button.\n** \'\'COM?\'\', as determined in previous step.\n** As far as I remember, everything else should be default.\n\n=== Running a fake race ===\n\nOnce the chosen terminal is configured as per the previous step, you should see a cursor with nothing going on. Type the letter \'g\' on the keyboard. Nothing should happen for a few seconds (during the countdown - \"4, 3, 2, 1, 0, go!\"). Then you should see a stream of numbers and letters filling the screen.\n\nThis is an example of what you might see in the terminal at an instant:\n<pre>\n1: 0\n2: 0\n3: 0\n4: 0\nt: 15311\n</pre>\n\nTest the hardware by waving a magnet in front of the hall effect sensor. (Turn the magnet around until the \'\'tick\'\' LED flashes. That will be the correct orientation of the magnet.)\n\nEvery time you wave a magnet in front of the hall effect sensor you will see the number following the corresponding sensor increment. So if you caused a tick on sensor 2, the following report will look like this:\n<pre>\n1: 0\n2: 1\n3: 0\n4: 0\nt: 15562\n</pre>\n\nAt this point, if all the sensors are behaving as expected, it\'s time to install and start running the PC application. Check out the page on [[Software Installation|software installation]].\n\n== Finally! Execute the Opensprints GUI ==\n\n# Simply run shoes by double-clicking it on your desktop\n# Then click \"Open an app\"\n# Browse to ~/opensprints/main.rb\n\n== Common faults ==\n\n= Mac OS X =\n\n# Grab a copy of the latest code: http://github.com/evanfarrar/opensprints/zipball/master\n# Get the serproxy program from Arduino\'s website and extract it somewhere like the opensprints directory: http://download.berlios.de/arduino/serproxy-0.1.3-3.bin.macosx.zip\n# Install the Arduino Development suite and the USB Serial Drivers: http://arduino.cc/en/Guide/MacOSX\n# Edit the serproxy.cfg  included in opensprints\' main directory to use your arduino\'s address. There is a line that says \"serial_device1=/dev/ttyUSB0\". Change it to something like \"/dev/cu.usbserial-A9005fET\" (if you browse around in the finder you should be able to find the exact address).\n# run the serproxy program from a terminal: \"cd ~/Desktop/opensprints; ./serproxy serproxy.cfg\"\n# edit your conf.yml to use the sensor named \"network\"\n# Get the latest version of shoes and use it to open \"opensprints/main.rb\" : http://shoooes.net/dist/shoes2.dmg\n\n= Windows =\n\n# Grab a copy of the latest code: http://github.com/evanfarrar/opensprints/zipball/master\n# Get the serproxy program from the Arduino [http://www.arduino.cc/en/Main/Software website] and extract it somewhere like the opensprints directory.\n# Get the Arduino Development platform and USB serial drivers: http://arduino.cc/en/Guide/Windows\n# Get shoes: http://shoooes.net/','utf-8'),(528,'The \'\'\'Main Board\'\'\', aka the \'\'USB interface board\'\', is basically an Arduino piggyback board that provides a safe and convenient interconnect for the sensors. Ethernet cables are used to connect the sensors to the Arduino.\n\n== Notes ==\n\n* The breakaway headers are very sensitive to heat. When soldering in the pins, work fast or the plastic casing will melt around the pin causing it to lean or tilt.\n* The top of the interface/piggyback board is the side that has text.\n\n== Assembly ==\n\n[[Image:broken_male_header_pins.jpg|thumb|none|400px]]\n[[Image:male_header_pins_closeup.jpg|thumb|none|400px]]\n\n# Break the male breakaway headers into two 6-position strips and two 8-position strips.\n# Use the Arduino board to align the breakaway header on the piggyback board. Connect the male header pins\' longer sides to the female pins on the Arduino. With the top of the piggyback board facing the top of the Arduino, press the Arduino into the piggyback board so that the shorter sides of the male pins enter the corresponding holes on the piggyback board. Ensure that all pins align before pressing the Arduino onto the piggyback board. Then tack the end pins on each strip quickly. This will hold the strips in place firm enough for you to remove the Arduino and finish soldering the remaining pins.\n# Seat the Arduino on the interface board. NB: The OpenSprints system is compatible with multiple versions of the Arduino USB device. See the [[electronics parts list]] for more info.\n# Solder RJ45 jacks to the piggyback board, one for each roller.\n# Affix the USB interface board to the bottom of the SERPAC A-31 project box with four machine screws.\n# (Optionally) cut the face plates of the project box to make openings for the USB jack and the RJ45 jack(s), and slide the face plates into place on the project box. Alternatively, omit this step.  Here are the drawings for the parts if you wanted to get them cut:\n#* Enclosure: [http://www.serpac.com/Products/Aseries/a-31.aspx Click on the User Prints tab]\n#* Ethernet Jack: [http://catalog.tycoelectronics.com/TE/bin/TE.Connect?C=1&M=BYPN&TCPN=5555164-1&RQPN=5555164-1 Click on the Product Drawings]\n#* Arduino Board:[http://arduino.cc/en/Main/ArduinoBoardDuemilanove Schematic & Reference Design]\n\n[[Image:Interface board headers.JPG|thumb|none|400px]]\n[[Image:Interface board unmounted.JPG|thumb|none|400px]]\n[[Image:Interface board mounted above 1.jpg|thumb|none|400px]]\n[[Image:Interface board mounted side 1.jpg|thumb|none|400px]]','utf-8'),(529,'The \'\'\'Main Board\'\'\', aka the \'\'USB interface board\'\', is basically an Arduino piggyback board that provides a safe and convenient interconnect for the sensors. Ethernet cables are used to connect the sensors to the Arduino.\n\n== Notes ==\n\n* The breakaway headers are very sensitive to heat. When soldering in the pins, work fast or the plastic casing will melt around the pin causing it to lean or tilt.\n* The top of the interface/piggyback board is the side that has text.\n\n== Assembly ==\n\n[[Image:broken_male_header_pins.jpg|thumb|none|400px]]\n[[Image:male_header_pins_closeup.jpg|thumb|none|400px]]\n\n# Break the male breakaway headers into two 6-position strips and two 8-position strips.\n# Use the Arduino board to align the breakaway header on the piggyback board. Connect the male header pins\' longer sides to the female pins on the Arduino. With the top of the piggyback board facing the top of the Arduino, press the Arduino into the piggyback board so that the shorter sides of the male pins enter the corresponding holes on the piggyback board. Ensure that all pins align before pressing the Arduino onto the piggyback board. Then tack the end pins on each strip quickly. This will hold the strips in place firm enough for you to remove the Arduino and finish soldering the remaining pins.\n# Seat the Arduino on the interface board. NB: The OpenSprints system is compatible with multiple versions of the Arduino USB device. See the [[electronics parts list]] for more info.\n# Solder RJ45 jacks to the piggyback board, one for each roller.\n# Affix the USB interface board to the bottom of the SERPAC A-31 project box with four machine screws.\n# (Optionally) cut the face plates of the project box to make openings for the USB jack and the RJ45 jack(s), and slide the face plates into place on the project box. Alternatively, omit this step.  Here are the drawings for the parts if you wanted to get them cut:\n#* Enclosure: [http://www.serpac.com/Products/Aseries/a-31.aspx Click on the User Prints tab]\n#* Ethernet Jack: [http://catalog.tycoelectronics.com/TE/bin/TE.Connect?C=1&M=BYPN&TCPN=5555164-1&RQPN=5555164-1 Click on the Product Drawings]\n#* Arduino Board:[http://arduino.cc/en/Main/ArduinoBoardDuemilanove Schematic & Reference Design]\n\n[[Image:Interface board headers.JPG|thumb|none|400px]]\n[[Image:Interface board unmounted.JPG|thumb|none|400px]]\n[[Image:Interface board mounted above 1.jpg|thumb|none|400px]]\n[[Image:Interface board mounted side 1.jpg|thumb|none|400px]]\n\n== See Also ==\n\n* [[Hardware Assembly]]\n* [[Roller Sensor Boards]]','utf-8'),(530,'Other questions? Need direct support? Check out the [http://www.opensprints.com/forum/ forum].\n== Preparation ==\n\n=== Parts & Tools ===\n\nThe complete [[Electronics parts list]]\n\n=== [[Soldering Tips]] ===\n\n* LEDs will NOT work if installed backwards due to polarity, the longer side of the LED goes in the + hole.\n* Use caution when handling the hall effect sensors as they are sensitive to static electricity. Note that each hall sensor has a beveled side (usually printed on as well). This side should be soldered to face away from the magnet as it passes by. \n* Consider using different colored LED\'s for the \"tick\" indicator for each board.\n* Good through-hole soldering tutorial provided by [http://www.sparkfun.com/commerce/tutorial_info.php?tutorials_id=106 SparkFun].\n\n== Assembly ==\n\n=== USB Interface (Main) Board ===\n\nSee [[Main Board]]\n\n=== Sensor Boards ===\n\n Each bike requires a separate board.\n To avoid soldering a damaged board in a dark smokey bar, it is HIGHLY suggested that you make spare boards.\n\nSee [[Roller Sensor Boards]]\n\n== What\'s Next? ==\n\nNow that your hardware is fully assembled you need to install two things:\n# [[Software_Installation#Programing_the_Arduino|Firmware]] on the Arduino USB Board.\n# [[Software_Installation#basic_message|Software]] on a computer or USB Thumb drive.','utf-8'),(531,'The \'\'\'Main Board\'\'\', aka the \'\'USB interface board\'\', is basically an Arduino piggyback board that provides a safe and convenient interconnect for the sensors. Ethernet cables are used to connect the sensors to the Arduino.\n\n== Notes ==\n\n* The breakaway headers are very sensitive to heat. When soldering in the pins, work fast or the plastic casing will melt around the pin causing it to lean or tilt.\n* The top of the interface/piggyback board is the side that has text.\n\n== Assembly ==\n\n[[Image:broken_male_header_pins.jpg|thumb|none|400px]]\n[[Image:male_header_pins_closeup.jpg|thumb|none|400px]]\n\n# Break the male breakaway headers into two 6-position strips and two 8-position strips.\n# Use the Arduino board to align the breakaway header on the piggyback board. Connect the male header pins\' longer sides to the female pins on the Arduino. With the top of the piggyback board facing the top of the Arduino, press the Arduino into the piggyback board so that the shorter sides of the male pins enter the corresponding holes on the piggyback board. Ensure that all pins align before pressing the Arduino onto the piggyback board. Then tack the end pins on each strip quickly. This will hold the strips in place firm enough for you to remove the Arduino and finish soldering the remaining pins.\n# Seat the Arduino on the interface board. NB: The OpenSprints system is compatible with multiple versions of the Arduino USB device. See the [[electronics parts list]] for more info.\n# Solder RJ45 jacks to the piggyback board, one for each roller.\n# Affix the USB interface board to the bottom of the SERPAC A-31 project box with four machine screws.\n# (Optionally) cut the face plates of the project box to make openings for the USB jack and the RJ45 jack(s), and slide the face plates into place on the project box.  This will add much needed structural support to the enclosure in the event it is stepped on, however you can omit this step.  Here are the CAD drawings for the parts if you wanted to get them professionally cut:\n#* Enclosure: [http://www.serpac.com/Products/Aseries/a-31.aspx Click on the User Prints tab]\n#* Ethernet Jack: [http://catalog.tycoelectronics.com/TE/bin/TE.Connect?C=1&M=BYPN&TCPN=5555164-1&RQPN=5555164-1 Click on the Product Drawings]\n#* Arduino Board:[http://arduino.cc/en/Main/ArduinoBoardDuemilanove Schematic & Reference Design]\n\n\'\'\'NOTE:\'\'\' Do to a [[Hardware Bug]] in version 2 the USB / power side of the Arduino board sticks out too far making it difficult to cut out.\n\n[[Image:Interface board headers.JPG|thumb|none|400px]]\n[[Image:Interface board unmounted.JPG|thumb|none|400px]]\n[[Image:Interface board mounted above 1.jpg|thumb|none|400px]]\n[[Image:Interface board mounted side 1.jpg|thumb|none|400px]]\n\n== See Also ==\n\n* [[Hardware Assembly]]\n* [[Roller Sensor Boards]]','utf-8'),(532,'#REDIRECT [[Bugs]]','utf-8'),(533,'#REDIRECT [[Bugs]]','utf-8'),(534,'#REDIRECT [[Bugs]]','utf-8'),(535,'#REDIRECT [[Bugs]]','utf-8'),(536,'#REDIRECT [[Bugs]]','utf-8'),(537,'== Hardware ==\n\n# Tick Indicator LED doesn\'t blink on the [[Roller Sensor Boards]]\n# When sitting on the [[Main Board]], Arduino Board sticks out too far on the USB / Power side so that the enclosure can not be cut to fit.\n\n== Software ==\n\n\'\'\'In order of priority:\'\'\'\n# Windows support, we should be able to read off of a CDC device without blocking the whole thread\n# Killing off the buffer overrun. This could be solved a number of ways, please voice your opinions\n## moving game logic into the UBW, asking it occasionally for statistics in summary format.\n## a second buffer to read info off of the ubw quickly in a dedicated thread, possibly listening to interrupts  \n# Increase tick granularity, real races can have rpms higher than a centisecond.  \'\'What is the range of actual values observed for roller speed in rotations/second?\'\'\n# Rearchitect race data structure to keep a complete record of the race -- all times at which a bike sent a tick.  This will be used to support secondary calculations like power, and will provide easier access for graphing the data in more flexible ways.\n# Integrate new FW packet format into Ruby data collection setup -- start using a complete race representation rather than just \"distance accumulated\"\n\nTest entry by DH support\n\n== See Also ==\n\n* [[Feature Requests]]','utf-8'),(538,'Other questions? Need direct support? Check out the [http://www.opensprints.com/forum/ forum].\n\n== Sensor Board ==\n\n[[Image:sensor_board_finished.jpg|thumb|left|Sensor Board in Enclosure|400px]]\n\n\n=== HARDWARE HACK: Tick indicator LED ===\n\nThere is a [[hardware bug]] / mistake in the design of the v2 sensor PCB that prevents the tick indicator LED from lighting only when a magnet is triggering the hall sensor. The tick indicator LED cathode is incorrectly tied to GND instead of VOUT from the HE sensor. A fairly simple rework is required, and is described below.\n\nThe workaround involves routing the cathode, or shorter leg from the tick LED along the back to the VOUT pin labeled on the front. The anode, or longer leg should be installed in the \"+\" socket. However, the cathode or \"-\" side, will be installed in the hole just to the left of it instead of the open hole to the right (if you are looking at the top of the board). The spacing will be a bit more than the spacing optimal for the LED but can certainly be installed with no problems if done with care.\n\n=== Parts ===\n\nA list of all the required components can be found in the [[Electronics parts list]] page. \n\n=== Assembly ===\n\nSee the pictures to the right...\n\n[[Image:sensor_board_top.jpg|thumb|Top of the sensor board: Labels for the VCC, GND and VOUT traces. |400px]]\n[[Image:sensor_board_bottom.jpg|thumb|Bottom of the sensor board: The date and version text.|400px]]\n[[Image:sensor_board_and_resistors.jpg|thumb|Resistor colors from left to right: Gold, Brown, Orange, Orange|400px]]\n[[Image:sensor_board_with_resistors.jpg|thumb|Solder resistors in place.|400px]]\n[[Image:sensor_board_and_red_led.jpg|thumb|The power indicator LED is installed to the right. Take care when installing the LED, the longer leg, or anode, should be installed in the \"+\" socket.|400px]]\n[[Image:sensor_board_with_resistors.jpg|thumb|\'\'\'BEFORE:\'\'\' Longer side of Indicator LED goes below the \"+\" sign, and the shorter (cathode) side goes above the \"+\" sign.|400px]]\n[[Image:sensor_board_and_indicator_led.jpg|thumb|\'\'\'AFTER:\'\'\' With LED in place, the longer side of Indicator LED goes below the \"+\" sign, and the shorter (cathode) side goes above the \"+\" sign.|400px]]\n[[Image:sensor_board_and_indicator_led_closeup.jpg|thumb|Closeup: Indicator LED|400px]]\n[[Image:sensor_board_hack.jpg|thumb|Bend the shorter (cathode) side of Indicator LED over to the VOUT|400px]]\n[[Image:sensor_board_hack_closeup.jpg|thumb|Closeup: Bend the shorter (cathode) side of Indicator LED over to the VOUT|400px]]\n[[Image:sensor_board_and_hall_effect_sensor.jpg|thumb|The Hall sensor is installed across the top. Take care that the beveled edge (normally printed on) is facing the board and not away from it. |400px]]\n[[Image:sensor_board_and_hall_effect_sensor_closeup.jpg|thumb|Closeup: The Hall sensor is installed across the top. Take care that the beveled edge (normally printed on) is facing the board and not away from it.|400px]]\n[[Image:sensor_board_and_capacitor.jpg|thumb|The capacitor is installed just in front of the sensor.  Direction doesn\'t matter.|400px]]\n[[Image:sensor_board_and_capacitor_closeup.jpg|thumb|Closeup: The capacitor is installed just in front of the sensor.  Direction doesn\'t matter.|400px]]\n[[Image:sensor_board_with_rj45_jack.jpg|thumb|Next, solder one or both of the RJ45 jacks to the board. If only one jack is being used, it can be soldered to either position, as the two jacks are wired in parallel.|400px]]\n[[Image:sensore_board_enclosure.jpg|thumb|The sensor PCB is designed to fit well inside a SERPAC C-6 plastic enclosure, with slight modification to the enclosure.|400px]]\n[[Image:sensor_board_enclosure_pre_cutting.jpg|thumb|The bottom half of the enclosure is the side that has the boss that the fastener screws into. On the bottom half of the enclosure, one of the shorter walls gets shaved off far enough that the locking legs of the RJ45 jacks are outside the enclosure.|400px]]\n[[Image:sensor_board_finished.jpg|thumb|Attach the top half of the sensor enclosure, and screw it down.  If it vibrates too much, consider using hot glue.|400px]]\n\n=== See Also ===\n\n* [[Hardware Assembly]]\n* [[Software Installation]]','utf-8'),(539,'#REDIRECT [[Bugs]]','utf-8'),(540,'== Hardware ==\n\n[[Image:sensor_board_hack_closeup.jpg|thumb|Tick Indicator Hack: bend the shorter (cathode) side of Indicator LED over to the VOUT|400px]]\n\n# Tick Indicator LED doesn\'t blink on the [[Roller Sensor Boards]]\n# When sitting on the [[Main Board]], Arduino Board sticks out too far on the USB / Power side so that the enclosure can not be cut to fit.\n\n== Software ==\n\n\'\'\'In order of priority:\'\'\'\n# Windows support, we should be able to read off of a CDC device without blocking the whole thread\n# Killing off the buffer overrun. This could be solved a number of ways, please voice your opinions\n## moving game logic into the UBW, asking it occasionally for statistics in summary format.\n## a second buffer to read info off of the ubw quickly in a dedicated thread, possibly listening to interrupts  \n# Increase tick granularity, real races can have rpms higher than a centisecond.  \'\'What is the range of actual values observed for roller speed in rotations/second?\'\'\n# Rearchitect race data structure to keep a complete record of the race -- all times at which a bike sent a tick.  This will be used to support secondary calculations like power, and will provide easier access for graphing the data in more flexible ways.\n# Integrate new FW packet format into Ruby data collection setup -- start using a complete race representation rather than just \"distance accumulated\"\n\nTest entry by DH support\n\n== See Also ==\n\n* [[Feature Requests]]','utf-8'),(541,'== Software ==\n\n# Sounds: race start, racer finish, overall race finish\n# MPH added to game interface: current MPH per racer, max MPH per racer, average MPH per racer.\n# Custom backgrounds\n# Configuration file would ask for Roller Diameter (inches or centimeters) instead of Circumference and then the program would calculate circumference on its own using Diameter * PI with the appropriate unit conversion.\n# If the race distance was changed on saving the configuration file a new version of firmware would be automatically created and uploaded (for basic_msg).\n# Configuration file would default to basic_msg until advanced_msg was stable.\n# Put checkboxes next to each of the rollers that make the roller inputboxes active or inactive (instead of the No bike button).\n# Dump to an Error Log instead of relying on Alt-/ for troubleshooting.\n\n== Hardware ==\n\n# Printable schematic outlines for cutting away at the [[Main Board]] and [[Sensor Board]] enclosures / boxes.\n# REQUIRE Extra sensor board to come with kit to be built and used as a backup on race nights.  As an alternative to having to fix a board during a race, it would be nice to just swap out the unit.\n# Big [[OpenSprints]] logo sticker (including website URL) to fit on the top of the [[Main Board]] enclosure.\n# Just for effect, Light up [[Main Board]] enclosure like a computer case.\n# Complete kits similar to [http://www.adafruit.com/index.php?main_page=index&cPath=6 Spoke POV] whereas directions are online.  Kits should include extra [[roller sensor boards]] and should be for 4 rollers so that no upgrades are needed.  In addition to the kits, make an official recommendation for a person / place that will solder (and test) the boards for those that don\'t want to solder or buy the tools.\n\n== Web Services ==\n\n# Race result uploads for each city.\n# Race event listings.\n# Press Kit section on website for reporters and columnists.\n\n== Other ==\n\n# Logo\n# Stickers\n\n== See Also ==\n\n* [[Bugs]]','utf-8'),(542,'#REDIRECT [[Roller Sensor Boards]]','utf-8'),(543,'== See Also ==\n\n* [[Software Installation]]\n* [[Firmware Development]]','utf-8'),(544,'#REDIRECT [[Firmware Development]]','utf-8'),(545,'#REDIRECT [[Software & Firmware]]','utf-8'),(546,'#REDIRECT [[Software & Firmware]]','utf-8'),(547,'== See Also ==\n\n* [[Software Installation]]\n* [[Source Code]]\n* [[Firmware Development]]','utf-8'),(548,'\'\'Currently the software only runs on a Linux system. If you are unfamiliar with the system this can seem a bit daunting, however there are a few tips and ideas for getting the system up and running as quick as possible.\'\'\n\n= Linux =\n\nWe recommend using the Ubuntu distribution of Linux, and here are 4 ways of installing Ubuntu:\n\n# Use [http://www.pendrivelinux.com/ubuntu-810-persistent-flash-drive-install-from-live-cd/ Pen Drive Linux], aka, make a bootable 2GB USB thumb drive that you can put in any Windows computer capable of booting off a USB device.\n# [https://help.ubuntu.com/community/Installation Install Ubuntu] as your only operating system.  Use this option if you already use Linux as a desktop operating system or have an extra computer that you don\'t mind dedicating to OpenSprints.\n# [https://help.ubuntu.com/community/WindowsDualBoot Dual Boot Ubuntu and Windows].  Use this option if you have extra hard drive space to spare.\n# Use [http://wubi-installer.org Wubi] to install Ubuntu on Windows as if it were just another program.  A tutorial/memoir of the wubi/opensprints software installation process on an inexpensive acer laptop, as well as the problems encountered can be found [http://docs.google.com/Doc?id=dd4kx4mt_278gh78kgcq here].\n\nChances are that you will be promoting an event, so you don\'t want the system to fail.  With that in mind, either bring a few computers to the event as backups and use the Pen Drive method, or dedicate a laptop or two to OpenSprints and spare them from daily wear and tear.\n\n== Installing Linux ==\n\n=== Step 1: Creating a bootable Ubuntu 8.10 persistent thumbdrive ===\n\n[[Image:sandisk-4gb-cruzer-u3-micro-usb-flash-drive.jpg|thumb|right|Sandisk 4GB Cruzer U3 Micro USB Flash Drive]]\n\nThe entire Ubuntu Linux operating system as well as the other software packages can be stored on a single 2GB thumb drive and be moved to any machine with little if any changes. The persistent thumbdrive installs a special copy of ubuntu that saves all changes and software packages to the thumbdrive, so no changes are lost. If your laptop currently has a windows operating system, it will remain intact and the whole setup becomes very portable and non-intrusive.\n\n\'\'\'Pen Drive Install\'\'\'\n\n[[Image:unetbootin.jpg|UNetbootin configured to install Ubuntu 8.10 Live on the E:\\ drive which is a USB device]]\n[[Image:format_windows_drive.jpg|Format the thumb drive (Start-->Computer-->Right Click on Drive-->Format) to remove all files.]]\n\n# Download the latest version of [http://unetbootin.sourceforge.net/ UNetbootin] \n# Insert an empty 2GB or greater Thumb drive, [http://www.u3.com/uninstall/ delete the U3 partition] if need be.\n# Format the thumb drive (Start-->Computer-->Right Click on Drive-->Format) to remove all files.\n# Run UNetbootin\n# Select the \'\'Distribution\'\' radio button, \'\'Ubuntu\'\' dropdown option, \'\'8.**_Live\'\' dropdown option\n#* \'\'\'Optional:\'\'\' You may want to consider downloading the ISO separately, that way you don\'t have to re-download if you have to do it again.\n# Select the \'\'Show all Drives\'\' checkbox, Type \'\'USB Drive\'\', Drive ??? \'\'\'NOTE:\'\'\' You will erase whatever drive letter you pick, so pick wisely.\n# Click the \'\'OK\'\' button.\n# Goto [http://unetbootin.sourceforge.net/diskimg/ http://unetbootin.sourceforge.net/diskimg/] and download one of the files (128mb.zip, 256mb.zip, or 512mb.zip) corresponding to the amount of persistent space you want (make sure the size of the persistent disk image is smaller than the free space you have on your USB drive).\n# Now extract the file \"casper.rw\" from the zip file to your USB drive.\n# Now edit D:\\syslinux.cfg (assuming D:\\ is where your USB drive is) and add in \"persistent\" at the end of the line that begins with \"append\", and save the file, so your syslinux.cfg should look something like this:\n \'\'\'BEFORE:\'\'\' append initrd=/ubninit file=/cdrom/preseed/ubuntu.seed boot=casper quiet splash --\n \'\'\'AFTER:\'\'\' append initrd=/ubninit file=/cdrom/preseed/ubuntu.seed boot=casper quiet splash \'\'\'persistent\'\'\' --\n\nCredit for the persistent install method and additional help on installing Ubuntu can be found at [https://wiki.ubuntu.com/LiveUsbPendrivePersistent Live USB Pendrive Persistent].\n\n=== Step 2: Changing the Default Boot Order in BIOS ===\n\n[[Image:cmos_bios_usb_boot.jpg|right|thumb|Example: CMOS BIOS]]\n[[Image:PhoenixBIOS_boot_order.jpg|right|thumb|Example: PhoenixBIOS]]\n\nEvery computer with a motherboard includes a special chip referred to as the BIOS (Basic Input/Output System). One of the primary jobs of BIOS is to search through a prioritized list of hardware devices to find a bootable operating system.  Most of the time you are booting off a hard drive, where an operating system is installed.  For the purposes of OpenSprints, you will need to boot off a USB device.\n\n# Getting a machine BIOS to boot from the USB drive will differ from computer to computer, typically with in the first 5 seconds of booting your computer the on-screen instructions on how to \"Enter Setup\" or \"Enter BIOS\" will show which key(s) to press. They are commonly F2, F12, or Delete. You will have to press this key immediately after powering on your system, it\'s easy to miss and have it load windows instead, if this happens simply reboot and try again.\n# Once in the BIOS, the drive boot order list has to be located and change in order to boot from the USB drive first. Search through your BIOS options until you see the option to change the boot order from the current hard drive (Eg. ATA/IDE HDD) to the USB thumb drive (AKA: Removeable Devices, USB Mass Storage, External USB Device).\n# Make sure to save changes before exiting the BIOS (sometimes when you exit it will prompt you for this).\n# After leaving the BIOS, the next reboot should boot from the USB drive and bring up the Ubuntu operating system.\n# The Ubuntu boot screen will have options for booting \"Persistent\", select this option (In practice you will just press enter twice at the ubuntu boot screen).\n\nCongratulations, you are now running Ubuntu Linux off of your USB Thumb drive in a persistent state (meaning everything you do going forward will be saved).\n\n=== Step 3: Establish an Internet Connection ===\n\nFirst, focus on getting your network connection to work, via either wired ethernet or wireless. Ubuntu\'s [https://help.ubuntu.com/community/NetworkManager NetworkManager] was designed make this as simple as possible.\n\nIf it doesn\'t work, your wireless or ethernet card doesn\'t have driver support by default.  If you are unable to get the internet to work, please consult the [http://ubuntuforums.org/search.php ubuntu forums]. Be sure to gather as much information on your hardware and network card via the hardware manuals and manufacture website etc.\n\n=== Step 4-7 Shortcut: Installation Script ===\n\nCut and paste the following code into a file on your <code>~/Desktop/</code> and call it <code>opensprints_installer.run</code>\n\n\'\'\'NOTE:\'\'\' You may need to change permissions on the file using <code>chmod 700 ~/Desktop/opensprints_installer.run</code>\n\n\'\'\'NOTE:\'\'\' Have your [[Main Board]] and USB 2.0 A / B Cable handy and ready to go.\n\n #!/bin/bash\n declare -r PI=3.14159265358979\n if [\'id -u\' != \"0\" ]; then\n echo \"You should be root to run this script.\"\n exit 1\n fi\n clear\n echo \"What is your race distance in meters?\"\n read -e RACE_DISTANCE\n echo \"What is your roller diameter in inches?\"\n read -e ROLLER_DIAMETER\n declare -r ROLLER_CIRCUMFERENCE = `echo $PI, $ROLLER_DIAMETER|awk \'{print 0.0254000 * $1 * $2}\'`\n declare -r RACE_LENGTH_TICKS = `echo $PI, $ROLLER_DIAMETER, $RACE_DISTANCE|awk \'{print $3 / (0.0254000 * $1 * $2)}\'`\n echo $ROLLER_CIRCUMFERENCE\n echo $RACE_LENGTH_TICKS\n sudo cp /etc/apt/sources.list /etc/apt/sources.list.backup\n sudo sed -i -e \"s/# deb/deb/g\" /etc/apt/sources.list\n sudo apt-get update\n sudo apt-get -y install gcc-avr avrdude avr-libc make gtkterm\n rm ~/Desktop/shoes2.run\n wget http://shoooes.net/dist/shoes2.run\n chmod 700 ~/Desktop/shoes2.run\n wget http://github.com/evanfarrar/opensprints/tarball/master\n tar -zxf ~/Desktop/*opensprints*.tar.gz\n rm ~/Desktop/*opensprints*.tar.gz\n mv ~/Desktop/*opensprints*/ ~/Desktop/opensprints\n #TODO: Set race_distance in conf-sample.yml to $RACE_DISTANCE\n sudo sed -i \"s/\'race_distance: 200\'/\'race_distance: $RACE_DISTANCE\'/g\" ~/Desktop/opensprints/conf-sample.yml\n #TODO: Set roller_circumference in conf-sample.yml to $ROLLER_CIRCUMFERENCE\n sudo sed -i \"s/\'roller_circumference: 1.0\'/\'roller_circumference: $ROLLER_CIRCUMFERENCE\'/g\" ~/Desktop/opensprints/conf-sample.yml\n cd ~/Desktop/opensprints/firmware/arduino/basic_msg/\n #TODO: Set raceLengthTicks in basic_msg.pde to $RACE_LENGTH_TICKS\n sudo sed -i \"s/\'raceLengthTicks=16\'/\'raceLengthTicks=$RACE_LENTH_TICKS\'/g\" ~/Desktop/opensprints/firmware/arduino/basic_msg/basic_msg.pde\n make clean\n make\n echo \"Connect the Arduino via USB and hit <enter>\"\n read continue\n make upload\n cd ~/Desktop/opensprints/\n xrandr --auto\n ~/Desktop/shoes2.run\n exit 0\n\n\'\'\'What does this do?\'\'\'\n\n* Add the universe repository and update apt-get. TODO: Limit repositories to exclude multiverse.\n* Download required software packages.\n* Download the shoes graphic library.\n* Download opensprints.\n* TODO: Ask for race distance & roller diameter, calculate and save appropriate config files.\n* Create Arduino HEX file.\n* TODO: Upload Arduino HEX file.\n\n=== Step 4: Installing necessary software packages ===\n\nThere are some software dependencies, so you will need to install a series of software packages in order to run opensprints as well as compile the necessary firmware for the Arduino controller.\n\n\'\'\'NOTE:\'\'\' If you haven\'t done so already you will need to [https://help.ubuntu.com/community/Repositories/Ubuntu add the universe repository] by uncommenting lines in /etc/apt/sources.list\n\nTo install software packages using an easy to use GUI interface:\n\n# Start and login to Ubuntu using the user you created.\n# Goto Applications --> Add / Remove\n# Select \"All available Applications\"\n# Type the package names (listed below) in the search function to find and install them.\n#* avrdude\n#* gcc-avr\n#* binutils\n#* avr-libc\n#* make\n#* gtkterm\n\nTo manually install the software packages issue the following command in a the command prompt (Applications --> Terminal):\n sudo apt-get update\n sudo apt-get install gcc-avr avrdude avr-libc make gtkterm\n\n\'\'\'NOTE:\'\'\' Avoid the temptation to upgrade existing packages, <code>sudo apt-get upgrade</code> will only fill up the free space on your USB device.\n\n=== Step 5: [http://help.shoooes.net/Installing.html Install the Graphics Library, Shoes] ===\n\n[[Image:downloading_shoes.jpg|thumb|right|Commands for downloading and executing shoes.]]\n[[Image:shoes.jpg]]\n\n# Download [http://shoooes.net/dist/shoes2.run Shoes] for Linux. <code>wget http://shoooes.net/dist/shoes2.run</code>\n# Save Shoes to the desktop (ex: ~/Desktop/shoes2.run)\n# Change file permissions: <code>chmod 700 ~/Desktop/shoes2.run</code>\n# To execute Shoes double click on the desktop icon or use the command: <code>./shoes2.run</code>\n\n== Step 6: Installing Opensprints Software ==\n\n# Download the latest version of the Opensprints software in [http://github.com/evanfarrar/opensprints/tarball/master tar] or [http://github.com/evanfarrar/opensprints/zipball/master zip] format from [http://github.com/evanfarrar/opensprints/tree/master github.com].\n# Untar or unzip the Opensprints software to ~/Desktop/opensprints/\n\n== Step 7: Programming the Arduino==\n\n[[Image:Arduino.jpg|thumb|right|Arduino USB Board]]\n\nThe Arduino microcontroller will need to be programmed with firmware. There are two firmware sources to choose from:\n\n# basic_msg -- programmed by Evan Farrar\n# advanced_msg --  programmed by Morgan (SF)\n# [http://www.arduino.cc/en/Main/Software arduino-00**] -- This is the Arduino panel software that is used to compile and burn hex firmware images to arduino MCs. It is included in the Opensprints software distribution linked above.\n\n===basic_message===\n\nBefore we can program the Arduino, we need to answer 3 math questions:\n\n# What is the \'\'race distance\'\' in meters?\n# What is the drum / \'\'roller circumference\'\' in meters?\n# How many times does the roller have to spin in order to finish the race?\n\n\'\'\'NOTE:\'\'\' If the following math is done incorrectly it will result in timing and finish errors.\n\n\'\'\'What is the race distance in meters?\'\'\'\n\nDetermine the distance you would like to race at. This is used for the animation.\n\nThis integer needs to match the \"race_distance:\" variable set in your \'\'\'[[conf.yml]]\'\'\' file, eg. in this case it would equal \"race_distance: 1400\"  If you are not familiar with this file yet, it is the main configuration file used by opensprints and is located at the root of the OS folder. The default is 200 (200 meters), so if you are just testing hardware, setting it to something low like 20 and then making sure your conf.yml matches later might make testing easier.\n\n\'\'\'What is the drum / roller circumference in meters?\'\'\'\n\nFind your roller circumference by multiplying the roller diameter by pi and converting to meters. This is for the calculations for time and winner.  Luckily Google Calculator does this for you.\n\n \'\'\'Examples:\'\'\'\n 2.25 inch (diameter) rollers: [http://www.google.com/search?q=(pi+*+2.25+in)+in+m (pi * 2.25 in) in m] = \'\'\'0.17954202 meters\'\'\'\n 3.0 inch (diameter) rollers: [http://www.google.com/search?q=(pi+*+3.0+in)+in+m (pi * 3.0 in) in m] = \'\'\'0.23938936 meters\'\'\'\n 4.5 inch (diameter) rollers: [http://www.google.com/search?q=(pi+*+4.5+in)+in+m (pi * 4.5 in) in m] = \'\'\'0.35908404 meters\'\'\'\n\nIf your roller isnt so easily calculated. Lets say its 23CM circumference. You want to err on the short side. The race animation will quit once the distance is reached and stop counting ticks. if the ticks have not been reached, the time will not be accurate or not operate at all.\n\n\n\'\'\'How many times does the roller have to spin in order to finish the race?\'\'\'\n\nWe will refer to each full rotation a \'\'tick\'\'.  Race distance (in meters) divided by the roller circumference (in meters) will give you the total number of ticks required to finish a race.  Here are some examples using Google Calculator and the earlier numbers:\n\n200 meter race distance divided by the circumference of 2.25 inch (diameter) rollers:\n [http://www.google.com/search?q=200+m+%2F+0.17954202+m 200 m / 0.17954202 m] = \'\'\'1,113.94536 ticks\'\'\'\n200 meter race distance divided by the circumference of 3.0 inch (diameter) rollers:\n [http://www.google.com/search?q=200+m+%2F+0.23938936+m 200 m / 0.23938936 m] = \'\'\'835.45902 ticks\'\'\'\n200 meter race distance divided by the circumference of 4.5 inch (diameter) rollers:\n [http://www.google.com/search?q=200+m+%2F+0.35908404+m 200 m / 0.35908404 m] = \'\'\'556.97268 ticks\'\'\'\n\n\'\'\'Programming the Arduino with basic_message\'\'\'\n\nFinally!  Now open a terminal window and change directory to the folder.\n  cd ~/Desktop/opensprints/firmware/arduino/basic_msg\n\nopen the basic_msg.pde with your favorite text editor (vim, nano)\n\nRound off the answer to our, \'\'how many times does the roller have to spin in order to finish the race\'\' question, edit the following line:\n  int raceLengthTicks = 1400;\n\n\'\'\'NOTE:\'\'\' This can\'t be a float / decimal value, it has to be a whole number!\n\nAlthough the distance can be changed easily once shoes is running a race, the race will not end until the determined amount of ticks is reached. \n\nNow to compile and upload your firmware to the arduino:\n# Go to the firmware directory (ex: ~/Desktop/opensprints/firmware/arduino/basic_msg/)\n# Type the \'\'\'make clean\'\'\' command.\n# Type the \'\'\'make\'\'\' command.\n# Attach the Arduino to your computer.\n# Run the command \'\'\'make upload\'\'\'.\n# You are now ready to run OpenSprints!\n\n\'\'\'NOTE:\'\'\' If \'\'make\'\' fails, you may have made a typo while editing the basic_message.pde file or some of your dependencies may be missing.\n\n===advanced_message BETA===\n\n\'\'\'NOTE:\'\'\' This version is still in testing, proceed at your own risk.\n\nDoes not require the above editing of source code. Just compile and upload your firmware to the arduino. From the firmware directory, type the \"make\" command. If that fails some of your dependencies may be missing.\n\nIf that is successful, attach the arduino to your computer and run the command \"make upload\". If that is successful, you are ready to run opensprints.\n\n==  Verifying the hardware ==\n\nConnect all the hardware together: the sensors connected to the interface board with ethernet cables, the programmed Arduino mounted on the interface board, and the Arduino connected to the computer with a USB cable.\n\n=== Setup for testing under Linux ===\n# Run \'\'gtkterm\'\'\n# Configure the port (Configuration -> Port) and select the following values:\n#* Port: \'\'/dev/ttyUSB0\'\'\n#* Speed: \'\'115200\'\'\n#* Parity: \'\'none\'\'\n#* Bits: \'\'8\'\'\n#* Stopbits: \'\'1\'\'\n#* Flow Control: \'\'none\'\'\n#* End of line delay: \'\'0\'\'\n\n=== Setup for testing under Mac OS X ===\n\n=== Setup for testing under Windows ===\n\n* Install and run [http://www.chiark.greenend.org.uk/~sgtatham/putty/download.html PuTTY].\n* With the Arduino connect to the PC, go to Hardware Manager and determine which COM port the Arduino is connected to.\n* Configure the port:\n** Click on the \'\'Serial\'\' radio button.\n** \'\'COM?\'\', as determined in previous step.\n** As far as I remember, everything else should be default.\n\n=== Running a fake race ===\n\nOnce the chosen terminal is configured as per the previous step, you should see a cursor with nothing going on. Type the letter \'g\' on the keyboard. Nothing should happen for a few seconds (during the countdown - \"4, 3, 2, 1, 0, go!\"). Then you should see a stream of numbers and letters filling the screen.\n\nThis is an example of what you might see in the terminal at an instant:\n<pre>\n1: 0\n2: 0\n3: 0\n4: 0\nt: 15311\n</pre>\n\nTest the hardware by waving a magnet in front of the hall effect sensor. (Turn the magnet around until the \'\'tick\'\' LED flashes. That will be the correct orientation of the magnet.)\n\nEvery time you wave a magnet in front of the hall effect sensor you will see the number following the corresponding sensor increment. So if you caused a tick on sensor 2, the following report will look like this:\n<pre>\n1: 0\n2: 1\n3: 0\n4: 0\nt: 15562\n</pre>\n\nAt this point, if all the sensors are behaving as expected, it\'s time to install and start running the PC application. Check out the page on [[Software Installation|software installation]].\n\n== Finally! Execute the Opensprints GUI ==\n\n# Simply run shoes by double-clicking it on your desktop\n# Then click \"Open an app\"\n# Browse to ~/opensprints/main.rb\n\n== Common faults ==\n\n= Mac OS X =\n\n# Grab a copy of the latest code: http://github.com/evanfarrar/opensprints/zipball/master\n# Get the serproxy program from Arduino\'s website and extract it somewhere like the opensprints directory: http://download.berlios.de/arduino/serproxy-0.1.3-3.bin.macosx.zip\n# Install the Arduino Development suite and the USB Serial Drivers: http://arduino.cc/en/Guide/MacOSX\n# Edit the serproxy.cfg  included in opensprints\' main directory to use your arduino\'s address. There is a line that says \"serial_device1=/dev/ttyUSB0\". Change it to something like \"/dev/cu.usbserial-A9005fET\" (if you browse around in the finder you should be able to find the exact address).\n# run the serproxy program from a terminal: \"cd ~/Desktop/opensprints; ./serproxy serproxy.cfg\"\n# edit your conf.yml to use the sensor named \"network\"\n# Get the latest version of shoes and use it to open \"opensprints/main.rb\" : http://shoooes.net/dist/shoes2.dmg\n\n= Windows =\n\n# Grab a copy of the latest code: http://github.com/evanfarrar/opensprints/zipball/master\n# Get the serproxy program from the Arduino [http://www.arduino.cc/en/Main/Software website] and extract it somewhere like the opensprints directory.\n# Get the Arduino Development platform and USB serial drivers: http://arduino.cc/en/Guide/Windows\n# Get shoes: http://shoooes.net/','utf-8'),(549,'','utf-8');
